Though not strictly an industrial city itself, its municipal area includes some industrial zones. The 2003 estimated population was about 91,200.

label: Belluno
scope_note: City of pre-Roman origin; was a medieval free commune before joining Venice in 1404; taken by the French 1797; passed to Austria 1813 & to the Italian kingdom in 1866.

label: Bourges
scope_note: Bourges is located almost exactly in the center of France and lies on the Canal du Berry, at the convergence of the Yèvre and Auron rivers. It was one of the pilgrimage sites on route to the Cathedral of Santiago de Compostela. The  hill on which the city is built is crowned with the 12th-century Gothic cathedral of Saint-Étienne. The palace of Jacques Coeur, chief financier to Charles VII, is an exellent source of French 15th-century civil architecture. Bourges is the sheep, cattle, wine, and cereals marketing center for the region. In 52 BCE, Julius Caesar recognized the city as one of the most beautiful cities in Gaul. Saint Ursin brought Christianity to Bourges in the 3rd century.  During the Hundred Years' War, Charles VII resided there between the years of 1422 and 1437, and Joan of Arc wintered there between the years of 1429 and 1430. Louis XI,  was born in Bourges and endowed the city in 1463 with a university, which was abolished during the French Revolution.

label: Boston
scope_note: Located on Charles river; site of key pre-Revolutionary War events, Boston Massacre 1770 & Boston Tea Party 1773; expanded with textile mills, shipbuilding & trade 18th-19th cen.; noted for Faneuil Hall (1742-1805) & Paul Revere House (1680).
wikidata_description: capital and largest city of Massachusetts, United States

label: Cividale del Friuli
scope_note: Located 9 miles ENE of Udine; was residence of patriarchs of Aquileia from 730-1238; fell to Venice in 1420.
wikidata_description: chief town of the homonym municipality

label: Treviso
scope_note: A Celtic & Roman town; center of Lombard duchy; site of important mint during Charlemagne's time; independent from 1020; under the Ghibelline leader Ezzelino da Romano 1237-1259; passed to Venice 1339, to French 1790s, to Austria 1815, to Italy 1866.

label: Straubing
wikidata_description: independent city in Lower Bavaria, southern Germany

label: Knossós
scope_note: Was principal city of Crete throughout Antiquity; flourished ca. 2000-1400 BCE; was seat of legendary king Minos and labyrinth of Daedalus; best known for ruins of the great Minoan palace and Neolithic deposits.
wikidata_description: ancient Minoan through Roman administrative center and city

label: Jesi
scope_note: Located on Esino river; colonized by Romans; destroyed by Goths and Lombards; given to Church by Frankish king Pepin III in 756; supported Holy Roman emperors until Battle of Benevento (1266), when it passed to papacy; noted as birthplace of Frederick II.

label: Todi
scope_note: Located on hill above the Tevere valley. According to legend, founded by Hercules and called "Eclis"; in fact, was founded by the ancient Italic Umbri in the 8th-7th century BCE; was on the frontier between ancient Umbrians & Etruscans. Taken by Rome 340 BCE; was a member of a league of Umbrian Guelph towns in the Middle Ages.

label: Bruxelles
scope_note: The city of Brussels is the capital of modern Belgium. The original village grew up around a chapel on an island in the Zenne River. By the 6th century, it found itself located on an important trade route, and became a flourishing commercial center specializing in woolens in the medieval period. The merchant aristocracy was forced to share power with the craftsmen after their revolt in 1421. It was ruled successively by the Duke of Burgundy, then the Holy Roman Empire. It was part of the Spanish Netherlands from 1530, then of modern Belgium from 1830. In the 20th and early 21st centuries, it produced textiles, chemicals, electrical equipment, machinery, rubber goods and brewed beverages. It has become something of an international capital since it became the headquarters of the European Union.
wikidata_description: municipality and capital city of Belgium

label: Olimbía
scope_note: Ancient religious center in NW Peloponnesus; was scene of the Olympian Games to honor Zeus, first held in 8th cen. BCE; date of these games, held every 4 years, marked units in Greek calendar (Olympiads); had many temples & works by Phidias & Praxiteles. here is evidence of settlement in the area of Olympia from the Early Bronze Age on, and although there is no archaeological proof for prehistoric cult activity at Olympia, tradition records that it was originally a place sacred to Ge, Cronus (the Mother of Gods), and Eileithyia as well as a cult center of the hero Pelops. At some time after the end of the Late Bronze Age the cult of Zeus was introduced and a walled sacred precinct was established.

label: Cleveland
scope_note: Located on Lake Erie at mouth of Cuyahoga River; city was laid out by surveyors from Connecticut; developed after New York State opened Erie Canal in 1825, when Ohio constructed canal to join the lake and Ohio River; industry grew after Civil War.
wikidata_description: city in and county seat of Cuyahoga County, Ohio, United States

label: Narbonne
scope_note: Said to be first Roman colony beyond the Alps, founded in 118 BCE; taken by Visigoths in 412, by Saracens in 719 and by Pepin the Short in 759; flourished as manufacturing city 11th-12th centuries; boulevards replaced medieval fortifications by 1870; site of 11th- and 14th-century church.

label: Melbourne
scope_note: World's most southerly urban area greater than 1 million population; Australia's largest cargo port; founded by Tasmanian settlers; center of gold rush 1850s; site of Summer Olympic Games 1956.

label: Nîmes
scope_note: Situated at the foot of barren hills, the Monts Garrigues, in a plain of vinyards. It was the capital of a Gaulish tribe; taken by Rome in 121 BCE, it became a chief city of Roman Gaul. It was plundered by Vandals and Visigoths in the 5th century. It was occupied by Saracens until 737, and then was under the counts of Toulouse in the 10th century. It  joined the French crown territories in 1229. It was a Protestant stronghold in the 16th century; it was the scene of an uprising in 1815. It is noted for well-preserved Roman buildings and artifacts.
wikidata_description: city and prefecture of the Gard department in the Occitanie region of Southern France

label: Arles
scope_note: Arles was one of the pilgrimage sites on route to the Cathedral of Santiago de Compostela. French pilgrimage routes to Compostela tend to follow old Roman roads, many of which continued to be utilized as primary roads of communication during the Middle Ages. Arles was a leading city of the west Roman Empire. It fell under Visigoth control during the 6th century and then under Muslims rule in 730. It has a Roman arena dating to the 1st century BCE, which is presently used for bullfights and plays. It also has many Roman ruins. Arles was home to Vincent van Gogh during a productive period of his career.

label: Szczecin
scope_note: Founded as Slav fishing village; became a powerful fortified town from 10th-11th cen.; peace treaty between Denmark and Sweden signed here in 1570; modern development began in 1826 with navigation of Oder River; cultural center of W part of nation.
wikidata_description: capital city of the West Pomeranian Voivodeship, Poland

label: Rottweil
wikidata_description: town in the district of Rottweil, Baden-Württemberg, Germany

label: Neumünster
scope_note: Located SSW of Kiel; is important railroad junction & manufacturing city, producing machinery & paper.
wikidata_description: church building in Neumünster, Schleswig-Holstein, Germany

label: Tours
scope_note: Tours is the capital of the Indre-et-Loire département, on the Loire River. It is the chief tourist centre for the Loire Valley and its historic châteaus. Tours offers sharp contrasts in buildings and architectural styles. Located in Tours is the cathedral of Saint-Gatien which sums up four centuries of French religious architecture: the choir is of the 13th century; the nave marks a transition between Flamboyant Gothic and Renaissance styles; the facade was built between 1426 to 1547. Tours was one of the pilgrimage sites on route to the Cathedral of Santiago de Compostela, home of the shrine dedicated to Saint James, the patron saint of Spain. The symbol of Saint James, the scalloped shell, became the primary symbol representing pilgrims. French pilgrimage routes to Compostela tend to follow old Roman roads, many of which continued to be utilized as primary roads of communication during the Middle Ages. Tours was a medieval center of learning and scene of the victory of Charles Martel over the Saracens in 732. Tours developed a prosperous silk industry in the 15th century. Its Musée des Beaux-Arts in the former 17th- to 18th-century archiepiscopal palace has an excellent collection of paintings. Tours entered the 1980s with strength due to its decentralization from the Paris region of machinery assembly, chemical products, and pharmaceutical industries. This was the birthplace of Balzac.
wikidata_description: city and commune in Indre-et-Loire, Centre-Val de Loire, France

label: Moissac
scope_note: Moissac was one of the pilgrimage sites on route to the Cathedral of Santiago de Compostela, home of the shrine dedicated to Saint James, the patron saint of Spain. French pilgrimage routes to Compostela tend to follow old Roman roads, many of which continued to be utilized as primary roads of communication during the Middle Ages. This location is situated on what once was a strategic point of the main land and water routes in the mid-Garonne region connecting Toulouse to Bordeaux. Moissac is the site of the Benedictine abbey of Saint-Pierre-de-Moissac, which was consecrated in 1180 and the former parish church of Saint Martin.

label: Catania
scope_note: Located at foot of Mount Etna; founded by Greeks in 8th cen. BCE; Athenian base of operations against Syracuse 432 BC; taken by Romans in First Punic War 263 BCE, by Saracens 902 CE & Normans ca. 1090; was often damaged by earthquakes & volcanic eruptions.

label: Königswinter
wikidata_description: town in the Rhein-Sieg district, in North Rhine-Westphalia, Germany

label: Flensburg
scope_note: Located at head of Flensburg fjord, is northernmost large German city; was prominent port by 16th cen.; often pillaged by Swedes; ruled by Denmark, then by Prussia after war of 1864; in plebiscite of 1920 voted to remain German; heavily bombed in WW II.

label: Monaco-Ville
scope_note: Most ancient part of the principality; located on a rocky promontory on S side of port; site of 13th-cen. Palais du Prince.

label: Maastricht
scope_note: Located along the Maas (Meuse) River at the junction of several canals. It was settled by the Romans and was the seat of a bishop from 382-721. It was held by the dukes of Brabant in 1204, then was under the joint sovereignty of Brabant and prince-bishops of Liège (1284). From the 13th to the15th century, it flourished due to the expanding cloth industry. It is noted for its cathedral, founded in the 6th century.

label: Elbla̜g
scope_note: Located at mouth of Vistula River; revolted against Teutonic Knights & became part of Poland in 1450; chief port of E Prussia in trade with England; ceded to Prussia - 1772; destroyed during World War II & since rebuilt; main industry is metal processing.

label: Akdamar Adası
scope_note: Small island in Van Gölü; contains a well-preserved medieval church & ruined monastic structures.

label: Williamstown
scope_note: Located on Hoosic River; noted as site of Williams College, founded in 18th cen.; also is site of earliest observatory in the nation, founded in 1838.

label: Richmond
scope_note: Sight of uprising during reign of Elizabeth I (1558-1603).

label: Pforzheim
scope_note: Pforzheim is a city located in southwestern Germany on the northern edge of the Black Forest where the Nagold and Würm Rivers join the Enz on the French border. Originally a Roman settlement, it became a German town, chartered in 1195, and an important medieval center, famous for the production of jewelry and watches. It was sacked in the Thirty Years' War and again in the War of Grand Alliance in the 17th century. It was almost totally destroyed in World War II, but has been rebuilt and restored. Its 2004 estimated population was 119,500.

label: Berchtesgaden
scope_note: The town of Berchtesgaden in located  in Bavaria in southern Germany on the Berchtesgden Stream in a deep valley surrounded on three sides by Austrian territory. Salt mines opened here in the 12th century, sparking a long rivalry over the trade with nearby Salzburg. The town was ruled by the provosts of the Augustinian abbey from 1300. Austria occupied it in 1704 and annexed it in 1805. After 1810, after a brief period of French rule, it was ceded to the kingdom of Bavaria. Some medieval architecture remains, notably the abbey church and the castle occupied first by the provost-rulers then by the kings of Bavaria in the warm summer months. In the 1930s and 1940s, Adolf Hitler and other Nazi leaders had chalets on the Obersalzberg overlooking the town. Hitler's chalet was bombed in World War II and in the 1950s was leveled and had trees planted over it. The local economy depends primarily on tourism, and the salt mines still function.

label: Noraduz
wikidata_description: village in Gegharkunik Province of Armenia

label: Sansepolcro
scope_note: Oratory was founded on the site in 10th cen.; was an important medieval & Renaissance center; noted as birthplace of painters Piero della Francesca (died 1492) & Matteo di Giovanni & as home of the Alberti family of architects & sculptors.

label: Coimbra
scope_note: Located in north central Portugal; under control of Moors until retaken by Alfonso III of Asturias and Leon in 878; fell to Ferdinand I of Castile 1064; birthplace of six medieval kings; noted for polyphonic music in early 1500s; publishing house was established 1800s.

label: Afāmiyā
scope_note: Ancient site located near modern Qal‘at el Madhiq. Was one of 4 great cities founded in N Syria by Seleucus I Nicator (301-281 BCE); a citadel of the Seleucid kings; was the capital of Apamene. The fortress was destroyed by Pompey in 1st cen. CE, when the city was re-established under the name Claudia Apamea; destroyed in Moslem conquest 7th cen.

label: Ferentillo
wikidata_description: town in the region Umbria, in Italy

label: Luzern
scope_note: Located on the W shore of Lake Lucerne, 25 m. SSW of Zurich. Former fishing village that evolved near an 8th century Benedictine monastery of St. Leodegar (Luciaria). Chartered as a city in 1180 and developed into important trade center after the St. Gotthard Pass opened route between the upper Rhine and Lombardy ca. 1230. Purchased by the Hapsburgs in 1291. Capital of the Helvetic Republic from 1798 to 1803. Site of a summer music festival since 1938.
wikidata_description: city at Lake Lucerne, in central Switzerland

label: Friedrichshafen
scope_note: The town of Friedrichshafen is located on north shore of Lake Constance in the state of Baden-Württemberg in southwestern Germany. The site was settled by at least the 9th century and came to be known as Buchhorn. Close by was the monastery of Hofen, dating from the 11th century. Friedrich I of Württemburg united the town and the then-suppressed monastery in the 19th century and created the new town of Friedrichshafen. A Zeppelin factory was established here, which may have been the main reason for the town being bombed in World War II. The 2004 estimated population was 58,000.

city: San Casciano in Val di Pesa
label: San Casciano in Val di Pesa
Langres
scope_note: The stronghold of the Lingones (a Gallic tribe), later an important Gallo-Roman & medieval fortified town; birthplace of philosopher Denis Diderot (b. 1713).

label: Aquileia
scope_note: Established for military purposes after Roman power extended to Po valley; sacked by Huns 452 & Lombards 568; a feudal principality until Venetian conquest of Friuli; declined after passing to Venice 1420; ruled by Austria 1509-1918, then passed to Italy; archaeological site named UNESCO World Heritage Site in 1998.

label: Radolfzell
wikidata_description: town in Konstanz district, Baden-Württemberg, Germany

label: Sontra
wikidata_description: town in Werra-Meißner-Kreis in Hesse, Germany

label: Fribourg
scope_note: Settled by Helvetii in ancient times and conquered by the Franks in 6th century CE. Modern town was founded by Berthold IV of Zähringen to protect a river ford in the 12th century. Ruled by various houses, including the Hapsburgs from 1277 to 1452. Center of Swiss Catholicism.
wikidata_description: capital of the canton of Fribourg in Switzerland

label: Marseille
scope_note: Oldest of France's major cities; taken by Caesar 49 BCE; deteriorated after decline of Roman Empire until the 11th century; part of kingdom of Arles 879, of Provence 10th century; gained independence in the 13th century; passed to France in 1481; important during the 19th century.
wikidata_description: French commune in Bouches-du-Rhône, Provence-Alpes-Côte d'Azur; the second largest city of France

label: Ioánnina
scope_note: Located on plateau under Oóros Mitsikéli (mountain), on a lake; was inhabited by prehistoric people; founded by Justinian in 6th century. flourished in 11th century. haven for refugees from Latin capture of Byzantine empire in Constantinople in 13th century.

label: Edinburgh
scope_note: Located on S shore of Firth of Forth; inhabited by Romans in 2nd century and Lothians in 6th century; divided into 12th-century Old Town and 18th-century New Town; became major textile and industrial center in 18th century; noted for Georgian architecture.

label: Glasgow
scope_note: Country's largest city & site of early Industrial Revolution in 18th cen.; religious center founded by St. Kentigern in 550; American Revolution disrupted trade until shipbuilding & textile industries began; notorious slums disappeared during 1980s.

label: Pavia
scope_note: Key defense point of upper Italy in Roman times; sacked by Attila 452; Charlemagne crowned King of Lombardy 774 and Frederick Barbarossa as King of Italy 1155; ruled by Visconti 1359 and Austrians, French & Spaniards 18th cen. until passed to nation 1859.

label: Nardò
scope_note: Located SW of Lecce city; originally Roman city of Naretum, it was both Byzantine & Norman; site of a 13th/14th-cen. Gothic cathedral & a circular chapel called the Osanna (1603); economy based on wheat, olive oil & tobacco.

label: Segovia
scope_note: Segovia was an Iberian settlement since ca. 700 BCE, falling to Roman control ca. 80 BCE. Segovia underwent Moorish occupation from early 8th century until its recapture by Alfonso VI in 1079. During the late 16th century the plague led to the city's decline, but revived during the age of railroad construction in the 19th century. An important historical site is the Roman-built Segovia aqueduct, well known as "El Puente." Other distinguished buildings include the Church of San Esteban, San Martín, La Trinidad, San Lorenzo, San Millán and the Alcázar, a palace for the royal family of Castile.

label: Bayeux
scope_note: First town to be liberated by Allied Forces in World War II.

label: Reggio nell'Emilia
scope_note: Located on Crostolo river; was founded by Romans on the Via Aemilia; was member of Lombard League in 12th cen.; later ruled by bishops; ruled by counts of Canossa from 10th cen.; independent in 12th cen.; held by Este family of Modena 1409-1796.

label: Montréal
scope_note: Canada's second largest city; occupies about a third of Île de Montréal. The first French settlement here was Fort Ville Marie (1642-1674), with foundations under the site of the current PAC Musée. It was given its first civic charter by Louis XIV in 1644; it peacefully surrendered to British troops in 1760; it was brought under British N American empire 1763.

label: Stadtallendorf
wikidata_description: town in Landkreis Marburg-Biedenkopf in Hesse, Germany

label: Haarlem
scope_note: Located along the Spaarne river, by the 12th century it had become a fortified town, the residence of the counts of Holland, and a market center for the Kennermerland. Besieged by the Spaniards for seven months before surrendering during the War of Independence in 1573. Experienced an economic upswing during the 17th century and the first Amsterdam-Haarlem railway line opened in 1839. Composers Wolfgang Amedeus Mozart, George Frederick Handel, and others performed at the world-famous St. Bavo's church. Center of Dutch painting in the16th and 17th centuries and tulip country.
wikidata_description: municipality in the Netherlands and capital city of North Holland

label: San Lorenzo de El Escorial
scope_note: Noted for elaborate monastery, palace, mausoleum and museum; Philip II built monastery 1563-1584 as memorial to victory over French in 1557; became his main residence; later was the dynastic center of the Spanish Hapsburgs.

label: Oldenburg
scope_note: The city of Oldenburg is located at the junction of the Hunte River and the Küstenkanal in the Weser-Ems district of the northwestern German state of Lower Saxony. First mentioned in 1108, it was chartered in 1345, it was an important medieval center, the seat of the powerful counts and dukes of Oldenburg. Destroyed by fire in 1615, it was neutral in the Thirty Years' War. In the first half of the 20th century it was the capitol of the now-defunct state of Oldenburg. Surviving historic architecture includes the Lambert Church, built in 1270 and rebuilt in 1794, and the ducal palace, built 1607-15. The city has a university, a state theater, and many art galleries. The major economic activities include textile manufacturing, shipbuilding and shipping, agricultural marketing, meat processing, and glassmaking. The 2004 estimated population was 158,600.

label: Leeds
scope_note: The village is first mentioned in the Domesday Survey of 1086 where it is called Esledes. Leeds village stands on the slope above the valley of the river Len, adjacent to Leeds Castle. It is noted for the church here, which has a massive 11th-century tower.

label: Einsiedeln
scope_note: Located on Alp Stream; developed around Benedictine abbey; principality of Holy Roman Empire from 1274; ruled by Schwyz from 1386; was pilgrimage center for "Black Virgin" statue; home of 15th-cen. religious reformer Ulrich Zwingli & physician Paracelsus.

label: Pamplona
scope_note: Pamplona was one of the pilgrimage sites on route to the Cathedral of Santiago de Compostela, home of the shrine dedicated to Saint James, the patron saint of Spain. The symbol of Saint James, the scalloped shell, became the primary symbol representing pilgrims. Various pilgrimage routes in the autonomous communities of Aragon, Navarre, and León correspond to old Roman roads built in the northern portion of the Iberian Peninsula.  It became the strongest fortified town of northern Spain after Philip II of Spain constructed the citadel of 1571. Pamplona is famous for the running of the bulls in the city streets during the Fiesta de San Fermín. Pamplona is located in an irrigated region that produces cereal and manufactures chemicals, liquor, and paper. Historic sites in Pamplona include the Catheral of Santa María, the Church of San Cernín, the parish Church of San Nicolás, and Hospital of San Miguel.

label: Cambridge
scope_note: Located on the rivers Cam and Granta; site of prehistoric and Roman remains; oldest college is Peterhouse (founded 1284); was confirmed a university city by Pope John XXII in 1384; visited by Erasmus in 1510; site of Holy Sepulchre Church, famed for its circular plan; the Fitzwilliam Museum is here.

label: Matera
scope_note: Was important in Neolithic period, producing pottery during Middle Neolithic that has given the name "Matera ware" to a widespread style; was thriving medieval center, held by Normans, Aragonese & then by Orsini family of Rome.

label: Oslo
scope_note: Founded by King Harald Hardraade in the 11th century. The city was destroyed by fire in 1624; it was rebuilt at the nearby Akershus fortress, which had been built ca. 1300. The city grew during the 19th century and after World War II; it has absorbed several neighboring towns.

label: Garmisch-Partenkirchen
scope_note: Garmisch-Partenkirchen  is located at the junction of the Loisach and Partnach Valleys in the Bavarian Alps in southern Germany at the foot of the Zugspitze, the highest peak in Germany. The town is the unification of two old villages, Garmisch and Partenkirchen, and was only chartered in 1935. It was the site of the Winter Olympics in 1936. It was planned to be a last retreat for Nazi leaders, but was taken by the Allies in April, 1945. Its historic architecture includes the Old Church of St. Martin, built in medieval times, the Baroque New Church of St, Martin, and the 18th-century Pilgrimage Church. The 2004 estimated population was 26,700.

label: Auxerre
scope_note: Important Roman city & center of learning; became a bishopric during the 3rd cen. CE; was capital of county of Auxerrois, which passed to Burgundy by the treaty of Arras in 1435.

label: Pavia
scope_note: Key defense point of upper Italy in Roman times; sacked by Attila 452; Charlemagne crowned King of Lombardy 774 and Frederick Barbarossa as King of Italy 1155; ruled by Visconti 1359 and Austrians, French & Spaniards 18th cen. until passed to nation 1859.

label: Kraków
scope_note: A cultural and artistic center since 14th century, Kraków was destroyed by Swedish wars in the 17th century, and later occupied by Austria from 1795-1918. It suffered Nazi attacks during World War II, and was also the location of a Nazi concentration camp, known as the Plaszow camp, in operation as a forced-labor camp from 1942-1944, and then a full concentration camp from 1944-1945. The camp held up to 20,000 people, and many thousands were killed by the SS during the camp's existence. Industry in Kraków revived after the war. The city is known for its rich architectural history, museums, and theaters.
wikidata_description: capital city of Lesser Poland Voivodeship in southern Poland

label: Milet Harabeleri
scope_note: Located near the mouth of the Menderes; was one of 12 Ionian cities and one of the greatest cities of ancient Asia Minor; was large trade center with 4 harbors; founded colonies on Black Sea, in Egypt and Italy; noted as a literary center.

label: Koblenz
scope_note: The western German city of Koblenz is located in a wooded area at the junction of the Rhine and Moselle rivers some 50 miles south-southeast of Cologne. It began as a Roman settlement established in 9 BCE by the general Drusus. In the sixth century it became the seat of the Frankish kings. The archbishops of Trier ruled it from 1018. It received its town charter in 1214. It was occupied by the French in 1794 and settled by a major movement of emigrés. Prussia took it over in1815, and it became the capital of the Prussian Rhine province until 1945. It was occupied by the Americans from 1919 to 1923, and by the French from 1923 to 1929. It was badly damaged in World War II, but has retained much of its historic architecture, including a ninth-century church rebuilt around 1200, several 13th-century churches and fortifications, the Baldwin Bridge across the Moselle, built in 1343, and the house where the Austrian statesman  Prince Metternich was born in 1773. Post-war planning and construction have made the modern city specious and attractive, and an important center for tourism and conferences. Its port is one of the major petroleum ports on the mid-Rhine. Manufacturing includes furniture, chemicals, and clothing. Its population for 2005 was calculated to be 108,146.

label: Trogir
scope_note: Located on island of Ciovo in Adriatic Sea. The city connects to the mainland by bridge. It was once ruled by Venice, Hungary, Byzantium, and later Italy. In 1918, it became a part of Yugoslavia in 1918, and later independent Croatia. The city was designated a World Heritage Site by UNESCO in 1997.

label: Córdoba
scope_note: Conquered by Romans 206 BCE; declined under rule of Visigoths 572-711; taken and almost completely ruined by Muslims 711; prospered as artistic and intellectual center in Middle Ages; annexed to Sevilla 1078; under control of Ferdinand III of Castile 1236.
wikidata_description: municipality in the province of Córdoba, Spain

label: Alsfeld
wikidata_description: town in Vogelsbergkreis in Hesse, Germany

label: Châlons-sur-Champagne
scope_note: Chief town of ancient Catalauni, Gallic tribe; fortified by Romans; site of defeat of Attila by Romans & Visigoths 451 which stopped advance of Huns in Europe; prosperous in 10th cen.; united to France 1360; taken by Germans 1870; occupied by Nazis 1940s.

label: Préveza
scope_note: Located on the Ambracian gulf in western Greece; was founded by Pyrrhus of Epirus in 290 BCE; noted for nearby strait where Octavius Augustus defeated Mark Antony in 31 BCE; held by Venice from 1499, then by Turks.

label: Zürich
scope_note: Located of the lake of Zurich, 60 m. NE of Bern. First inhabited in the Neolithic period by lake dwellers, it was later occupied by the Gallic Helvetii, the Romans in 58 CE, the Alemanni and the Franks, and to the German Stem duchy of Swabia.  In the 16th century, under the influence of Ulrich Zwiingli, it became the leading power of the Swiss Reformation, starting a civil war, which ended by a Roman Catholic victory at Kappel in 1531. Notable buildings include the Romanesque Grossmünster of the 11th and 13th centuries and the Fraumünster of the 12th and 15th centuries. James Joyce is buried here
wikidata_description: capital of the canton of Zurich, Switzerland

label: Palencia
scope_note: Main town of Iberian tribe Vaccaei; seat for the kings of Castile and their courts in the 12th-13th centuries; Gothic cathedral (constructed between 1321-1504) houses El Greco's "St. Sebastian," noted Flemish tapestries, woodwork, and stonework.

label: Erlangen
scope_note: Erlangen is a city in Bavaria in the south of Germany, situated north of Nürnberg at the confluence of the Schwabach and Regnitz Rivers. The site was settled in the eighth century, and ruled first by the Bishop of Würzberg, then by the Bishop of Bamberg from 1017. It was sold to the prince of Bohemia in1361, received its town charter in 1398, then came under the rule of Nürnberg in 1402. It prospered with the arrival of French Huguenot refugees who settled in "Christian Erlang" in 1686. It passed to Bavaria in 1810. Historic buildings include the palace, built 1700-1704, and the town hall dating from 1731. The city still produces hats, drapery, and gloves, crafts introduced by the Huguenot settler. The production of electrical equipment is the major modern industry. It is also the home of the Friedrich-Alexander Univeristy of Erlangen-Nürnberg. The 2004 estimated population was 99,800.

label: Schwerin
scope_note: The city of Schwerin is situated on a lake, the Schweriner See, southwest of Rostock in the northeast German state of Mecklenburg-Vorpommern, of which it serves as the capitol.  Originally a Wendish settlement, the German town was founded by the Saxon duke Henry the Lion in the 12th century. It went to Mecklenburg in 1358. Its inhabitants accepted the Reformation in 1524. From 1624 to 1631 imperial troops occupied it during the Thirty Years' War. T prospered and gained importance over the centuries, often serving as the capitol of Mecklenburg-Schwerin. From 1952 to 1990 it was the capitol of the DDR district of Schwerin.  It has retained some of its historic architecture, notably the Gothic cathedral, begun in 1270 and only completed in 1890. There are also the dukes' palace, 1843-57, and the palace church built in 1560-63. Local industries include food processing, pharmaceuticals, plastics, wood products, and cigarettes. The 2004 estimated population was 97,700.

label: Baghdād
scope_note: The city was sacked by Muslim Arabs 634 CE. It rose to importance as a religious, trade, and cultural center on the Silk Road in the 8th century. It was nearly destroyed by Mongols in 1258, and conquered by Tamerlane in 1401. It was taken by Suleiman the Magnificent in 1534, became part of the Ottoman Empire 1638. Later, it was taken by the British in 1917.

label: Dubrovnik
scope_note: Located on the southern Dalmatian coast, the city was ruled by Byzantium after the fall of Rome. It was an independent trade city nominally under the rule of Venice, Turkey, and Hungary from 1205 to 1808. In 1808, the city was taken by Napoleon, later to be given to Austria in 1814. Eventually, it became part of Yugoslavia, then independent Croatia. The Old City of Dubrovnik was designated a World Heritage Site by UNESCO in 1979.
wikidata_description: city and settlement in Dubrovnik-Neretva County, Croatia

label: Kremsmünster
scope_note: Site of important Benedictine abbey founded in 777.
wikidata_description: municipality in Kirchdorf District, Upper Austria, Austria

label: Rimini
scope_note: On Adriatic Sea at mouth of Marecchia river; recorded by Greek historian Strabo in 1st cen. BCE; became great Roman center, but sacked by Sulla; passed to Byzantines, Goths, Lombards and Franks; held by Malatesta family from 13th cen., by pope from 1509.

label: Reutlingen
scope_note: The city of Reutlingen is situated on the Echaz River in the Swabian Alps south of Stuttgart in the state of Baden-Württemberg in southwestern Germany. Founded by Frederick II in the 13th century, it was an important medieval fortified center. It was the first city in Swabia to join the Protestant Reformation in the 16th century. It became part of Württemberg in 1802. It is noted for its medieval architecture, including many high-gabled, half-timbered houses, and some Gothic structures, such as the Marienkirche begun in 1247. The modern city's major economic activities are leather tanning and textile manufacture. The 2004 estimated population was 112,200.

label: Lindau
scope_note: Located partly on an island in the Bodensee; is a resort and trade center for agricultural and dairy products.
wikidata_description: city at Lake Constance in Bavaria, Germany

label: Bergamo
scope_note: Located in southern foothills of the Alps; sacked by Attila the Hun in the 5th century; rebuilt and became seat of Lombard duchy 1296; passed to Venice 1428-1797, to Austria in 1815, and  part of Italian kingdom 1859; site of Romanesque Cathedral begun in 1137 and Cappella Colleoni (1470-1476). The city today (population ca. 125,000) is divided into two parts: upper Bergamo (città alta) and lower Bergamo (città bassa), the modern city; the upper part crowns a steep hill and retains its circuit of 16th-century walls.

label: Chiusi
scope_note: Was one of the 12 original cities of Etruria; flourished 7th-6th centuries BCE; noted as site from which Lars Porsena marched against Rome ca. 500 BCE; was subject to Rome from 295 BCE; declined in Middle Ages due to proximity to swamps of Chiani river.

label: Kaufungen
wikidata_description: municipality in Landkreis Kassel in Hesse, Germany

label: Metz
scope_note: Fortified by Romans; sacked by Attila 5th cen.; prospered as free imperial city 13th cen.; taken by French along with Tour & Verdun 1552; surrendered to Germans in 1870 & was under German rule 1871-1918; reverted to France after World War I.

label: Wrocław
scope_note: Originated on trade route between Roman Empire & Baltic Sea; home of many German immigrants since 13th cen.; passed to Bohemia in 1526 & to Prussia in 1741; damaged by Russian & Nazi sieges of 1945; was rebuilt & industrialized in 1950s-1960s.
wikidata_description: city in the Lower Silesian Voivodeship, southwestern Poland, and historical capital of Silesia

label: Stockholm
scope_note: Built upon numerous islands as well as on the mainland, primarily by the Swedish ruler Birger Jarl in 13th cen.; rapidly developed as member of Hanseatic League; extensively rebuilt in 1634; destroyed by fires & rebuilt in 18th cen., expanded in 19th cen.
wikidata_description: capital and largest city of Sweden

label: Tarragona
scope_note: Tarragona, capital city of Tarragona province, is situated at the mouth of the Francolí River. Former seat of Iberian tribe, it was taken by Roman generals Gnaeus and Publius Scipio in 218 BCE. According to custom, Tarragona is the site where St. Paul established the Christian church in Spain in 60 CE. In 714, Tarragona was destroyed by Moors and then retaken by Christians in the 12th century, where it became part of the kingdom of Aragón. It is an active seaport and an important agricultural market.

label: Le Puy
scope_note: Le Puy was one of the pilgrimage sites on route to the Cathedral of Santiago de Compostela, home of the shrine dedicated to Saint James, the patron saint of Spain. The symbol of Saint James, the scalloped shell, became the primary symbol representing pilgrims. French pilgrimage routes to Compostela tend to follow old Roman roads, many of which continued to be utilized as primary roads of communication during the Middle Ages. Le Puy is a site of unknown antiquity, although estimated to have gone through a period of Roman habitation. Pilgrimages from Le Puy to Compostela began as early as the 6th century. This city became the starting location for one of the four main pilgrimage routes, specifically for German and Teutonic pilgrims. Le Puy is a manufacturing city, located in south-central France in the mountainous volcanic region. It is the site of the 12th-century Romanesque Cathedral of Notre-Dame as well as a Gothic church.

label: Montecatini Terme
scope_note: Located on thermal mineral springs & baths; famous as site of defeat of Florence by Uguccione della Faggiuola of Pisa in 1315, in wars between Black & White factions of Guelphs; mineral baths were constructed in 14th cen. & town became a spa center.

label: Hohenschwangau
scope_note: The castle of Hohenschwangau was built in the 12th century. Located near the village of Schwangau; it passed from the Welfs to the dukes of Bavaria in 1567. it was destroyed by Napoleon and restored by Crown Prince Maximilian in 1832-1837 in Romanesque style. Ludwig II spent his early years here. The interior is in troubadour style, with wall paintings of Bavarian knights and folk heroes. Today it is a busy tourist attraction.

label: Gera
scope_note: Located on Weisse Elster river, SW of Leipzig; was important medieval center; ruled by Meissen from 1547, by Reuss family from 1547; destroyed by fire 1639, 1686 and 1780; heavily damaged in WW II; today produces textiles, metal products, oils and furniture.

label: Herculaneum
scope_note: Located at foot of Mount Vesuvius; was a thriving resort during Roman times; destroyed, with Pompeii in 79 CE when Vesuvius erupted, as Herculaneum was still being rebuilt after an earthquake several years earlier. The ruins offer the best known evidence of ancient Roman private life; one of three sites grouped together in an UNESCO World Heritage Site in 1997 and noted for their well-preserved remains due to ash covering. The modern town of Ercolano is in part built on the ancient ruins of Herculaneum, but most of the ancient site, and the officially designated historical monument, lies south of the town center.

label: Namur
scope_note: The city is the capital of the province of Namur, situated at the confluence of the Sambre and Meuse Rivers. It was a fortified town in pre-Roman times, and became the seat of the counts of Namur from 908; their citadel on a rocky outcrop between the two rivers was refortified several times over the centuries and not abandoned for good until 1862. It passed to Burgundy in 1421, and to the new nation of Belgium with the rest of the Burgundian Netherlands in 1830. Its strategic location on the various routes into France meant that the city was often the scene of conflict in the 17th and from the 19th to the 20th centuries. It underwent considerable damage during both World Wars. Despite this, many historic structures remain, such as the Baroque cathedral of St. Aubain, the Jesuit church of St. Loup, the convent of the Sisters of Our Lady, containing 13th-century treasures of silver and gold craftsmanship; and the Meat Hall, built in 1588, which houses the archaeological museum. Its industries include tourism, glass, paper, leather goods, steel products, and cement. Its 2003 estimated population was 105,700.

label: Biberach an der Riß
wikidata_description: town and district capital in the Upper Swabia region of the German state of Baden-Württemberg

label: Grado
scope_note: Located on a small island between the Laguna di Grado & the Adriatic; renowned commercial port during Roman period; seat of the patriarchate of Nova Aquileia ca. 570-1451, when title was given to Venice; site of 6th cen. cathedral.

label: Brescia
scope_note: In Alpine foothills; sacked by Attila the Hun 452; taken by rival Italian families 10th-14th cen.; wealthy in 16th cen. until sacked by French 1516; taken by Napoleon 1796; passed to Austria 1815, Sardinia 1859 & to nation 1860; site of many Roman ruins.

label: Gallipoli
scope_note: Was considered by ancients to be of Greek origin; by tradition, was founded by the Lakedaimonian Leukippos, for whom it was an important port; according to Pliny, it was called Anxa under the Messapians; taken from Byzantines by Normans in 1071.

label: Otranto
scope_note: Nation's easternmost town; retained Greek language until 11th cen.; was important trade center with Orient until razed by Turks in 1480; supply base during WW II; scene of Horace Walpole's novel The Castle of Otranto; connected by hydrofoil to Corfu.

label: Sion
scope_note: Located on the Rhône River; became an episcopal see in 580; King Rudolf III of Burgundy made the bishop a count of the Valais in 999; site of the pilgrimage church of St. Catherine.

label: Coburg
scope_note: The town of Coburg is located on the Itz River in northern Bavaria, Germany in the foothills of the Thuringian Forest. It was a noted medieval center. It passed to the house of Wettin in 1353. It was a strategically important fortified town from the 15th century, withstanding several sieges during the Thirty Years War of 1618-1648. With the town of Gotha, it alternated as the capital of Saxe-Coburg-Gotha from 1826 to 1918. The castle of the dukes of Saxe-Coburg-Gotha Coburg was renovated in the early 20th century and houses fine art collections. That ducal family line has produced several European monarchs, including that of the United Kingdom. Their residence, converted from a suppressed monastery in 1543, now houses a fine library and several art collections. Local industries include lumber and paper milling, breweries, and the manufacture of textiles, glass, and toys. The 2004 estimated population was 42,600.

label: Estella
scope_note: Estella was one of the pilgrimage sites on route to the Cathedral of Santiago de Compostela, home of the shrine dedicated to Saint James, the patron saint of Spain. The symbol of Saint James, the scalloped shell, became the primary symbol representing pilgrims. Various pilgrimage routes in the autonomous communities of Aragon, Navarre, and León correspond to old Roman roads built in the northern portion of the Iberian Peninsula. In 1090, King Sancho of Spain founded this town exclusively for settlers of French origin and for pilgrimage crossing. Historic sites in Estella include the churches of San Miguel, San Juan Bautista, Nuestra Señora del Puy, San Salvador del Arenal, Santa María del Castillo, San Nicolás, and Nuestra Señora de Rocamadour. There are also the parish churches of San Pedro de Lizarra, Santo Sepulcro, and San Pedro de la Rúa. The Chapel of San Martin, the Palacio Real, the Puente de la Cárcel, and the Puente de San Martin are also here.

label: Kansas City
scope_note: Located in NE Kansas at junction of Kansas & Missouri rivers, adjoining Kansas City, Missouri; formation of rival pro- & anti-slavery towns in close proximity after Kansas-Nebraska Act (1854) brought rapid development; heavy flooding in 1903, 1951 & 1977.
wikidata_description: city and county seat of Wyandotte County, State of Kansas, United States

label: Besançon
scope_note: Taken by Julius Caesar in 58 BCE; Roman ruins here include an arch of Marcus Aurelius, aqueduct, and amphitheater. It became a free imperial city  in 1184; French since 1674. Besançon was fortified by the engineer Vauban in the 17th century. It is a center for the watch and clock industries.

label: Piacenza
scope_note: Founded by the Romans in 218 BCE, it was destroyed by the Gauls 200 BC & later rebuilt; became part of the Lombard League in the 12th cen.; under the control of the Visconti & Sforza families from 1337 to 1512.

label: Monaco-Ville
scope_note: Most ancient part of the principality; located on a rocky promontory on S side of port; site of 13th-cen. Palais du Prince.

label: Maria Saal
scope_note: Noted for the pilgrimage church of Maria Saal, first consecrated in 750 by Bishop Modestus. In 1480, Hungarians sieged the present day fortified church, but were unable to take it.
wikidata_description: municipality in Klagenfurt-Land District, Carinthia, Austria

label: Amberg
scope_note: The city of Amberg is located on the Vils River, at the edge of the Bavarian Forest in Oberpfalz, Bavaria, Germany. It was noted as a court town by the 11th century, and was a major trading center and fortified city from the 14th to the 16th century. It was the scene of the defeat of the French by Archduke Charles of Austria in the 1796 in War of the First Coalition. Among its historic structures still surviving re the medieval walls and town gates, along with many fine churches. Modern industries include glass grinding, enameling, porcelain and brick works, breweries, and iron works. The 2004 estimated population was 44,700.

label: Grebenstein
wikidata_description: town in Landkreis Kassel in Hesse, Germany

label: Bourg-en-Bresse
scope_note: The main center for Bresse-Dombes lowlands; made chief city of Bresse by dukes of Savoy early 15th cen.; has 16th-cen. Gothic Notre-Dame church & museum of antiquities; economy depends on light manufacturing, farm trade & tourism.

label: Fílippoi
scope_note: Founded by the exiled Athenian politician, Kallistratos, & colonists from Thasos in 4th cen. BCE; taken by Philip II of Macedon in 356 BCE; made famous by nearby battle of Brutus & Cassius against Antony & Octavian in 42 BCE.

label: Trapani
scope_note: Founded by Carthaginians; was important naval base during First Punic War (mid-3rd cen. BCE); later ceded to Rome; conquered by Vandals 440 CE, Saracens in 1077, & later by the Normans who made it part of the Kingdom of the Two Sicilies.

label: Terni
scope_note: Located on Nera river; developed as ancient Umbrian town; was important Roman center, possibly birthplace of historian Tacitus and site of murder of Emperor Gallus in 253 CE; sacked in 6th-7th, and 12th centuries; went to Papacy in the 14th century; devastated in WW II.

label: Baltimore
scope_note: Located at the head of Patapsco river estuary above Chesapeake Bay; settlement founded as outlet for local tobacco, developed as producer of clipper ships in 18th century; many citizens had Southern sympathies in Civil War, though state was pro-Union.

label: Halle
scope_note: The town of Halle is located on the Charleroi-Brussels canal in the Belgian province of Brabant, ten kilometers southwest of Brussels. It is noted as a pilgrimage site for a miraculous statue of the Virgin Mary, the Black Virgin, located in the Basilica of Our Lady, a 14th-century Gothic church.  It also houses the Southwest Brabant Museum. Its population by a 2000 estimate is about 34,000.

label: Esslingen
scope_note: The town of Esslingen is located on the Neckar River in the district of Stuttgart in southwestern Germany at a site of commanding, strategic height. It lies at the center of a fertile wine-producing and fruit-growing area. Documented in 777 as Cella and in 866 as Hetsilinga, it was fortified and chartered about 1219. It was a free imperial city until it passed to Württemberg in 1802. Historic architecture includes three town halls, the old citadel standing upon a high crest, and the Church of Our Lady, built between 1321 and 1516, the first structure to be designed in the Swabian gothic style. The 2004 estimated population was 91,600.

label: Herculaneum
scope_note: Located at foot of Mount Vesuvius; was a thriving resort during Roman times; destroyed, with Pompeii in 79 CE when Vesuvius erupted, as Herculaneum was still being rebuilt after an earthquake several years earlier. The ruins offer the best known evidence of ancient Roman private life; one of three sites grouped together in an UNESCO World Heritage Site in 1997 and noted for their well-preserved remains due to ash covering. The modern town of Ercolano is in part built on the ancient ruins of Herculaneum, but most of the ancient site, and the officially designated historical monument, lies south of the town center.

label: Lecce
scope_note: On Salentina peninsula; possibly site of Roman town of Lupiae; contested between Lombards, Byzantines and Saracens after fall of Roman Empire; has ruins of Roman amphitheater (from 4th century BCE) and examples of 16th-17th century Apulian Baroque architecture.

label: Bern
scope_note: Located on the frontier between German-speaking Alemannians and French-speaking Burgundians, its name may be derived from the German 'bär', a bear, which is its heraldic device and used on its civic seal since 1224. Founded by duke Berthold V of Zähringen in 1191, it became free imperial city after 1218. Site of important disputations between Catholics and reformers in 1528.
wikidata_description: city in Switzerland, capital of the canton of Bern and de facto capital of Switzerland

label: Blois
scope_note: Blois is the capital of the Loir-et-Cher dèpartement, on the Loire River, northeast of Tours. It was first mentioned in the 6th century by Gregory of Tours. Joan of Arc set out from Blois in 1429 to raise the siege of Orléans. Blois was one of the pilgrimage sites on route to the Cathedral of Santiago de Compostela, home of the shrine dedicated to Saint James, the patron saint of Spain. The symbol of Saint James, the scalloped shell, became the primary symbol representing pilgrims. French pilgrimage routes to Compostela tend to follow old Roman roads, many of which continued to be utilized as primary roads of communication during the Middle Ages. Located in Blois is the château, which began as a feudal castle; it displays splendid work of all the architectural periods from the 13th to the 17th century. Many of the ancient buildings between the château and the river were destroyed in World War II; some have been rebuilt. The town has many Gothic and Renaissance buildings. It is one of the major tourist centers of the Loire Valley. Bloise produces corn (maize), asparagus, and wine in the surrounding countryside. The industry decentralization in the Paris region has promoted recent growth in Blois.
wikidata_description: French commune and city in Loir-et-Cher, Centre-Val de Loire

label: Barnard Castle
scope_note: Located on the north bank of the River Tees; grew around Norman castle built by Bernard de Balliol 1112-1132; site of uprising during reign of Henry VIII in 1569; noted for Bowes Museum (1892); Dickens was inspired to write the novel, Nicholas Nickelby, here in 1838.

label: Barletta
scope_note: On Adriatic Sea; captured by Ostrogoths 5th cen., Lombards 6th cen. & became part of Kingdom of Naples 11th cen.; site of Spanish victory over French during Spanish French Wars 1502; seat of the archbishops of Nazareth 1291-1918.

label: Sankt Wolfgang im Salzkammergut
wikidata_description: municipality in Gmunden District, Upper Austria, Austria

label: Neustadt an der Weinstrasse
scope_note: The city of Neustadt an der Weinstrasse is located on the eastern slopes of the Haardt mountains at the mouth of the Speyer-Bach. It was founded in 1220 and chartered in 1275. It retains several historic structures, including the Casimirianum, the seat of Heidelberg University from 1578-1583, now used as a convention hall, the town hall that was once a Jesuit College, and the Collegiate Church dating from the 14th century. It was damaged in the Thirty Years' War, and held by France in the1690s and the 1790s.  It was damaged heavily in World War II but has been rebuilt. The modern city is the capital  of the Rheinhesse-Pfalz district, and in the center of the famous German Weinstrasse, or Wine Route. It hosts the annual German wine festival, and is a center for the study of viticulture. Local industries include the production of paper and metal products, and tourism is a major economic mainstay. The 2005 population was calculated at 54,080.

label: Colmar
scope_note: Colmar is the capital of the department of Haut-Rhin. It is first mentioned in chronicle of the Saxon wars of Charlemagne (800-814). In 1226 Holy Roman Emperor Frederick II accorded it the status of an imperial town, and walls were built surrounding it.  Rudolph of Hapsburg granted it civil rights in 1278. Sweden occupied it in 1632 during the Thirty Years War. Louis XIII of France took it under his protection in 1635, and then France gradually annexed it over the years 1648-1678. Germany and France alternately took possession of the town between 1871 and 1945, since when it has been part of France. The town is known for its fountains, churches, and Alsatian Renaissance buildings, and the Musée Unterlinden houses the famous Isenheim Altarpiece by Matthias Grünewald. It is the birthplace of Frédéric-Auguste Bartholdi, the creator of the Statue of Liberty.

label: Pienza
scope_note: Town planning was sponsored by Pius II (of Piccolomini family); was created as a haven for Humanist culture; architect Bernardo Rossellino designed the urban plan that included a cathedral, episcopal palace, town hall & the Piccolomini palace; historic core named an UNESCO World Heritage Site in 1996.

label: Prato
scope_note: Located on Bisenzio river NW of Florence; by Middle Ages was a famous commercial center; was an independent commune by 11th cen.; taken by Florence in 1350; was sacked by Spanish in 1512 during campaign to restore Medici of Florence.

label: Berat
scope_note: The historic center of the town is designated, along with the historic center of Gjirokastër, a World Heritage Site. It was a town in the ancient the ancient Greek region Epirus. It is possible that it was founded by Cassander, and named after his father Antipater in 314 BCE. A fortress-settlement of the Greek Dassaretae tribe existed in the area as the 6th century BCE, as it was then located on the border between Illyria and Epirus. It was captured by the Romans in the 2nd century BCE.

label: Viterbo
scope_note: Established by Etruscans; taken by Romans ca. 310 BCE; was given to popes by Countess Matilda of Tuscany in 11th cen.; was residence of several popes in Middle Ages; city was severely damaged in WW II, but has been rebuilt.

label: Jena
scope_note: Located in Gera area on Saale river; ruled by House of Wettin from 14th cen., by dukes of Ernestine line from 1485; was noted academic center, long focus of liberal ideas in Germany, including those of evolutionist E Haeckel & Karl Marx; damaged in WW II.

label: Salisbury
scope_note: Located in the valley adjacent to the mound where Old Sarum was located; developed around new cathedral that was built here in 13th cen.; flourished as cloth & wool center; streets are laid out in gridiron pattern that retain city's medieval character.

label: Trani
scope_note: Originated as Roman town & flourished under Norman & Swabian Kings of Sicily; noted for castle of Frederick II (1233-1249), Palazzo Caccette (1458) & St. Pelegrinus Cathedral (1094) dedicated to a martyred Greek Pilgrim; known for fine wines & marble.

label: Konstanz
scope_note: The city of Konstanz is located on Lake Constance, where the Rhein River exits it. It was the site of a Roman fort, which was taken by the Alemanni in the 3rd century BCE, and made an episcopal see in the 6th century. It prospered in the linen trade from 13th century, threw off episcopal rule in the 14th century, and became the leader of a confederacy of towns. It joined the Protestant Schmalkaldic League 1531, but became Roman Catholic again in 1547. It came under Austrian rule and remained there until ceded to the duchy of Baden in 1805. The city remains a cultural and economic center, and has much historic architecture, including the Kaufhaus built in 1388, the Renaissance town hall, the Gothic Rosgarten Museum, and the Insel Hotel, a former medieval Dominican monastery. There are also a university and an art museum. It is a popular tourist destination. The 2004 estimated population was 80,100.

label: Cardiff
scope_note: Was Roman fort in the 1st century CE; expanded into walled town by Normans in the 12th century; ruled by several British monarchs 15th-19th centuries; world's largest coal exporter 1913-1963; other industries are steel and food-processing.
wikidata_description: capital city of Wales, United Kingdom

label: Utrecht
scope_note: Located on Kromme Rijn, Oude Rijn and Vecht rivers. Inhabited by Romans as early  as 48 BCE ans was the headquarters of bishop St. Willibrord in 696. It was residence to early German emperors and was chartered in 1122. Important ecclesiastical, cultural, and commercial city, it was also the home of Adrian IV, the only Dutch pope. The Peace Treaty of Utrecht ending the War of Spanish Succession was signed here in 1713.
wikidata_description: municipality in the Netherlands and capital city of the province of Utrecht

label: Aarau
scope_note: Located on the Aare river at the foot of the Jura mountains; founded by counts of Kyburg, then passed to the Hapsburgs in 1264; taken by Bernese in 1415; today town manufactures electrical goods, bells, precision instruments, shoes & other goods.

label: Al Uqşur
scope_note: With the village of Karnak, Luxor is on the site of ancient Thebes (capital of the New Kingdom). It is noted for having ruins of many temples and burial grounds. When Thebes declined, Luxor remained the more heavily populated part of the ancient city and grew into a modern market town.

label: Lier
scope_note: Lier is a commune in the province of Antwerp in northern Belgium, at the confluence of the Little and Great Nete Rivers. Founded in the 8th century, the early town was associated with St. Gummerus, died 774 CE, who was a courtier to King Pepin and became a hermit here to escape his nagging wife. It received town status from Duke Henry of Brabant in 1212. The site of much northern European strife over the ages, it was besieged and captured by the Spanish in 1582, by the Dutch in 1595, and by the English in 1706 during the War of the Spanish Succession. Belgian nationalists repelled a Dutch attack there in 1830. World War I caused the destruction of much of the town, but a significant amount of its medieval architecture has survived. Notable buildings include Saint Gummarus' Church, built 1425-1577, and the 17th century Zimmer Tower, which features a multifaced astrological clock. Traditional industries include lace making, embroidery mills, and the manufacture of clothing, beaded bags, and musical instruments. The 2003 estimated population is 32, 500.

label: Pau
scope_note: Pau was one of the pilgrimage sites on route to the Cathedral of Santiago de Compostela, home of the shrine dedicated to Saint James, the patron saint of Spain. The symbol of Saint James, the scalloped shell, became the primary symbol representing pilgrims. French pilgrimage routes to Compostela tend to follow old Roman roads, many of which continued to be utilized as primary roads of communication during the Middle Ages. The towns name Pau means "Palisade" in Béarnais. Archaeological studies indicate that in the beginning of the 13th century there were several palisades on the various levels of the cliff which overlooked the Gave de Pau. Located in Pau is a castle and the church of Saint-Martin.

label: Spina
scope_note: Important pre-Roman city founded by either the Pelasgians, the Thessalians or by Diomedes at the mouth of a branch of the Po River; noted for Attic red-figureware.

label: San Gimignano
scope_note: Walled hill town that still retains medieval character; named for 4th-cen. bishop who freed the town from Germanic control; troubled by Guelph/Ghibelline conflict of two feuding families in Middle Ages; taken by Florence in 1250, and again in 14th cen.; historic center named UNESCO World Heritage Site in 1990.

label: Brașov
scope_note: Was founded by Teutonic Knights in 13th cen.; became center of Saxon colony & marketplace for trade of cloth, weapons, metalwork & wax throughout Walachia & Moldavia; fortified against Turks in 15th cen.; German inhabitants lost their autonomy in 1876.

label: Burgdorf
scope_note: Located on the Emme river; founded by dukes of Zähringen in 12th cen.; ruled by Bern from 1384.

label: Valencia
scope_note: Captured by Visigoths in 413 & by Moors in 714; seat of independent Moorish kingdom of Valencia 1021; kingdom captured from Moorish Almoravids by El Cid, who held it until his death in 1099; kingdom & city retaken by Moors 1102; united with Castile 1479.
wikidata_description: municipality in Spain, capital city of the Valencian Community

label: Kißlegg
wikidata_description: municipality in the district of Ravensburg, Baden-Württemberg, Germany

label: Michelstadt
scope_note: Located in: Germany

label: Euskirchen
scope_note: The small western German city of Euskirchen lies some 20 miles south southwest of Cologne. A thriving medieval center, it received its city charter in 1302.  It was the birthplace in 1852 of Nobel Prize-winning chemist Emil Fischer. It is now a modern manufacturing city. Its population estimate for 2004 was 54,500.

label: Barcelona
scope_note: Carthaginian settlement was taken by Romans; Visigoths then held the city until Moorish rule began in 8th century CE; Carolingian supremacy began in 801; powerful medieval counts controlled all of Catalonia and Aragon; was great commercial power.

label: Qiddīsah Kātrīnā, Dayr al
scope_note: Located on the N slope of Mt. Sinai; monastery was founded in 3rd cen. CE and rebuilt by Justinian ca. 530; the Codex Sinaiticus, Codex Syriacus & other early manuscripts of the Bible were found here.

label: Bad Cannstatt
scope_note: The town of Bad-Cannstatt is located on the outskirts of the city of Stuttgart in southwestern Germany. It was the site of prehistoric settlements and a Roman fort.

label: Miltenberg
wikidata_description: urban municipality of Germany in Bavaria and seat of Miltenberg district

label: Greifswald
scope_note: The city of Greifswald lies near the mouth of the Ryck River at Greifswalder Bay on the Baltic Sea in northeastern Germany. It was documented as a market center for the Eldena monastery by 1209. It was settled by traders from the Netherlands in 1240, and joined the Hanseatic League in 1270. It was taken by Sweden in 1648, then by Prussia in 1815. Its historic structures include the 1350 town hall, several churches from the Gothic and Renaissance periods, and a university founded in 1456. The city is a communications hub, serving as both a port and a railway junction, and a trade center, handling wheat, coal, and wood. It has foodstuff, textile, and machinery manufactures. Its 2004 estimated population was 52,500.

label: Hessisch Oldendorf
wikidata_description: Town in the Lower Saxony district of Hameln-Pyrmont, Germany

label: Salerno
scope_note: Located on Gulf of Salerno; was settled by Greeks; was a Roman colony by 195 BC; ruled by Goths; part of Lombard Duchy of Salerno in 6th cen.; seat of independent principality 9th cen.; under Normans (from 1076), then Kingdom of Naples; damaged in WW II.

label: Rieti
scope_note: Located on the Velino river in the Abruzzi Apennines; was an important center for ancient Sabines; conquered by Romans 290 BCE, when the village became a strategic point in the Via Salaria that linked Rome to the Adriatic Sea through the Apennines for transporting salt. Was part of Lombard duchy of Spoleto in early Middle Ages, later went to Papal States; was often a residence of the popes.

label: Chemnitz
scope_note: The eastern German city of Chemnitz is situated on the Chemnitz river on the north slope of the Ore Mountain range. It lies on the historically important salt route to Prague. It was chartered in 1143. In 1308 it was taken over by the Wettin family of Meissen. It was granted a textile-bleaching monopoly in 1357, which inspired a prosperous linen industry. In the 19th century machine construction began in Chemnitz, facilitated by the growing expansion of coal and lignite production in Saxony. It is noted for the creation of the first spinning wheel, the first machine tools, and the first locomotive in Germany. It was severely damaged in World War II, but was rebuilt. Historic structures include the 1496 town hall, the medieval Red Tower, and a former Benedictine monastery of 1136 with a Gothic hall church that is now a museum. Chemnitz is a center for education, having a college of education, a school of machine construction, and several technical schools. It is a transportation hub and an industrial center with both heavy and light industries, notably for a wide variety of textiles. The calculated population for 2005 was 246,654.

label: Amboise
scope_note: Was lordship inder counts of Anjou in 11th cen.; united to royal domain 1431; castle became a royal residence, later a state prison; chapel is said to be burial place of Leonardo da Vinci.

label: Carcassonne
scope_note: Was important medieval fortified center; was taken by Saracens in 728; flourished as seat of viscountship 11th-13th cen.; taken by Simon de Montfort 1209; went to France 1247; destroyed by Black Prince 1355; mix of Iberian, Celtic & Roman influences; an immense stone arch is a reminder of the Visigoth Empire.

label: Vitoria-Gasteiz
scope_note: Located on the Zadorra river southwest of San Sebastián, the town was given charter by Sancho VI the Wise of Navarre in the 12th century. It was taken in 1200 by Alfonso VIII of Castile who brought it under his kingdom. It is the location of the old Santa María cathedral, founded in 1180 and rebuilt in the 14th century.

label: Çanakkale
scope_note: Located northeast of Çanakkale city; Thracians occupied ancient city after Trojan War until settlement by Milesians with permission of Gyges king of Lydia ca. 700 BCE; one end of bridge which Xerxes' army crossed when invading Greece 480 BCE; later became toll station.

label: Chiusi
scope_note: Was one of the 12 original cities of Etruria; flourished 7th-6th centuries BCE; noted as site from which Lars Porsena marched against Rome ca. 500 BCE; was subject to Rome from 295 BCE; declined in Middle Ages due to proximity to swamps of Chiani river.

label: Legnica
scope_note: Located on Kaczawa River; became important trade center in 13th cen.; ruled by Piast kings; taken by Hapsburgs in 1675; was severely damaged during World War II; returned to Poland at Postdam Conference in 1945.
wikidata_description: city with powiat rights of Poland

label: Cottbus
scope_note: The city of Cottbus is located on the Spree River, at the edge of the Spree Forest in eastern Germany near the Polish border. It was a fortified trading town by the 12th century and ruled by Brandenburg from 1445, by Saxony from 1635, and by Prussia from 1815. Its surviving historic structures include some of the old fortifications and several 14th- and 15th-century churches. An industrial center, it produces electrical equipment, textiles, building materials, and leather. Its 2004 estimated population was 102,400.

label: Reinheim
wikidata_description: town in Landkreis Darmstadt-Dieburg in Hesse, Germany

label: Lippstadt
scope_note: The city of Lippstadt is situated on the Lippe river on the slopes of the Teutoburg Forest in the state of North Rhine-Westphalia in western Germany. It was probably founded by the lords of Lippe in the 12th century. A member of the Hanseatic League from 1260; the town was split between the ruling house of Lippe and the county of Mark, which went to Brandenburg in 1614. Divided in ownership between Prussia and Lippe, Lippe sold its share to Prussia in 1850. The modern city is industrial, with iron founding, textile production, and metalworking it main economic activities. Historic structures include several 13th-century churches and old half-timbered residences, a Rococo hall in a local hotel, and a town hall dating from 1773. There are also four moated castles in the vicinity. The 2004 estimated population was 67,500.

label: Gorizia
scope_note: Located on Isonzo River; seat of a duchy 11th-16th cen.; became important Austrian cultural center under Hapsburg control 16th cen.; scene of heavy fighting during WW II; after treaty of 1947, northern portion became Yugoslav (now Croatian) town of Nova Gorica.

label: Ravensburg
scope_note: The city of Ravensburg is situated on the Schussen River, north of Lake Constance in the state of Baden-Württemberg in southwestern Germany. It was founded and chartered in the 11th century. It went to the Hohenstaufen family in 1180, then in 1276 became a free city of the Holy Roman Empire, which it remained until 1802. A flourishing medieval trading center, it joined the Swabian League in the 14th century. Much of its medieval architecture belongs, including the wall tower from the old fourteenth-century fortifications, the parish church, the town hall, and St. Jodok's Church. Textiles and machinery are among its main products today. The 2004 estimated population was 48,400.

label: Babenhausen
wikidata_description: main settlement of Babenhausen in Germany

label: Leipzig
scope_note: The eastern German city of Leipzig is situated at the junction of the Pleisse, Parthe, and Weisse Elster rivers, some 113 miles southwest of Berlin. By the 11th century it had developed as a fortified settlement at the intersection of major European trade routes. It was first mentioned in 1015 under the name Urbs Libzi, and was granted town status by 1170. It quickly became a commercial center, and the agriculture of the fertile Leipzig basin made it a notable market town. Famed for printing since 1470, by 1700 it was the most important German center of commerce, and did a busy trade in books, textiles, and furs. In 1839 the first German railway was built between Dresden and Leipzig, promoting the growth of industries such as metallugy. Leipzig also became a cultural center, famed as the home of J.S. Bach who, in his later years, was the city's director of church music. It was heavily damaged in World War II, and was extensively rebuilt. New post-war industries include the manufactures of machine tools, garments, and electronics. The great Leipzig Fair held every spring is the major market for trade between eastern and western Europe. The city remains a cultural leader with the University of Leipzig founded in 1409, academies of music, bookmaking, and drama, an orchestra, and an opera house. Surviving and restored historic architecture includes the Old Town Hall, the Old Commercial Exchange, and the 13th-century St. Thomas' church. The calculated population for 2005 was 492,637.

label: Nordhausen
scope_note: City located on the Zorge River and next to the Harz Mountains in the fertile area known as the Goldene Aue. A royal castle was built in Nordhausen near an old Frankish settlement 927 CE. In 1802, it became part of Prussian Saxony until 1945 (except from 1807-1813, when it was part of Westphalia). On the outskirts of Nordhausen, the Nazis established a concentration camp of the same name (also called Dora-Mittelbau, or Dora-Nordhausen). The Nazis evacuated the camp in April 1945, before its liberation by the U.S., and forced the prisoners on a brutal "death march" to Bergen-Belsen concentration camp.

label: Liverpool
scope_note: England's sixth largest port, Liverpool rapidly expanded due to trade with the Americas and the West Indies in the 18th century. The first dock opened in 1715 and is now 7 miles long. The city was the destination of many Irish immigrants during the Irish famine (1845-1848). During World War II, it was heavily bombed.
wikidata_description: city in Merseyside, England, United Kingdom

label: Alessandria
scope_note: Located at confluence of Bromida & Tanaro rivers; founded by Lombard League as stronghold in Alpine valley against emperor Frederick I Barbarossa in 12th cen.; ruled by Visconti of Milan from 14th cen., by House of Savoy from 1713.
wikidata_description: Italian city and commune in Piedmont

label: Vicenza
scope_note: Founded by Ligurians in 1st cen. BCE; gained independence in 1164 and joined Lombard League; was destroyed by Emperor Frederick II in 1236; ruled by Della Scala family of Verona 14th cen.; part of Venetian Republic 15th cen.; named UNESCO World Heritage Site in 1994 due to its many villas constructed by Andrea Palladio.

label: Logroño
scope_note: Logroño was one of the pilgrimage sites on route to the Cathedral of Santiago de Compostela, home of the shrine dedicated to Saint James, the patron saint of Spain. The symbol of Saint James, the scalloped shell, became the primary symbol representing pilgrims. Various pilgrimage routes in the autonomous communities of Aragon, Navarre, and León correspond to old Roman roads built in the northern portion of the Iberian Peninsula. Its wool production and location on the medieval pilgrimage route to Santiago de Compostela led to its growth. Churches in Logroño include the 11th-century Santa María del Palacio, 16th-century Santiago el Real and 15th-17th-century Santa María la Redonda.

label: Herford
scope_note: The city of Herford in the Detmold district of the west-central German state of North Rhine-Westphalia is situated where the Werre river joins the Aa river. By 789 it had developed around Benedictine convent founded in the 8th century and was confirmed by the Holy Roman Emperor Louis the Pious in 823. It joined the Hanseatic League in 1547. Brandenburg ruled it from 1647, Westphalia from 1807, and Prussia from 1815. The 13th-century Benedictine church still stands. The modern city produces a diverse range of goods including chocolate, cigars, machinery, textiles, carpets, and metal objects. In 2004, its population was estimated at about 65,000.

label: Narva
scope_note: Located on Narva river near its outfall into the Gulf of Finland; flourished as commercial center in Middle Ages; occupied by Russia in 16th cen., then by Sweden; noted as site of Swedes defeat of Peter I the Great in 1700 & his victory in 1704.

label: La Charité-sur-Loire
scope_note: Charité-sur-Loire, La was one of the pilgrimage sites on route to the Cathedral of Santiago de Compostela, home of the shrine dedicated to Saint James, the patron saint of Spain. The symbol of Saint James, the scalloped shell, became the primary symbol representing pilgrims. French pilgrimage routes to Compostela tend to follow old Roman roads, many of which continued to be utilized as primary roads of communication during the Middle Ages. An important site located in Charité-sur-Loire is the priory church of Ste-Croix-Notre-Dame.

label: Vaison-la-Romaine
scope_note: Was important Celtic city; occupied by Romans during the Augustan period; was bisopric from 3rd cen.; enjoyed productive autonomy until invaders drove population across nearby Ouvèze river; was resettled in 17th cen.; noted for extensive Roman ruins.

label: Timotesubani
wikidata_description: temple, monastery and church building in Borjomi Municipality, Georgia

label: Elefsína
scope_note: Located on bay of Eleusis; was an very early independent city; taken by Athens in 7th cen. BCE; traditional festivals were converted into a major Athenian religious ceremony, the Eleusian mysteries; ruined by Gothic Alaric in 365 CE.

label: Brindisi
scope_note: On Y-shaped sea inlet of Adriatic; was terminus of Appian Way; taken by Caesar 49 BC & Virgil died here 19 BC; prospered during Norman conquest 1071 & with Suez Canal construction 1869; was briefly seat of Italian government after death of Mussolini 1943.

label: Bolzano
scope_note: On Talvera & Isarco rivers; fell to Lombards 680 & Franks 740; seat of Bavarian border countships from 680 until it fell to episcopate of Trent 1027; part of Napoleonic Kingdom of Italy 1810-1813; passed to Italy 1918; inhabitants mostly German-speaking.

label: Kawm Umbū
scope_note: Stone temple and settlement site with remains dating from ca. 1550 BCE.

label: Heilbronn
scope_note: The city of Heilbronn is located on the Neckar River in the Swabian Forest in southwestern Germany. It was originally a Roman settlement; it was first documented in 741. It belonged to the Frankish crown lands in the 8th century, and was the site of a Carolingian palace from the 9th century. It became a free imperial city in 1281. It suffered in the 16th-century Peasants War, but revived. It was heavily damaged in World War II, but many of its historic structures have been rebuilt. These include St. Killan's Church, designed in a mix of Gothic and Renaissance styles, and the town hall of 1540. The surrounding land is rich and grows large crops of fruits and vegetables, including wine grapes. The city is a commercial center with an important harbor on the Rhine-Neckar shipping route. Machinery and wine are important local products. The 2004 estimated population was 121,300.

label: Wolfenbüttel
scope_note: The city of Wolfenbüttel is situated on the Oker River in the district of Braunschweig in Lower Saxony in north-central Germany. The town grew around a castle that became the Guelph (Welf) dukes' residence in the 13th century. It was captured by the Protestant Schmalkaldic League in 1542; went to Braunschweig in 1753. The old town contains the castle residence of the dukes of Braunschweig-Wolfenbüttel and the Church of St, Mary, built 1604-23. There are also many Renaissance and Baroque half-timbered houses. The ducal Herzog-August Library contains a large collection of medieval manuscripts. The ducal librarians have included such notable people as the philosopher Leibnitz and the playwright Gotthold Lessing. The modern city's industries include canning, the production of chemical and musical equipment, and agricultural machinery. The 2004 estimated population was 54,800.

label: Velletri
scope_note: Historically controlled valley between the Alban & Volscian mountains; sacked by Romans 338 BC; was seat of the gens Octavia (ancestors of Emperor Augustus); was independent city-state from 11th cen. to 1549, when it fell to the Papal States.

label: Vendôme
scope_note: Vendôme is a historic town and capital of an arrondissement in the département of Loir-et-Cher, in north-central France. Vendôme is situated on the Loir River, which divides and intersects the town. In the south there is a hill on which are ruins of the 11th-century castle of the counts of Vendôme. Vendôme was one of the pilgrimage sites on route to the Cathedral of Santiago de Compostela, home of the shrine dedicated to Saint James, the patron saint of Spain. The symbol of Saint James, the scalloped shell, became the primary symbol representing pilgrims.
