French pilgrimage routes to Compostela tend to follow old Roman roads, many of which continued to be utilized as primary roads of communication during the Middle Ages. Vendôme became part of France in 1589 under Henry IV. The town was damaged during World War II, but then restored. It contains a diverse local industry which includes household appliances, computers, printing, control and measurement apparatus, and food processing.

label: Versailles
scope_note: Built by French kings on site of Louis XIII's hunting lodge; seat of court of Louis XIV who built large palace; meeting place of States-General in 1783; scene of several treaty signings; German headquarters 1870-1871; seat of French government 1871-1879.
wikidata_description: French city and commune in Yvelines, in Île-de-France

label: Kórinthos
scope_note: Was one of the most powerful cities of ancient Greece; settled in prehistoric times; modern city was founded by Dorian invaders; was important maritime power by 7th cen. BCE, & colonized widely; was destroyed several times by war & earthquakes, & rebuilt.

label: Anagni
scope_note: First settlers, the Ernici, were defeated by Romans in 305 BC; was Roman civitas & later a municipium; was important bishopric; site where Pope Boniface was taken hostage by Philip IV of France in 1303 during struggles between papacy & heads of state.

label: Cagliari
scope_note: Located on S coast; was important Phoenician center, later principal Carthaginian stronghold in Sardegna; taken by Rome in Second Punic War (ca. 218 BCE), became crucial Roman harbor; independent in Middle Ages, taken by Pisans, Aragonese & Savoy (1718).

label: Cagliari
scope_note: Located on S coast; was important Phoenician center, later principal Carthaginian stronghold in Sardegna; taken by Rome in Second Punic War (ca. 218 BCE), became crucial Roman harbor; independent in Middle Ages, taken by Pisans, Aragonese & Savoy (1718).

label: Messina
scope_note: Founded by Greeks from Chalcis; destroyed by Carthaginians 397 BCE; was Roman free city 241 BCE; taken by Goths, Byzantines, Arabs (842), Crusader Richard I of England (1190); ruled by Angevins, Aragonese, then by Spanish Bourbons 13th cen.-1713.

label: Aosta
scope_note: At junction of Great and Little St. Bernard passes; birthplace of St. Anselm, archbishop of Canterbury; became duchy in 1302; occupied by French several times in the 18th and 19th centuries; site of nearly intact Roman city walls, arch of Augustus, and amphitheater ruins.

label: Conques
scope_note: Conques was one of the pilgrimage sites on route to the Cathedral of Santiago de Compostela, home of the shrine dedicated to Saint James, the patron saint of Spain. The symbol of Saint James, the scalloped shell, became the primary symbol representing pilgrims. French pilgrimage routes to Compostela tend to follow old Roman roads, many of which continued to be utilized as primary roads of communication during the Middle Ages. Important historic sites in Conques include the former abbey church of Sainte Foy and the parish church of Saint-Thomas de Cantorbéry.

label: Aquileia
scope_note: Established for military purposes after Roman power extended to Po valley; sacked by Huns 452 & Lombards 568; a feudal principality until Venetian conquest of Friuli; declined after passing to Venice 1420; ruled by Austria 1509-1918, then passed to Italy; archaeological site named UNESCO World Heritage Site in 1998.

label: Ragusa
scope_note: Located in Iblei mountains above the gorge of the Irminio river; was recorded as important Greek center by 6th century BCE; was thriving late Roman center on major road; modern town grew up across a declivity from the ancient site.

label: Trento
scope_note: On Adige River; was Roman military base; seat of Lombard duchy 6th cen.; passed to Austria 16th cen.; site of Council of Trent (1545-1563) where doctrines of Catholic Reformation were established; passed to Italy 1918 & badly flooded 1966.
wikidata_description: Italian city in the North-East of the country

label: Kraków
scope_note: A cultural and artistic center since 14th century, Kraków was destroyed by Swedish wars in the 17th century, and later occupied by Austria from 1795-1918. It suffered Nazi attacks during World War II, and was also the location of a Nazi concentration camp, known as the Plaszow camp, in operation as a forced-labor camp from 1942-1944, and then a full concentration camp from 1944-1945. The camp held up to 20,000 people, and many thousands were killed by the SS during the camp's existence. Industry in Kraków revived after the war. The city is known for its rich architectural history, museums, and theaters.
wikidata_description: capital city of Lesser Poland Voivodeship in southern Poland

label: Bilbao
scope_note: Largest city in Basque country; most significant Spanish port; flourished from active trade with Spanish colonies in America 18th cen.; under French occupation 1795 & during Peninsular War 1808-1813; attacked by Carlists 1835 & 1874.

label: Jaca
scope_note: Jaca was one of the pilgrimage sites on route to the Cathedral of Santiago de Compostela, home of the shrine dedicated to Saint James, the patron saint of Spain. The symbol of Saint James, the scalloped shell, became the primary symbol representing pilgrims. Various pilgrimage routes in the autonomous communities of Aragon, Navarre, and León correspond to old Roman roads built in the northern portion of the Iberian Peninsula. Jaca during the 11th century consisted of two parts, the Burgos of San Nicolás and the Burgos Nuevo. Burgos Nuevo encouraged French people to become settlers. Historic sites in Jaca include the Cathedral of San Pedro, the Church of Santiago and Santo Domingo, the Church of San Gines, the Sarchophagus of Donä Sancha, and the Inn of the Church of the Holy Spirit.

label: Netze
scope_note: The small town of Netze is located near Waldeck in the district of Kassel in the German state of Hessen. A Cistercian abbey was founded here in 1228 around which the town grew..

label: Siegburg
scope_note: The western German town of Siegburg is situated on the Sieg river, some 14 miles southeast of Cologne. It was the site of an abbey founded by saint Anno in 1064, It received its charter in 1182. Its principal historic building is a 12th-century church. The shrine of St. Agnes there has a reliquary said to be by the noted 12th-century goldsmith and enamellist Nicholas of Verdun. Famed German composer Engelbert Humperdinck was born here in 1854. Local industry produces synthetic fibers. The population estimate for 2004 was 38,200.
wikidata_description: city in the district of Rhein-Sieg-Kreis, in North Rhine-Westphalia, Germany

label: Niort
scope_note: Developed around castle built by Henry Plantagenet 1155; taken by Louis VIII 1224; ruled by England 1360-1373; Protestant stronghold 16th cen.; suffered through Revocation of Edict of Nantes 1685; site of 15th-cen. Gothic-Renaissance church.

label: Ródhos
scope_note: Located at isolated northern tip of island; designed by Hippodamus of Miletus and founded in 5th cen. BC; resisted attack by Macedonians, then citizens erected the huge bronze statue of Helios, known as the Colossus of Rhodes, later destroyed by earthquake.

label: Cerveteri
scope_note: At one point a major Etruscan city-state.

label: Gaeta
scope_note: Located on the Gulf of Gaeta, northwest of Naples. Under Romans by 4th century BCE; town and port were connected by a road ca. 184 BCE, allowing it bo become a resort. Loyal to the Byzantine Empire after 5th century BCE. Was independent hroughout Gothic, Lombard, and Saracen wars and invasions. Was a maritime republic in the 8th century; autonomous duchy after 915; taken by Normans in 1140. In the 15th century it was the center of struggles for succession to the throne of Naples. Its capitulation to the Kingdom of Italy in 1861 marked the end of the Bourbon Kingdom of the Two Sicilies.

label: Novara
scope_note: Located on the Agogna river; was founded by Caesar on site of Celtic settlement; destroyed in 5th cen., but rebuilt in 6th cen.; burned by emperor Henry V in 1110; in Lombard League by 1167; ruled by Milan, then went to Austria 1714, to Savoy in 1738.

label: Bitonto
scope_note: Located SW of Bari; Roman coins dating from 6th-3rd cen. BC have been found here; was Roman municipality & became part early Norman Kingdom of Naples; site of Romanesque cathedral (1175-1200) & several Renaissance palaces.

label: Fiesole
scope_note: Hill town located above Florence; was an important Etruscan center,  founded 8th-9th century BCE; was conquered by Rome in 283 BCE; taken by Florence in 1125 CE; noted as home of painter Fra Angelico.

label: Moskva
scope_note: First noted as village 1147; grew around 13th-cen. Kremlin; sacked and rebuilt several times; expanded culturally and economically under Peter the Great in 17th cen., Catherine the Great in 18th cen. and Soviet government in 20th cen.; bombed during WW II.
wikidata_description: capital and most populous city of Russia

label: Neuwied
scope_note: The western German city of Neuwied is situated on the Rhine river some seven miles north northwest of Koblenz. The Romans created a military post here, but that settlement did not continue. In 1649 Frederick III, count of Wied, built a palace here and the town was founded around it in 1653y by the count for religious refugees. It was chartered in 1662.  It passed to the duchy of Nassau in 1806, then to Prussia in 1815. Its historic architecture includes a 18th-century Baroque castle, and the Roman military camp is being excavated. The economic activities of the modern city include engineering, the manufacture of cement, pumice building materials, chemicals, wood products, and rolled metal. The 2005 population was calculated at 66,901.

label: Chalon-sur-Saône
scope_note: An important town of the Gallic tribe of Aedui; exchanged for other fiefs in the Jura by Jean le Sage 1237; granted a charter 1256; held out against Austrian troops 1814; has 12th/15th-cen. cathedral, 14th-cen. church & 15th-cen. episcopal palace.

label: Bramdean
scope_note: An Elizabethan manor house is here.

label: Grantham
scope_note: St. Wulfran church has Norman pillars & a fine library; the Angel & Royal is one of the rare hostels established by the Knights Templar in the Middle Ages.

label: Calah
scope_note: Founded in the 13th century BCE by Shalmaneser I; declined in the 7th century BCE since Sargonids used Nineveh as their residence; sacked 614 BCE. Ancient Assyrian city was called Kalhu, called by Arabic name, Nimrud.

label: Ávila
scope_note: Fell to Moors around 714; taken by Alfonso VI for Christians 1088; walls built around ancient city 12th cen.; modern city situated outside walls; Moriscos expelled 1607-1610 & commerce subsequently declined; birthplace of mystic Saint Teresa. The Old Town of Ávila with its Extra-Muros Churches was named a World Heritage Site by UNESCO in 1985.
wikidata_description: municipality in Castile and León, Spain

label: Medina del Campo
wikidata_description: city of Spain in Valladolid province

label: Tongeren
wikidata_description: former city and municipality in Limburg, Belgium

label: Kortrijk
scope_note: Kortrijk is a town in West-Vlaanderen, western Belgium, situated along the Lys River and the Lys-Schelde Canal. First established as a Roman settlement; a chapel was erected here by St. Eloi in 7th century. It was a thriving producer of linen damask in medieval times. The inhabitants defeated the French cavalry here in 1302 in what came to be famed as the "Battle of the Golden Spurs", but the town was sacked in revenge in 1382. Captured by the Germans in World War I, it became a major base for the Ypres front. Like much of the Flanders region, it was severely damaged in World War II. Its art and architecture include the Broelbrug, a bridge built around 1400 with two massive towers, Anthony Van Dyck's painting "Elevation of the Cross", executed in 1631, housed in the church of Notre Dame, 1191-1211 which also features the conjoining chapel of the counts of Flanders, dating from 1374. Other notable structures are the St. Martin's Church in Gothic style, a 14th century belfry, and the Flamboyant Gothic town hall built in the 15th and 16th centuries. Commercially, the town is currently one of the primary producers and exporters of linen in Western Europe. The 2003 estimated population was about 74,800.

label: Mannheim
scope_note: The city of Mannheim is located on the east bank of the Rhine River, opposite Ludwigshafen at the confluence of the Neckar River and the Rhine in southwestern Germany. First mentioned as a village in 764, it was expanded and fortified by the Elector Frederick IV in 1606. It was heavily damaged and rebuilt in the Thirty Years' War and in the prelude to the War of the Grand Alliance in the 17th century. The Electors of Palatine moved their residence there in 1720, and built many structures in the Baroque style, notably the Jesuit Church, the castle, the town hall, and the pilgrimage church. The city became a center of high culture in the 18th century, which it has remained to this day, famous for its music, art museum, and Germany's National Theater. Destroyed again in 1795, it was once more rebuilt and was a center of revolutionary activity in 1848-1849. A harbor constructed there on the Rhine in 1834 encouraged economic and industrial activity. The city was heavily damaged again in World War II, but most of its principal historic buildings have been restored. Its principal manufactures include textiles, chemicals, fertilizer, and food products, and coal and iron are traded through its river harbor. The 2004 population estimate was 309,600.

label: Bielefeld
scope_note: The German city of Bielefeld is located at the edge of the Teutoburg Forest in the district of Detmold in the state of North Rhine-Westphalia. It was mentioned in the 11th-century biography of Bishop Meinwerk of Paderborn, and chartered by Count Hermann of Ravensberg in the 13th century. It joined the Hanseatic League in the 14th century. It passed under the rule of several principalities, from the county of Ravensberg in the 13th century, to the duchy of Jülich in 1346, and to Brandenburg in 1647. The city was badly damaged in World War II, but was rebuilt. It nevertheless retains many historic structures, including St. Mary's Church documented in the late 13thcentury, Sparrenburg Castle, built in 1250 and rebuilt after a fire in 1877, the medieval Jodokus and Altstädter Nicolai Church, and the Gothic Crüwell House, dating from 1540. The modern city has a gallery of modern art, a concert hall, an opera, a playing card museum, and a university founded in 1969. Well-known for its linen since the 16th century, it also weaves plush and silk textiles. There are other manufactories,  including for paper, clothing, sewing machines, bicycles, and electronic equipment. In 1973, Bielefeld absorbed several neighboring towns, doubling its size. The estimated population for 2004 was 323,700.

label: Ferentino
scope_note: Was chief city of ancient Hernici; was conquered by Rome in 361 BC; was famous medieval papal residence; noted for ancient fortifications.

label: Urbino
scope_note: Settled by Umbrians, then was home to Etruscans, Celts & Gauls; taken by Rome 3rd cen. BCE; ruled by Church 9th-13th cen.; was a major political and cultural center from 15th cen.; went to Papal States in 1626; has had little modern industrial development; historic core named an UNESCO World Heritage Site in 1996.
wikidata_description: town in the Marche region of Italy

label: Lugano
scope_note: Possession of Milan, town was occupied by French in 1499, taken by Swiss in 1512; part of Ticino since 1803; was seat of bishop of Italian-speaking Switzerland from 1888.
wikidata_description: city in the canton of Ticino, Switzerland

label: Sevilla
scope_note: Important cultural center during rule of 'Abbādid dynasty & later Almoravid and Almohad confederations; prospered after Spanish Christians under Ferdinand III expelled Muslims in 1248; Velásquez, Zurbarán & Murillo painted in Sevilla during the 17th century.

label: Schweinfurt
scope_note: Schweinfurt is situated on the canalized Main River in Bavaria in central Germany. It was an important medieval center, the seat of as margravate in the first century CE. It was occupied and fortified by Gustavus Adolphus in the Thirty Years' War in the 17th century. It fell under the rule of Bavaria in 1803. Due to its being a major ball bearing production center in Germany during World War II, it was heavily bombed. Its surviving historic architecture includes its Late Gothic town hall, built 1570-72, St Johannes' Church, built 1554-62, and the Old Gynasium (school), built 1581-83. It is an important industrial city, producing motor vehicles, steel, and electronics. Other economic activities include breweries and an important cattle and sheep market. Its 2004 estimated population was 54,800.

label: Kronberg
scope_note: Located west of Frankfurt-am-Main.

label: Hameln
scope_note: The city of Hameln lies on the Weser River southwest of the city of Hanover in Lower Saxony. It was an ancient Saxon settlement. The Abbey of St. Boniface was founded there in the late 8th century and the town grew up around it. Receiving its charter around 1200, it became the possession of the duchy of Brunswick around 1259 and later joined the Hanseatic League.  In legend it is the site of the rat-catcher Pied Piper's story, which was perhaps based on the exodus of young men colonizing the east, or on Nicholas of Köln leading thousands of children on the tragic Children's Crusade in 1212. Hameln attracts many tourists, situated as it is at the center of the Lower Weser Highlands scenic area and nature park. It has a river port and railway junction, and local industries including food processing and the production of chemicals, carpets, and machinery. Its 2004 estimated population was 59,200.

label: Mönchengladbach
scope_note: The northwestern German city of Mönchengladbach is located west of Düsseldorf in the state of North Rhine-Westphalia. The town developed around a Benedictine monastery founded in 972, and received its charter in 1336. For a few years between the World Wars it combined with two other towns, Rheydt and Odenkirchen to become Gladbach-Rheydt, but was split up again in 1933. In 1975 Mönchengladback absorbed Rheydt. The modern city retains much of its historic architecture, notably the 13th-century Romanesque cathedral, with a 10th-century crypt and a Gothic choir, a Romanesque parish church, a 12th-century-convent church, and the Baroque remodeling of 1663 of the former Benedictine abbey. There are several choral societies, and a local museum with a fine collection of Coptic textiles. There are also a botanical garden and several parks. The city is an educational center with the Duns Scotus Academy for philosophy and theology, colleges for agriculture and textile engineering, and a school of economics. Mönchengladbach has long been famed for textile production, and hosts the German Research Institute for textiles. Other products include paper, iron, machinery, chemicals, petroleum, and leather. It serves as a transportation center for rail, air, and highways. The city is the headquarters for the North Atlantic Treaty Organization (NATO) for north-central Europe. Its population estimate for 2004 was 263,300.

label: Chenonceaux
scope_note: Site of the famous Château de Chenonceaux on the Cher River, built by Thomas Bohier 1515-1522; residence of Diane de Poitiers & of Catherine de Médicis.

label: Albi
scope_note: An active center of Catharism; captured in 1215, causing bishops to lose their estates to the crown; temporal power was granted to bishops 1264 until French Revolution; Gothic Sainte-Cécile cathedral is town's chief architectural glory.

label: Dhílos
scope_note: Was a flourishing ancient commercial center; was sacked by Mathridates VI in 88 BC & was not rebuilt.

label: Naẕerat
scope_note: Largest Arab city in Israel; Biblical home of Joseph, Mary & Jesus; captured several times during Crusades; site of St. Mary's Well; its Christian inhabitants massacred by Baybars 1263; taken by Turks 1517 & by British 1918; has many churches.

label: Cosenza
scope_note: Located at confluence of Busento & Crati rivers; was ancient capital of the Brutii; important in 2nd Punic War; noted as site of tombs of Louis II of Anjou & Isabella of Aragon (in the cathedral); has been often devastated by earthquakes, but rebuilt.
wikidata_description: Italian comune in the province of Cosenza, Calabria

label: Bressanone
scope_note: Located at S end of Brenner Pass; site of conflicts between counts of Tyrol 11th-19th cen.; ceded to Italy 1919.

label: Lausanne
scope_note: Located on the N shore of Lake Geneva, 32 m. SE of Geneva. Originally a Celtic settlement and then a Roman military camp, it was ruled by prince-bishops from the 6th century to 1536. The Ottoman Empire signed a treaty here with Italy in 1912 and with Turkey in 1923. It was an intellectual center in the 18th century and was the home of Gibbon, Rousseau, and Voltaire.
wikidata_description: capital city of the canton of Vaud, Switzerland

label: České Budějovice
scope_note: The city of Ceske Budejovice lies south of Prague at the confluence of the Malse and Vltava Rivers. It was founded as a fortified town by the king of Bohemia in 1265, and still retains much of its medieval architecture, notably the arcaded town square. It is the town where Budweiser beer was first produced, and beer brewing is still a major industry. It has been known for the manufacture of pencils since 1790. It also produces porcelain, enamelware, furniture, tobacco, and food products. It serves as the capital of the region of Jihocesky. The 2003 estimated population was 98,600.

label: Biedenkopf
wikidata_description: town in Landkreis Marburg-Biedenkopf in Hesse, Germany

label: Spangenberg
wikidata_description: town in Schwalm-Eder-Kreis in Hesse, Germany

label: Saronno
scope_note: Manufacturing commune located 18 miles SE of Varese; site of a 13th/17th-cen. pilgrimage church; noted for its macaroons.

label: Vercelli
scope_note: Located on the Sesia river; was chief town of the Ligurian Libici people; taken by Rome & noted for two battles nearby, against Hannibal (218 BC) & Cimbri (101 BC); flourished in Middle Ages; went to Milan in 1335, to Savoy in 1427.

label: Spoleto
scope_note: Ancient city that was home to Umbrians and Etruscans; taken by Rome in 242 BCE; attacked by Hannibal (217 BCE), Marius and Sulla; flourished as key city on Roman Flaminian Way; given by Charlemagne to Pope in 8th cen.; destroyed by Frederick I in 1155, rebuilt; to Papacy 1354-1860.

label: Split
scope_note: Located on a peninsula on the Adriatic Sea; there is a deep, sheltered harbor on the south side.  The city was damaged by the Avars in 615. It was a port of medieval Dalmatia. It later became an important Byzantine city (from 812); also later held by Venice, Austria, and France. In 1918 it became part of Yugoslavia and in 1992 of independent Croatia. Controlled by Axis troops during WW II, most of port area was destroyed by Nazis. Best known for the ruins of the Palace of Diocletian (295-305 CE); collectively with the historic royal residences, fortifications, and churches in the city, the palace was designated a UNESCO World Heritage site in 1979.

label: Batalha
scope_note: Noted for the Battle of Aljubarrota that was fought near here in 1385, when John I of Portugal defeated John I of Castile & secured Portugal's independence; large Dominican abbey was built here to commemorate the victory, but was sacked by French in 1810.

label: Luzern
scope_note: Located on the W shore of Lake Lucerne, 25 m. SSW of Zurich. Former fishing village that evolved near an 8th century Benedictine monastery of St. Leodegar (Luciaria). Chartered as a city in 1180 and developed into important trade center after the St. Gotthard Pass opened route between the upper Rhine and Lombardy ca. 1230. Purchased by the Hapsburgs in 1291. Capital of the Helvetic Republic from 1798 to 1803. Site of a summer music festival since 1938.
wikidata_description: city at Lake Lucerne, in central Switzerland

label: Segovia
scope_note: Segovia was an Iberian settlement since ca. 700 BCE, falling to Roman control ca. 80 BCE. Segovia underwent Moorish occupation from early 8th century until its recapture by Alfonso VI in 1079. During the late 16th century the plague led to the city's decline, but revived during the age of railroad construction in the 19th century. An important historical site is the Roman-built Segovia aqueduct, well known as "El Puente." Other distinguished buildings include the Church of San Esteban, San Martín, La Trinidad, San Lorenzo, San Millán and the Alcázar, a palace for the royal family of Castile.

label: Seo de Urgel
scope_note: Town was built on the site of an older Iberian village; noted as seat of the bishop who has been joint prince of Andorra since 840 CE; today, the second prince of Andorra is the president of France.

label: Bernau bei Berlin
wikidata_description: German town in the Barnim district

label: Valenciennes
scope_note: Ruled by Charlemagne 811; part of Holy Roman Empire; passed to counts of Hainaut 1047; famous for lacemaking 15th cen.; taken by Louis XIV 1677; ceded to France 1678; besieged 1814; captured by Germans 1914-1918; birthplace of Jean Watteau 1684.

label: Compiègne
scope_note: Flourished duringthe Middle Ages; site of assemblies and councils under Merovingian kings; taken from duke of Burgundy by Charles VI in 1415; scene of capture of Joan of Arc by English in 1430; headquarters of Germany 1870-1871; site of noted 18th-century palace.

label: Melle
scope_note: Melle is located on left bank of Béronne river. The town's original name, "Metallum," derived from a lead mine during Roman times. Melle was one of the pilgrimage sites on route to the Cathedral of Santiago de Compostela, home of the shrine dedicated to Saint James, the patron saint of Spain. The symbol of Saint James, the scalloped shell, became the primary symbol representing pilgrims. French pilgrimage routes to Compostela tend to follow old Roman roads, many of which continued to be utilized as primary roads of communication during the Middle Ages. It was under the authority of the counts of Maine from the Middle Ages to the 16th century. Located in Melle are the Church of Saint-Savinien, the former Priory of Saint-Hilaire, and the former priory church of Saint-Pierre.

label: Ragusa
scope_note: Located in Iblei mountains above the gorge of the Irminio river; was recorded as important Greek center by 6th century BCE; was thriving late Roman center on major road; modern town grew up across a declivity from the ancient site.

label: Terni
scope_note: Located on Nera river; developed as ancient Umbrian town; was important Roman center, possibly birthplace of historian Tacitus and site of murder of Emperor Gallus in 253 CE; sacked in 6th-7th, and 12th centuries; went to Papacy in the 14th century; devastated in WW II.

label: 's-Gravenhage
scope_note: Originally located in woodland called Haghe ("hedge"), town grew around residence of counts of Holland. In 1248, Wilhelm II built a castle, which his successors have expanded into the present-day buildings. Grew economically in the late 14th century when the judiciary moved from Holland and Zeeland to the Hague and later it became the seat of the stadholders and the government under Maurice of Orange (1567-1625). At the turn of the 19th century, it became an important conference center and headquarters for many institutions, most notably the International Court of Justice of the United Nations.
wikidata_description: city and municipality in the Netherlands, seat of the Dutch government

label: Santo Domingo de la Calzada
scope_note: Santo Domingo de la Calzada was one of the pilgrimage sites on route to the Cathedral of Santiago de Compostela, home of the shrine dedicated to Saint James, the patron saint of Spain. The symbol of Saint James, the scalloped shell, became the primary symbol representing pilgrims. Most construction of pilgrimage routes in Spain began by the end of the 10th century. Located in Santo Domingo de la Calzada is an 11th-century bridge and the 12th-century Cathedral of Santo Domingo de la Calzada.

label: Altusried
wikidata_description: municipality in the district of Oberallgäu, Bavaria, Germany

label: Capua
scope_note: Founded 856 CE on site of ancient Casilinum; captured 1501 by Cesare Borgia; was one of the fortified defenses of the Kingdom of Naples; fell to Kingdom of Italy in 1860; scene of heavy fighting in World War II (October 1943).

label: Enna
scope_note: Ancient site of principal temple of Ceres (in mythology, her birthplace); headquarters of slaves in first Servile War 134-132 BC; captured by Saracens in 9th cen.; seat of an emirate in the 10th cen.; important Moslem center during Norman conquest.

label: Dormagen
scope_note: The small city of Dormagen is located about nine miles south of Düsseldorf in the northwestern German state of North Rhine-Westphalia. It is an active city with theaters, concert halls, an opera, and a local history museum. It produces chemicals, refined sugar, and rayon textile. The estimated population for 2004 was 63,600.

label: Bautzen
scope_note: The eastern German city of Bautzen is located on a granite elevation above the Spree river some 32 miles east northeast of Dresden. The site was first settled by Slavs under the name Budyšin, and was the location of the Peace of Bautzen between the German king Henry II and the Polish king Boleslaw I in 1018. It passed to Germany in 1033, then to Bohemia in 1319, and to Saxony in 1635. It became the capital of the Lusatian cities in 1346, and remains the cultural and political center for the western Slavic people called the Lusatian Sorbs (Wends) to this day. In 1813 a tremendous battle in which Napoleon's troops defeated a Russian-Prussian army was fought here. Surviving historic architecture includes the Ortenburg Castle built 1483-1486, and St. Peter's Church built between 1220 and 1497, which since 1523 has been shared by Protestants and Roman Catholics. The city's industries include textile, machinery, and electrotechnical equipment manufacture, papermaking, iron founding, and the production of vehicles .The calculated population for 2005 was 41,606.

label: Abbeville
scope_note: Town on the on the Somme River; during the 9th century was part of the abbey of Saint-Riquier. Noted as the site of early Paleolithic stone industry and is the type site for Abbevillian culture; town was founded as dependency of abbey of St. Riquier in the 9th century; ruled by England from 1272; site of marriage between Louis XII and Mary, sister of England's Henry VIII.

label: Árgos
scope_note: Founded by Pelasgian people in 2nd millenium BCE. is one of nation's most ancient cities; Mycenaean center from 1300 BCE; ruled by Dorians before 7th cen. BC; center of Achaean League after 146 BCE.

label: Reggio di Calabria
scope_note: Located on Strait of Messina; site having settlement origins in the Bronze and Iron Ages, Rhegion was eventually colonized by Chalcis in either 730 or 743 BCE; founded by Greeks as sister city to Zancle; destroyed by Dionysius of Syracuse in 387 BCE; allied with Rome 270 BCE; taken by Alaric (410 CE), Totila, Saracens, Pisans, Guiscard & Aragon (1282); often ravaged by earthquakes.

label: Civita Castellana
scope_note: Easternmost town of the tufa region of Etruria; chief city of the Faliscans, a people who considered themselves Etruscan although their language was akin to Latin; destroyed by Rome in 241 BCE, when its people were forced to move to Falerii Novi; the site was repopulated in the 8th century CE as a possession of the Roman Catholic Church; was made a city-state by Pope Gregory V in 998; passed to house of Savelli in 14th century.

label: Montecassino, Abbazia di
scope_note: Abbey founded by St. Benedict of Norcia, who died there. It was sacked by Lombards in 589, destroyed by Saracens in 884, and damaged by an earthquake in 1349. The monastery was rebuilt in the early 1500s, and the church was rebuilt and completed by 1727. It suffered more damage at the hands of the French in 1798, but was restored once again by Pope Pius VII. In 1806, it was secularized by Joseph Bonaparte, but nine years later, it was re-established. The abbey was reduced to ruins by Allied bombing in 1944, but has since been completely restored to its appearance after being rebuilt in 1727.

label: Sabbioneta
scope_note: Designed as the capital of his small duchy by Vespasiano Gonzaga Colonna duca di Sabbioneta; intended to be an example of an ideal city based on a grid system and balancing military and civil needs; named an UNESCO World Heritage Site along with Mantova as examples of Renaissance town planning.

label: Assisi
scope_note: Located on spur of Monte Subasio; was home to Umbrians (an Italic tribe) & Etruscans; later settled by Romans; site of feud of Dukes of Spoleto in Middle Ages; was independent commune in 12th cen., later part of the Papal States. Noted for large church and relics of St. Francis of Assisi. Was named UNESCO World Heritage Site in 2000.

label: Budapest
scope_note: Has the administrative status of a capital city.
wikidata_description: capital and largest city of Hungary

label: Tübingen
scope_note: The city of Tübingen is situated on the Neckar River at its junction with the Ammer and Steinach Rivers, in the state of Baden-Württemberg in southwestern Germany. The settlement grew around the castle of the counts palatine of Tübingen in the 11th century, and was first documented as a town in 1231. The town went to Württemberg in 1342, but changed hands among the Swabian League, Swedes, French, and Holy Roman Empire in the 17th century. Long renowned as a seat of learning, it was home to astronomer J Kepler, poet J Hölderllin, and philosopher G Hegel. The most notable of its historic structures is the Hohentübingen ducal castle, built in the 16th and 17th centuries and now housing several institutes belonging to the University of Tübingen. Modern industries include metal and machinery, textile, and paper manufactures. It is also a publishing center. The 2004 estimated population was 83,300.

label: Anagni
scope_note: First settlers, the Ernici, were defeated by Romans in 305 BC; was Roman civitas & later a municipium; was important bishopric; site where Pope Boniface was taken hostage by Philip IV of France in 1303 during struggles between papacy & heads of state.

label: Crema
scope_note: Located on Serio River; possibly of Celtic origin; sacked by Emperor Frederick I Barbarossa in 1159; fell to Visconti family 1338; under Milanese, Venetian, French & Austrian rule until Italian unfication 1860; site of Lombard Gothic cathedral 1284-1341.

label: Cáceres
scope_note: Located on low ridge S of Tagus river; founded as Roman town; taken by Moors 9th cen.; military Order of Santiago was founded here 1171; now comprises old upper town & modern lower town; noted for 15th-16th cen. churches & home of conquistador Juan Cano.

label: Enns
scope_note: Celtic settlement; Roman military camp (Lauriacum, later became modern town of Lorch on nearby separate site); chartered as city in 1212.

label: Heiligenkreuz
scope_note: Site of the oldest Cistercian Abbey in Austria, founded in 1133, and taking its name from a relic of the True Cross, presented to the abbey by an Austrian duke.

label: Bad Orb
wikidata_description: town in Main-Kinzig-Kreis in Hesse, Germany

label: Rasdorf
wikidata_description: municipality in Landkreis Fulda in Hesse, Germany

label: Schwerte
wikidata_description: town in the district of Unna, in North Rhine-Westphalia, Germany

label: Caen
scope_note: Important under the Norman dukes of the 10th and 11th centuries; captured by the English in 1346 and 1417-1450; prosperity was broken by revocation of Edict of Nantes in 1685 and city became Protestant; center for Girondist movement during Revolution; largely destroyed in World War II.

label: Saumur
scope_note: The town is located on rising ground between the Loire River and its tributary the Thouet, two miles above their confluence. The town occupies an island in the Loire and has spread to the right bank. It was the seat of the medieaval region of Saumurois. It grew up around a monastery and fort, built in the 10th century by the counts of Blois. It is noted as the site of the château of the dukes of Anjou, dating to the 14th century and strengthened with ramparts in the 16th century. The town today is known for a cavalry school and wines.

label: Avignon
scope_note: Conquered by Romans, Goths, Burgundians, Ostrogoths, and Franks; formerly part of Arles Kingdom; sold to Pope Clement VI by Joanna I of Naples 1348; seat of papacy 1309-1377 and Avignonese popes during Western Schism 1378-1417; became part of France 1791.

label: Frascati
scope_note: Located in Alban hills; town grew up around a villa; inhabitants of nearby Tusculum fled here when their city was destroyed in 1191; was papal possession in Middle Ages; has long been a favorite summer residence for Roman nobility; badly damaged in WW II.

label: Erice
scope_note: Originally settled by Elymi in Early Iron Age; part of Carthaginian Empire from 405 BC; contested by Greek Syracuse; taken by Epirus in 278 BC & destroyed by Carthage in Punic wars ca. 260 BC; went to Rome after First Punic War; thriving medieval center.

label: Kingston
scope_note: Located in SE Ontario; trading post and fort ruined by British in 1758; resettled by United Empire Loyalists in 1783; used as base for British naval force on Lake Ontario during War of 1812; produces ships, mining equipment and ceramics.

label: Fribourg
scope_note: Settled by Helvetii in ancient times and conquered by the Franks in 6th century CE. Modern town was founded by Berthold IV of Zähringen to protect a river ford in the 12th century. Ruled by various houses, including the Hapsburgs from 1277 to 1452. Center of Swiss Catholicism.
wikidata_description: capital of the canton of Fribourg in Switzerland

label: Stein am Rhein
wikidata_description: municipality in the canton of Schaffhausen, Switzerland

label: Höchst
scope_note: Located south of Frankfurt-am-Main; there is a town of the same name in Darmstadt.

label: Plauen
scope_note: The eastern German city of Plauen is situated on the slopes of the Weisse Elster river valley in the Vogtland. It was probably founded by Slavs in the 12th century, receiving its charter in 1220. It went to Bohemia in 1327, then to Saxony in 1466. It was the flourishing center of the textile industry in Saxony from the 15th century, and became famous for lace making. It was badly damaged in World War II. Surviving historic architecture includes the restored 12th-century Johanneskirche, the 1250 former castle of the Vögte, the imperial advocates who ruled the city in medieval times, now law courts, the old town hall rebuilt in 1548, and the Lutheran church built 1693-1708. Still famous for lace making, the modern city now produces a variety of textiles, has a mixture of heavy and light industries, and serves as a railway hub. The calculated population for 2005 was 69,378.

label: Saint-Guilhem-le-Désert
scope_note: Saint-Guilhem-le-Désert was one of the pilgrimage sites on route to the Cathedral of Santiago de Compostela, home of the shrine dedicated to Saint James, the patron saint of Spain. French pilgrimage routes to Compostela tend to follow old Roman roads, many of which continued to be utilized as primary roads of communication during the Middle Ages. Important historical structures located in Saint-Guilhem-le-Désert include the former Abbey-Church of Saint-Guihem and Saint-Sauvear, the village with several houses with Romanesque facades of the 12th century, and a bridge called the Pont du Diable.

label: Soissons
scope_note: Name derived from Suessiones, a Gaulish tribe; garrison town under Romans; seized by Clovis in 486; scene of Merovingian king Childeric III's deposition in 752; held by counts of Soissons under Capetian dynasty 987-1328; site of 12th- and 13th-century Gothic cathedral.

label: Fontainebleau
scope_note: Site of one of largest residences built by kings of France; palace is noted for work by famed artists; town was site of signing of Edict of Nantes by Louis XIV in 1685; became popular resort for Parisians in 19th century; scene of Napoleon's abdication in 1814.

label: Monte Sant'Angelo
scope_note: Located 27 miles NE of Foggia; site of the sanctuary of San Michele (founded 491 CE), built on site of cave where archangel Michael is said to have appeared to St. Laurentius, archbishop of Sipontum.

label: Enna
scope_note: Ancient site of principal temple of Ceres (in mythology, her birthplace); headquarters of slaves in first Servile War 134-132 BC; captured by Saracens in 9th cen.; seat of an emirate in the 10th cen.; important Moslem center during Norman conquest.

label: Solothurn
scope_note: Located on the Aare river.developing from a Roman settlement, it became a free town of the Holy Roman Empire in 1218. Admitted to the Swiss Confederation in 1481, itbecame an important cultural center in the 18th century. Residence of the Roman Catholic bishop of Basle since 1828.
wikidata_description: city in Switzerland, capital of its canton

label: Ljubljana
scope_note: Was strategic Roman city on road to Pannonia; ruined by Huns (451) & Magyars (900s); ruled by dukes of Carniola 12th cen.; under Otakar II of Bohemia 1270; went to Hapsburgs 1277; captured by French 1809, seat of Illyrian Provinces until 1813.

label: Langenselbold
wikidata_description: town in Main-Kinzig-Kreis in Hesse, Germany

label: Agen
scope_note: Aginnum was the capital of the Nitiobrigi, a Celtic people who settled on both sides of the Garonne; by the 4th century CE it had become the second city of Aquitania II.

label: Épinal
scope_note: Originally developed around a 10th-century monastery; passed to Charles VII, King of France 1422-1461; ceded to dukes of Lorraine in 1465; incorporated into France in 1766; became famous for producing colored picture prints in the 18th and 19th centuries.

label: Oxford
scope_note: City allegedly founded as a nunnery by Frideswide (died 735). Famous for the 12th-century Oxford University, the country's oldest; the first college, University College, dates from 1249. Oxford was first mentioned as a town in a Saxon chronicle dated 912. Headquarters of the Royalists during the 17th-century English Civil War. A center for auto production since 1918; noted for important sytems of canals and railways.

label: Nineveh
scope_note: Was an ancient city that succeeded Nimrud as the capital of the Neo-Assyrian Empire. It was made into a spectacular center by Sennacherib and developed into cultural center by Ashurbanipal in the 7th century BCE. A large library of cuneiform tablets was here. The city fell to Nabopolassar of Babylon in 612 BCE. The two main mound-ruins of Ninevah are known as Tell Nabi Yunus, and Kouyunjik.

label: Civita Castellana
scope_note: Easternmost town of the tufa region of Etruria; chief city of the Faliscans, a people who considered themselves Etruscan although their language was akin to Latin; destroyed by Rome in 241 BCE, when its people were forced to move to Falerii Novi; the site was repopulated in the 8th century CE as a possession of the Roman Catholic Church; was made a city-state by Pope Gregory V in 998; passed to house of Savelli in 14th century.

label: Loreto
scope_note: Located 15 miles S of Ancona; famous for the Casa Santa, said to be the house in which Jesus lived, brought by angels from Nazareth.

label: Girona
scope_note: Girona is situated near the Ońar River in the foothills of the Los Angeles mountains. The capital city of Girona province was taken by Muslims in 714 then recaptured by Franks under Charlemagne in 785. It fell again in 793 and was retaken by Louis of Aquitaine in 797 to later be brought into the kingdom of Aragón. Historic landmarks include the Gothic cathedral and Provincial Archaeological Museum.
wikidata_description: municipality and capital city of the Province of Girona, Catalonia, Spain

label: Feldkirch
scope_note: Developed in strategic location near the Arlberg Pass; was heavily fortified in Middle Ages; its count sold it to Austria in 1375; was famed for schools, particularly the Jesuit college founded in 1648; still noted for surviving medieval walls & castle.
wikidata_description: city in Feldkirch District, Vorarlberg, Austria

label: München
scope_note: Capital of Bavaria and the third-largest city in Germany; situated on both sides of the Isar River, north of the Alps. Henry the Lion, duke of Bavaria, established Munich in 1157 as a mint and market for Benedictine monks from Tegernsee. It suffered declined during the 17th century under the Swedish occupation and the plague epidemic of the Thirty Years' War. It revived under the Bavarian king Ludwig I, whose building and urban planning activities defined the character that the city has today. The city witnessed the rise to power of the Nazi party in the 1920s and 1930s, and was heavily damaged in World War II, when Allied bombing destroyed about 40% of its buildings. Still, a great deal of historic architecture survives, much of its rebuilt or restored, including the church the Frauenkirche, built 1468-1488. The city boasts seven old city gates, and many fine building built in the 19th century under Ludwig I. Munich is an active cultural center for the whole of Europe, with many libraries, theaters, museums, art galleries, and concert venues. It has several of the largest breweries in Germany and is renowned for its annual Oktoberfest celebrations. Light industry and tourism are major economic activities. The 2004 estimated population was 1,241,100.
wikidata_description: capital and most populous city of Bavaria, Germany

label: Osnabrück
scope_note: The city of Osnabrück is located on the canalized Hase River between Teutoburg Forest and Wiehengebirge in the Weser-Ems district of the northwestern German state of Lower Saxony. Charlemagne founded a bishopric here in 785 on an earlier Saxon settlement. It received its charter in 1171 and became a member of Hanseatic League, best known for its fine linen. It accepted the Reformation in 1543, but the Peace of Westphalia, signed there in 1648, declared that alternating bishops should be Protestant and Roman Catholic. The bishopric was secularized in 1803 and ceded to Hanover, but was re-established as Catholic again in 1858. It was heavily damaged in World War II, nevertheless some of its historic structures did survive, including the bishop's palace built 1667-90, the town hall built 1487-1512, and two Gothic churches, In 1970 was founded the University of Osnabrück there. The economic activities of the modern city include the manufacture of automotive equipment, machinery, textiles, paper, and chemicals. Locally there are saline springs and moated castles. The 2004 estimated population was 165,000.

label: Wittenberg
scope_note: Located on Elbe river; was medieval center; is famed as birthplace of Reformation, where Martin Luther nailed Theses to door of church in 1517; declined after Dresden replaced Wittenberg as capital of Saxony in 1547; went to Prussia in 1815.

label: Dhafní
scope_note: Noted for its great monastery, probably partially constructed with spoils from a Sanctuary of Apollo; also noted for a nearby cave where Pan & the nymphs were worshiped from 5th cen. BC.

label: Marsala
scope_note: Located on the western tip of island; was well-fortified outpost of Carthage, withstood attack of Pyrrhos in 267 BCE; went to Rome in 241 BCE; became famous in Britain for its wine in 18th century; Garibaldi landed here with 1000 "Red Shirt" volunteers in 1860.

label: Murcia
scope_note: Located at junction of Segura & Guadalentín rivers; trades in citrus fruits, almonds, cereals, olive oil & pepper; manufactured products include woolens, linen, cottons, leather, furniture & hats; famous for silk industry dating from Moorish era.

label: Hisarlık
scope_note: Hisarlık is believed to be the site of the Troy of Homer's Iliad. The settlement began as an Early Bronze Age citadel in the 3rd mill. BCE. Excavations reveal that several battles took place here, one apparently destroying the city ca. 1180 BCE, perhaps forming part of the cultural memory that was set down in the Iliad ca. 700 BCE. Shortly after the event of 1180 BCE, it was probably resettled by a population from the eastern Balkans. Greeks began moving into the area around Troy ca. 700 BCE. It was later ruled successively by Persia, Alexander the Great, Seleucid dynasty, Pergamum kingdom and Rome. It was finally a Byzantine settlement, and ultimately abandoned ca. 1350 CE.

label: Washington
scope_note: Coextensive with District of Columbia; located on swampy ground at navigational head of Potomac River; site was selected by 1st US president George Washington; city plan was laid out by French engineer Charles L'Enfant; burned in War of 1812, but rebuilt.
wikidata_description: capital city of the United States of America

label: Antwerpen
scope_note: The city of Antwerp is located on both sides of the Schelde River on a vast alluvial plain. Known to have been inhabited since the 2d century BCE, it has been important commercial center since the 12th century. It flourished in the 15th century under Philip the Good of Burgundy, when a famous academy of painting was founded there. It is noted as one of world's major seaports. Its population by a 2003 estimate is 450,000 and it is the second largest city in Belgium.
wikidata_description: municipality in the province of Antwerp, Belgium

label: Augsburg
scope_note: The city of Augsburg is located at the junction of the Wertach and Lech Rivers at the tip of the plain between them. It was the site of Bronze Age and Roman settlements, was destroyed by the Alemanni in the 5th century, then rebuilt by the Franks. It was a leading medieval commercial and banking center; and was an important site in the development of Lutheranism in the 16th century. It declined in power during the Thirty Years War and passed to Bavaria in 1806. The artists Hans Holbein, the Elder and the Younger, and Hans Burgkmair were born in the town. Augsburg is the administrative capital of the Bavarian district of Swabia. It was the site of a firestorm caused by bombardment in World War II and was severely damaged, but much of its historic architecture survived to be restored. The city is rich in Romanesque, Gothic, and Baroque buildings and fountains. It has a university founded in 1970, three colleges of music, and a technical college. In 1974, Augsburg annexed two neighboring cities, Göggingen and Haunstetten. It has grown to be a major site for heavy industry, chemicals, metal, and electrical plants. The 2004 estimated population was 260,600.

label: Herbstein
wikidata_description: town in Vogelsbergkreis in Hesse, Germany

label: Aachen
scope_note: The city of Aachen is located on the German frontier with Belgium and The Netherlands in the northwestern state of North Rhine-Westphalia. It was the site of Roman baths from the1st century BCE. It probably was birthplace of Charlemagne, who adopted the city as the second capital of the Holy Roman Empire and made it a center of learning and culture. From medieval times to the Reformation it served as the main coronation place of emperors and German kings. Destroyed in 881, it was rebuilt and in the late 12 century was fortified and obtained civic rights. It became a free imperial city around 1250. It began a decline in the 16th century, ceased to be the seat of imperial coronations in 1560, and was almost entirely burned in a great conflagration in 1656. It was the site of the signing of treaties to end the wars of Devolution in 1688 and of Austrian Succession in 1748. Annexed by France in 1801, it fell to Prussia by the Congress of Vienna in 1814-1815. Belgium occupied it briefly after World War I, and in World War II it was the first large German city to be taken by the Allies, in October 1944. Despite the bombing, much of its historic architecture has survived, in at least restored or rebuilt condition. Aachen Cathedral, a UNESCO World Heritage site, includes the famous Palatine Chapel of the Carolingian era, built between 790 and 805. Its choir and side chapels are Gothic. Notable medieval churches include St. Foillan's, St. Nicholas's, and St. Paul's, all of which began reconstruction right after being damaged. The town hall of around 1530 on the ruins of Charlemagne's palace and containing the wonderful Hall of the Emperors has also been restored. Culturally Aachen is am important city, with the Suermondt Ludwig Museum of Art in the market square, the international Newspaper Museum with examples of newspapers dating back to the 16th century, and many educational institutions, including the first university ever founded in Prussia (1870). The warmest ho springs in Germany are located in the suburb of Burtscheid. Aachen is also a center of industry and commerce, with nearly every type of heavy industry represented there. Goods such as chemicals, textiles, plastics, machinery, glass, electronics, and cosmetics are produced there. The estimated population for 2004 was 249,200.

label: Gelsenkirchen
scope_note: Located on Rhein-Herne-Kanal N of Essen, bisected by Emscher river; old village grew suddenly & annexed neighbors after coal mines opened in 1853; was bombed in WW II, though 3 old castles survived; city today is dominated by heavy industry.

label: Epídhavros
scope_note: Ancient site located on Saronic gulf, near modern Palaia Epidaurus; was an ancient seaport, noted as site of famous temple to Asclepius, Greek god of medicine & healing; habitation on this site was last recorded in the 6th cen. CE.

label: Acquapendente
wikidata_description: chief town of the homonym municipality

label: Empoli
scope_note: Located on lower Arno river; was active in medieval Florentine wars; famed for Ghibelline congress of 1260, where destruction of defeated Florence was successfully opposed (referred to in Dante's Inferno); was heavily damaged in WW II, but rebuilt.

label: Didyma
scope_note: Ancient temple sanctuary on W coast of Asia Minor, seat of oracle & cult of Apollo; 6th-cen. temple was destroyed by Persia in 494 BC; oracle & cult were restored under Alexander the Great after 334 BC; new temple was begun ca. 300 BC, but not completed.

label: Città di Castello
scope_note: Located on the Tiber river; was devastated by Totila the Goth; flourished under Vitelli family during the Renaissance, when much of the town's architecture was constructed; today town produces furniture, textiles, machinery & cement.

label: Strasbourg
scope_note: Strasbourg is the capital of the department of Bas-Rhin in the Alsace region of northeastern France. Strategically located on the Ill River, it was originally a Celtic settlement, then a Roman garrison town. In the 5th century it was sacked by Attila the Hun, then rebuilt by the Franks. The Oath of Strasbourg 842 between the eastern and western Frankish kings was taken there. It became a free city under the Holy Roman Empire. In 1681 it was seized by Louis XIV of France but retained many of its free city privileges until after the French Revolution. Germany and France alternated possession until finally in 1945 it reverted to France. It sustained significant damage in the Franco-German war of 1870-1871 and in World War II. The old city features a cathedral built between the 11th and 15th centuries, and the Châteay de Rohan, an episcopal palace now housing three museums. The modern industrial city of the 21st century is the seat of the assembly of the European Union.
wikidata_description: capital and largest city of Grand Est, located in the historical region of Alsace

label: Rouen
scope_note: Former center of the Rotomagi; invaded by Normans in the 9th century; occupied by England 1418-1449; site of trial and execution of Joan of Arc in 1431; taken by Huguenots 1562; held by Germany 1870; site of famous 13th-century Gothic cathedral damaged in World War II.

label: Lille
scope_note: Destroyed by Philip Augustus 1214, rebuilt by Joanna, Countess of Flanders; given to King of France 1312; passed to Burgundian possessions and recaptured by Louis XIV 1667; captured by Duke of Marlborough 1708; restored to France by Treaty of Utrecht 1713.
wikidata_description: city and commune in Nord, Hauts-de-France, Northern France

label: Menalaion
scope_note: Located three miles from Spárti; this was possibly the site of Homeric Sparta, since Menalaion was clearly the site of a major settlement contemporary with Homer's tale, and there are fewer contemporary remains at Spárti.

label: Benevento
scope_note: Located at confluence of Calore & Sabato rivers, on the site of Beneventum; founded by Samnites; later was important Roman town on Appian Way & base for their expansion in S Italy; destroyed by Totila the Ostrogoth in 452 CE; ruled by Lombards, Byzantines (11th cen.) & then pope.

label: Calvi Risorta
scope_note: Commune that is the site of an ancient city on the Via Latina, dating to late 7th cen. BCE; remained the city of the Ausones until the siege by Romans 334 BCE, after which it became a Latin colony (the 1st in Campania); recorded in the Late Republican period as a municipium.

label: Cividale del Friuli
scope_note: Located 9 miles ENE of Udine; was residence of patriarchs of Aquileia from 730-1238; fell to Venice in 1420.

label: Como
scope_note: On SW end of Lake Como; sacked by Milanese 1127; after 1335, ruled by Visconti & Sforzas of Milan; liberated & added to Kingdom of Italy by Garibaldi 1859; Mussolini arrested & executed here 1945; site of Santa Maria Maggiore cathedral (14th-18th cen.).

label: Caltanissetta
scope_note: A prehistoric and Greek settlement. Remains of huts of the Chalcolithic period, with Serraferlicchio, S. Ippolito, and Castellucio style pottery, have been found in the area of the present cemetery and in Sabucina on the San Giuliano mountain, which towers over the modern town.

label: Piazza Armerina
scope_note: Located on 3 hills in fertile farm area; territory has been inhabited since 8th-7th centuries BCE; was noted center during Greek, Roman, and Byzantine periods; expanded during 15th century to encompass nearby villages.

label: Chioggia
scope_note: Seaport on island in Venetian lagoon 15 miles S of Venice; supremacy of Venice over Genoa decided here in naval campaign 1379-1380.

label: Tall al-Ḥarīrī
scope_note: Ancient Mesopotamian city on right bank of Euphrates River; flourished throughout early dynastic period; was important artistic center, and was the commercial and political focus of western Asia by 1800 BCE; conquered by Hammurabi ca. 1700 BCE. Site of the Temple of Ishtar. Located on the west bank of the Euphrates River in present-day Syria. Its strategic location made Mari a very important city during ancient times.

label: Lienz
scope_note: Located on the Drava River, it is noted as a tourist resort.
wikidata_description: town in Lienz District, Tyrol, Austria

label: Šibenik
scope_note: Located on an estuary of the Krka River and the Adriatic Sea. The town grew up around St. Mihovil Castle. Venice and Hungary struggled to possess it until 1412. From 1797 to 1815, Šibenik was part of Napoleon's Illyrian Provinces, then later ruled by the Austro-Hungarian Empire. It was taken by Italy after WW I,  later becoming part of Yugoslavia, and later independent Croatia. The Cathedral of St James in the city was built from 1431-1535, and was designated a World Heritage Site by UNESCO in 2000.

label: Kastl
scope_note: This Kastl is one of two municipalities in Oberpfalz with this name.

label: Cuxhaven
scope_note: The city of Cuxhaven is located in Lower Saxony in northwestern Germany on the North Sea coast at the mouth of the Elbe River. It was an important medieval center. It was conquered by Hamburg in 1394 and served as its fore port until 1937. It received its charter only in 1907. Heavily damaged in World War I, it retains little historic architecture. It does have a 14th-century lighthouse, the oldest in Germany, and the 14th-century castle of Ritzebüttel, which now houses a museum. The city is a major fishing, fish processing, and shipbuilding port. It is also a noted beach resort and health spa. The 2004 estimated population was 53,000.

label: Bonn
scope_note: The German city of Bonn is located some fifteen miles south of Cologne on the Rhine river. Romans documented a river crossing here in the 1st century BCE, and occupied a fortress here from the 1st to the 5th century CE. It was a Frankish town from the 9th century, and from the 13th century was a prosperous town, the capital of the electorate and archbishopric of Cologne. It was occupied by the French from 1794, and then annexed to Prussia in 1815. In the 19th century it grew famous as a rich, fashionable cit y, remaining as such until World War II, when it was heavily damaged. From 1949 to 1990 it was the capital of West Germany and grew in size and importance, annexing several nearby towns in 1969. Efforts were made to preserve the residential look of the city and so only restricted light industry was allowed, Bonn is a cultural center, famed as the birthplace of the composer Ludwig van Beethoven. It has many musical institutions, including an orchestra, and hosts many national and international concerts, mainly in its modern concert hall, the Beethovenhalle. There are many private theaters and performance halls and a large municipal theater that hosts opera, drama, ballet, and musicals. There are two major museums. Its historic architecture includes a Romanesque basilica surmounted by five towers, and three old churches dating from the 10th, 11th, and 12th centuries respectively. There is also the former Electorate Palace, now the Rhenish Friedrich Wilhelm University of Bonn, founded 1786 and the Poppelsdorf Palace, which has botanical gardens. Generally the city is well provided with green open spaces and broad tree-lined streets. The estimated population for 2004 was 311,000.
wikidata_description: city in Germany and capital of former West Germany

label: Périgueux
scope_note: Périguex was an important Roman settlement of Gallic Petrocorii. In 730 it was sacked by Saracens and then by the Normans in 844. The medieval town developed around an abbey between the 5th and 14th centuries. It was one of the pilgrimage sites on route to the Cathedral of Santiago de Compostela, home of the shrine dedicated to Saint James, the patron saint of Spain. The present city was created in 1240 by the joining of La Cité and Puy-Saint-Front. It suffered as a Protestant stronghold during the 16th century. Périguex contains various Roman remains and Romanesque churches.

label: Yogyakarta
scope_note: Taken by Great Britain 1812; passed to Dutch 1816; governmental seat of Republic of Indonesia 1946-1949 despite occupation of Dutch troops December 1948-July 1949; known for its handtooled silver items, batik & leather products.

label: Monza
scope_note: Seat of Lombard kings during ancient times & Middle Ages; cathedral's iron crown used in coronations of Charlemagne, Charles V & Napoleon I; King Humbert I of Italy assassinated here in 1900; site of 13th-cen. town hall & palace of Lombard kings.

label: Macerata
scope_note: Located on hill between Chienti & Potenza rivers; ancient town was destroyed ca. 408 CE by Visigothic king Alaric; was a thriving commune in 12th cen.; went to Papal States ca. 1445. Located near the site of ancient Ricina.

label: Bari
scope_note: Began as important Roman colony & commercial center 2nd cen. BC; became Saracen stronghold 9th cen.; seat of Byzantine governor of Apulia 885; razed by William the Bad of Sicily 1156, but rebuilt under Frederick II (1220-1250); damaged by British WW II.
wikidata_description: Italian city, capital of the Apulia region

label: Aosta
scope_note: At junction of Great and Little St. Bernard passes; birthplace of St. Anselm, archbishop of Canterbury; became duchy in 1302; occupied by French several times in the 18th and 19th centuries; site of nearly intact Roman city walls, arch of Augustus, and amphitheater ruins.

label: Porto
scope_note: Town on ancient site, settled by Greeks or by Romans (scholars disagree). Controlled by Visigoths from ca. 540 CE; fell to Moors 716; retaken by Christians 997; birthplace of Henry the Navigator 1394; trading of port wine began 1678; captured by British troops under Duke of Wellington in 1809; is manufacturing & fishing center.

label: İstanbul
scope_note: The city was held by the Persian Empire in 512 BCE. Later was a Roman Republic free city. It was the seat of Constantine I's empire from 330, and the terminus of the ancient Silk Road trade route. Was declared a Christian city by Constantine. From the 6th-13th centuries, the city was attacked by Persians, Arabs, Bulgars and Russians, and eventually taken by the Fourth Crusade army in 1203. Later taken by Ottomans.
wikidata_description: city in Turkey located at the Bosporus Strait

label: Wiener Neustadt
scope_note: Located on the S edge of the Vienna basin, it was founded by the Badenbergs in 1194 as a frontier stronghold against the Hungarians. It was granted a municipal charter in 1277 and was an Imperial residence from 1452-1493.

label: Simmelsdorf
wikidata_description: municipality in Landkreis Nürnberger Land in Germany

label: Düren
scope_note: The small German city of Düren is situated on the Ruhr river in the foothills of the Eifel mountains some 18 miles east of Aachen. The site was probably first occupied by Romans. Pippin III the Short, king of the Franks, established a residence here and a town grew around it, documented first in 748. Pippin's son Charlemagne held diets here in 775 and 779. It was ruled by the dukes of Jülich from 1242, was burned to the ground by the army of the Emperor Charles V in 1543, was taken by France in 1801, and passed to Prussia in 1814. World War II saw it nearly totally destroyed by aerial bombardment, but it was rebuilt following the war. In the 1970s it grew rapidly due to its absorption of two nearby towns. Düren is an industrial center, producing glass, chemicals, metal wares, textiles, paper, and sugar. It is also a center of scientific research, with a botanical garden and an astronomical observatory. Its estimated population for 2004 was 93,000.

label: Dax
scope_note: Dax was one of the pilgrimage sites on route to the Cathedral of Santiago de Compostela, home of the shrine dedicated to Saint James, the patron saint of Spain. The symbol of Saint James, the scalloped shell, became the primary symbol representing pilgrims. French pilgrimage routes to Compostela tend to follow old Roman roads, many of which continued to be utilized as primary roads of communication during the Middle Ages. It was an ancient center for hot saline springs and mineral baths. Dax was a medieval capital of viscount of Béarn and the seat of an early bishop. Historic sites in Dax include ruins of city walls and the Cathedral of Notre-Dame.

label: Glasgow
scope_note: Country's largest city & site of early Industrial Revolution in 18th cen.; religious center founded by St. Kentigern in 550; American Revolution disrupted trade until shipbuilding & textile industries began; notorious slums disappeared during 1980s.

label: Conversano
scope_note: Peucete center with remains of megalithic walls & numerous tombs; during the Middle Ages, passed from the Byzantines to the Lombards; Norman castle & Romanesque cathedral (11th-12th cen.).

label: Viareggio
scope_note: Located on Ligurian Sea; Lucca constructed a wharf and fortification here in the 12th century; houses had been constricted in the area by the second half of the 15th century; was a commercial center by the late 16th century; developed as a spa center in the 19th century.

label: Worcester

label: Aswān
scope_note: Was thriving town 1st mill. BC; was home to colony of Jewish mercenaries in 5th cen. BC; served as frontier garrison post for Romans, Turks & British; today is popular winter resort; noted for ruins of temple by Ptolemy Euergetes & for Aswān High Dam.

label: Leoben

label: Arnsberg
scope_note: The city of Arnsberg, the capital of the district of Arnsberg in the west-central German state of Nordrhein-Westfalen, is located on a loop of the Ruhr River. Founded in 1077 at the site of a pre-existing castle, it served as the seat of the counts of Werlin from the 11th century, receiving its charter in 1238. It became a member of Hanseatic League, and the seat of the Westphalian Vehmir counts from the 15th century. It was the site of secret tribunals ("Vehmgericht") that usurped functions of the government. Notable for the ruins of the old Werlin castle and the church of Wedinghausen Abbey, it is a vacation resort and spa, known as the "Pearl of the Sauerland." Industries include brewing, paper milling, and the manufacture of metal products. The 2004 estimated population was 77,100.

label: Saarbrücken
scope_note: The German city of Saarbrücken is situated on the Saar river at the mouth of the Sulz, about 39 miles southeast of Trier. It was a Celtic and then a Roman river crossing, later settled by German Frankish kings who built a castle there in the 10th century. The town grew around the castle, and received its charter in 1321.The bishops of Metz and counts of Saarbrücken ruled it from the 14th century to 1793 when France invaded it and occupied it until it went to Prussia in 1815. With the industrial revolution it produced large amounts of coal, iron, and later steel. After World War I it became capital of the Saarland. It was bombed by the Allies in World War II, but has since been rebuilt and once again become a center of iron and steel industries. It also produces beer, cement, coal, and optical instruments. Surviving historic architecture includes a 13th-century Gothic church, an 18th-century castle, and an 18th-century town hall. It has a university founded in 1948. The calculated population for 2005 was 181,779.
wikidata_description: capital of the German state of Saarland

label: Mont-Saint-Michel
scope_note: Rocky islet off the coast of Normandy; site of a famous sanctuary; is cut off from the mainland at high tide; was heavily fortified and resisted sieges during the Hundred Years' War and Wars of Religion; established as a prison by Napoleon. Designated a World Heritage Site, along with the Bay, by UNESCO in 1979.

label: Senlis
scope_note: Charles VIII and Emperor Maximilian I signed a treaty here on 23 May 1493, by which Charles relinquished the Franche-Comté; site of early Gothic cathedral, 15th-century town hall and ruins of former royal residence.

label: Melfi
scope_note: Noted for 12th century cathedral and 13th century castle; has suffered destructive earthquakes.

label: Merano
scope_note: Located near site of Roman town of Castrum Maiense (ca. 5th cen. CE); comprises part of Tirol ceded to Italy from Austria 1918; noted for Gothic parish church (1367-1495) & Hapsburg residence Castello Principesco.

label: Bettona
scope_note: Was an ancient Umbrian center; later was a Roman municipium, & a free city-state during the Middle Ages; Etrusco-Umbrian remains include walls & artifacts from the necropolis.

label: Norcia
scope_note: Traces of human settlement in the area date back to the Neolithic Age. Was founded by ancient Sabines; colonized by Rome in 20 BCE; was birthplace of St. Benedict (born ca. 480 CE), founder of the Benedictine monastic movement; has survived several major earthquakes 18th-20th cen.

label: Treviso
scope_note: A Celtic & Roman town; center of Lombard duchy; site of important mint during Charlemagne's time; independent from 1020; under the Ghibelline leader Ezzelino da Romano 1237-1259; passed to Venice 1339, to French 1790s, to Austria 1815, to Italy 1866.

label: Kars

label: Houston
