label: Otterberg
scope_note: The western German town of Otter berg is located near Kaiserslautern. It was the site of an important Cistercian monastery in the 12th century. After the Reformation, the parish church was divided by an inner wall and used by both Roman Catholics and Lutherans. The 2005 population was calculated at 5237.

label: Nevers
scope_note: Nevers was one of the pilgrimage sites on route to the Cathedral of Santiago de Compostela, home of the shrine dedicated to Saint James, the patron saint of Spain. The symbol of Saint James, the scalloped shell, became the primary symbol representing pilgrims. French pilgrimage routes to Compostela tend to follow old Roman roads, many of which continued to be utilized as primary roads of communication during the Middle Ages. Nevers was constantly controlled by various powerful European families in the Middle Ages; for example, it was acquired by the Gonzaga family of Mantua in 1538 and later, in 1659, Nevers was given to the Mancini family by Cardinal Mazarin. Located in Nevers is the 11th-century Romanesque Cathedral of Saint-Cyr-et-Sainte-Julitte and many 13th-18th-century buildings.

label: Béziers
scope_note: Surrounded by old walls; has ancient Gallic fortress; captured by Romans 120 BC; a stronghold of viscounts of Carcassone 12th cen.; scene of massacre of 20,000 people for having harbored Albigenses 1209; seat of episcopal see until 1790.

label: Étampes
scope_note: Étampes evolved from the union of several other settlements. It is one of the pilgrimage sites on route to the Cathedral of Santiago de Compostela, home of the shrine dedicated to Saint James, the patron saint of Spain. The symbol of Saint James, the scalloped shell, became the primary symbol representing pilgrims. French pilgrimage routes to Compostela tend to follow old Roman roads, many of which continued to be utilized as primary roads of communication during the Middle Ages. Étampes lies along the Juine River, south of Paris. In the Middle Ages the city was a stronghold and preserved are several architectural remnants of those times. Étampes is now a commercial center with diversified industries.

label: Faistós
scope_note: Was a thriving ancient city; was site of an ancient Minoan palace; also flourished throughout Classical and Hellenistic periods.

label: Fondi
scope_note: Located on Appian Way near the Lago di Fondi; settlements here date to 1000 BCE; was a Volsci town; had limited Roman citizenship by 338 BCE; was papal property from 5th cen. BCE; sacked by Lombards in 592 CE & Saracens in 846 & 1534; held successively by several families in Middle Ages.

label: Genève
scope_note: Originally a fortified settlement of the Allobrogian Celts, it was conquered by the Romans and was part of Roman Gaul until it passed to the Burgundian kingdom and served as its capital from 443 to 534. John Calvin established a theocratic state in 1541 and made 16th Geneva the center of Protestant Europe. Annexed to France in 1798 and admitted to the ranks of Swiss cantons in 1814. From 1920 to 1946, it was the seat of the League of Nations, its building later taken over by the UN. Site of many international conferences dealing with political developments, most notably Vietnam in 1954 and Laos in 1962.
wikidata_description: city in Switzerland and capital of its canton

label: San Lorenzo de El Escorial
scope_note: Noted for elaborate monastery, palace, mausoleum and museum; Philip II built monastery 1563-1584 as memorial to victory over French in 1557; became his main residence; later was the dynastic center of the Spanish Hapsburgs.

label: Soria
scope_note: Soria is situated on the west bank of the Duero River.  Alfonso I, the Warrior of Aragon restored the town after invasion by Moors and was later passed on to Alfonso VII of Castile. The Museo Numantino contains significant Iberian and Roman objects from ruins of nearby Numantia. Romanesque historical sites include the churches of Santo Domingo and San Nicolás, the colegiata (collegiate church) de San Pedro, and the closter of the Convent of San Juan de Duero.

label: Székesfehérvár
scope_note: Strategically located in defensible hinterlands of swamps; Romans established a settlement on site of earlier Celtic village; Hungarian Stephen I made town fortified capital of kingdom in 10th cen.; destroyed by Turks in 17th cen. & by Nazis in 1945.

label: Wels
scope_note: Developed as a Roman military installation at an important crossroad; was the capital of the ancient province of Noricum.

label: Prenzlau
wikidata_description: town and administrative seat of Uckermark district, Brandenburg state, Germany

label: Bocholt
scope_note: The small northwestern German city of Bocholt is situated on the Aa river in a forest of beech trees near the German-Netherlands border. The bishop of M ünster chartered it in 1222. Its historic architecture includes the Gothic church of St. George built1415-1486, the Renaissance town hall of 1618-1621, which was restored in 1928-1934, and the two castles of Anholt and Gemen. The city was heavily damaged in World War II, but was rebuilt and has grown, particularly in the 1970s when it annexed a few neighboring towns and grew by more than 30%. It is a textile production center, especially for cotton, and manufactures machine work and iron goods. The population estimate for 2004 was 73,200.

label: Hamm
scope_note: The city of Hamm lies on the eastern edge of the German Ruhr industrial area, situated along the Lippe and Ahse Rivers and Lippe-Seiten Canal. Founded in 1226 as the capital of Mark countship, it was an influential member of the northern European mercantile union, the Hanseatic League, from 1417. It declined after the various wars of the 17th and 18th centuries, but revived with the19th-century industrial revolution, because of its proximity to coal mines and the development of heavy industries. It functioned as a traffic, supply, and power center in World War II, and was in consequence heavily bombed. Overhalf of its buildings were destroyed. Surviving historic structures include the medieval St. Paul's Church and the ruins of the 16th-century St. Agnes Church. The modern city is an important railway junction. Its industries include the manufacture of metal wire and cable chief among them. The 2004 estimated population was 185,200.

label: Andernach
scope_note: The German town of Andernach is situated on the left bank of the Rhine river some dozen miles northwest of Coblenz. Its location has historically been an important strategic site. The Romans built a large fortress here in 12 BCE. Here Charles the Bald, king of the West Franks, was defeated by Louis the Younger in 876 CE. The Holy Roman Emperor Otto I defeated his rebellious brother here in 939, and Lothair III defeated Henry V here in 1114. In 1253 it became a member of the Hanseatic League. The French army burned it in 1689, then occupied it in 1795. It was given to Prussia in 1815. In World War II the Allies took it in March 1945. The city today still has a 12th-century watchtower and a 13th-century parish church. The 2005 population estimate was 28,089.

label: Orléans
scope_note: Orléans is the capital of Loiret department and the Centre region in north-central France. Orléans was conquered by Julius Caesar in 52 BCE; many Roman ruins have been found here. It was the most important city in France after Paris during the 10th and 11th centuries and it was the center of the royal duchy established by Philip VI in 1344. Orléans was one of the pilgrimage sites on route to the Cathedral of Santiago de Compostela, home of the shrine dedicated to Saint James, the patron saint of Spain. The symbol of Saint James, the scalloped shell, became the primary symbol representing pilgrims. French pilgrimage routes to Compostela tend to follow old Roman roads, many of which continued to be utilized as primary roads of communication during the Middle Ages. Orléans is known as the city that was saved by the heroine Joan of Arc. An equestrian statue of Joan of Arc in the center of town and the large Gothic-style Cathedral of Sainte-Croix are historic landmarks.  Modern Orléans is a center for gardening and horticulture; it is particularly known for its roses. Other industries in Orléans include textiles, food processing, machinery manufacturing, and electrical engineering.
wikidata_description: large city and commune in Loiret, Centre-Val de Loire, France

label: Tours
scope_note: Tours is the capital of the Indre-et-Loire département, on the Loire River. It is the chief tourist centre for the Loire Valley and its historic châteaus. Tours offers sharp contrasts in buildings and architectural styles. Located in Tours is the cathedral of Saint-Gatien which sums up four centuries of French religious architecture: the choir is of the 13th century; the nave marks a transition between Flamboyant Gothic and Renaissance styles; the facade was built between 1426 to 1547. Tours was one of the pilgrimage sites on route to the Cathedral of Santiago de Compostela, home of the shrine dedicated to Saint James, the patron saint of Spain. The symbol of Saint James, the scalloped shell, became the primary symbol representing pilgrims. French pilgrimage routes to Compostela tend to follow old Roman roads, many of which continued to be utilized as primary roads of communication during the Middle Ages. Tours was a medieval center of learning and scene of the victory of Charles Martel over the Saracens in 732. Tours developed a prosperous silk industry in the 15th century. Its Musée des Beaux-Arts in the former 17th- to 18th-century archiepiscopal palace has an excellent collection of paintings. Tours entered the 1980s with strength due to its decentralization from the Paris region of machinery assembly, chemical products, and pharmaceutical industries. This was the birthplace of Balzac.

label: Thásos
scope_note: Located on north coast of island, looking across strait to the mainland; had 2 harbors, one was fortified; town was devoted to worship of Herakles even before the arrival of the Greeks.

label: Vólos

label: Merano
scope_note: Located near site of Roman town of Castrum Maiense (ca. 5th cen. CE); comprises part of Tirol ceded to Italy from Austria 1918; noted for Gothic parish church (1367-1495) & Hapsburg residence Castello Principesco.

label: Breda
scope_note: Originally an important fortress located at the confluence of the Mark and Aa rivers, it was ruled by family of Godfrey I from the 12th century until it was sold to Brabant in 1327. Important for its wool and cloth trade, it received a charter in 1252. It passed to the house of Nassau in 1404, then to William I of Orange. Occupied by Spaniards in 1590, recaptured by Prince Maurice of Orange, and then captured again by the Spanish general Spinola in 1625, the town's surrender was made famous by the Velásquez painting 'The Surrender of Breda' (ca. 1635). Expanded economically in the 19th century.

label: Neuchâtel
scope_note: Was thriving Burgundian town by 11th century. Served as the cultural, aristocratic, and  governmental center of the canton since the 12th century. Noted for its Gothic church and castle. Its renowned university was established here in 1838.

label: Bergama

label: Ludwigshafen
scope_note: The city of Ludwigshafen is a river port on the west bank of the Rhine in southwestern Germany. It serves as a gateway to the important Rhine valley wine-growing region. It was founded in 1606 under the name Rheinschanze as a bridgehead opposite the city of Mannheim, and was developed later by the Bavarian king, Ludwig I, after whom it was renamed in 1843. It received its city charter in 1859. It was the home of poet and dramatist F Schiller after his exile from Stuttgart. It was badly damaged in World War II and in a disastrous explosion of chemical plants in 1948. Its industry features the production of steel, machinery, and chemicals. It serves as a railway hub and a center of commercial river traffic following the opening of its harbor. It has become a center for sports since the construction of the Southwest Stadium in 1951. The 2005 population was calculated at 162,514.

label: Lübeck
scope_note: Located on Trave & Wakenitz rivers, near Baltic Sea; was seat of Slavic principality; German city founded by count of Holstein in 12th cen.; destroyed by fire, but rebuilt by Henry the Lion in 1159;
wikidata_description: city in Schleswig-Holstein in northern Germany

label: Piraeus
scope_note: The largest port in Greece, Piraeus was the mooring port for Athens by the 7th century BCE. It was fortified by Athenian naval commander Themistocles ca. 490, with walls connecting it to Athens. The modern city was badly damaged in World War II and rebuilt.

label: Rimini
scope_note: On Adriatic Sea at mouth of Marecchia river; recorded by Greek historian Strabo in 1st cen. BCE; became great Roman center, but sacked by Sulla; passed to Byzantines, Goths, Lombards and Franks; held by Malatesta family from 13th cen., by pope from 1509.

label: Cremona
scope_note: On the north bank of the Po River; Roman poet Virgil attended school here; sacked by Goths amd Huns in the 5th century; joined Lombard League in 1167; under Venetian rule 1499-1509, Spanish from 1535, and Austrian after 1707; noted for a museum of antique musical instruments.

label: Mantova
scope_note: On Minico River; Latin Poet Virgil born nearby 70 BC; Lombard League member 1167; contolled by Bonacolsi 1267-1328, Gonzagas 1328-1707 and by French 1797 until joining Kingdom of Italy 1866; site of Sant' Andrea cathedral begun by Alberti in 1472; named an UNESCO World Heritage Site along with Sabbioneta as examples of Renaissance town planning.

label: Lochstedt
scope_note: East Prussia.

label: Hofstetten bei Brienz
wikidata_description: municipality in the canton of Bern in Switzerland

label: Oviedo
scope_note: Oviedo is situated in northern Spain and lies 18 miles (29 km) southwest of Gijón. Oviedo is one of only a few medieval towns in Spain not to be conquered by Moors during the Middle Ages. Notable city landmarks include the cathedral, bishop's palace and the Convento de San Vicente. Economically, the city is primarily dependent upon coal and iron mining, as well as food processing.

label: Fulnek
scope_note: The town of Fulnek is situated in the region of Severomoravský in the Czech Republic at the historical border between the former margraviate of Moravia and Silesia. The place name was first mentioned in 1293. Its Gothic castle of the 13th century was rebuilt in the 17th century, and obtained its present appearance when it was rebuilt anew after a large fire in 1810. Other historic architecture includes the Renaissance houses and Baroque façades of Fulnek's central square, which suffered heavy damage in 1945 and were restored after World War II.

label: Opava
scope_note: The town of Opava is located northwest of Ostrava on the Opava River in the region of Severomoravský in the northeastern Czech Republic near the border with Poland. It was first mentioned in 1195, by the 14th century it was a principate under the king of Bohemia, and eventually became the capital of Austrian Silesia. It was the site of the signing of the Congress of Troppau between Prussian, Austrian, and Russian delegates after the Napoleonic Wars in 1820. It was damaged during World War II and lost much of its historic architecture. Surviving examples include the town-hall tower in the Upper Square; the restored 17th-century Church of St. George in the Lower Square, and the Gothic Church of St. Mary that had been built by Teutonic Knights. The economic activities of the modern town include the production of clothes, machinery, railroad cars, and foodstuffs. Its 2003 estimated population was 61,500.
wikidata_description: city in Opava District, Moravia-Silesian Region, the Czech Republic

label: Princeton
scope_note: Located on Millstone River, NE of Trenton; was founded near plantation established in 1681 by Captain Henry Greenland; thrived due to location along Philadelphia-New York stagecoach route & relocation of College of New Jersey here.
wikidata_description: municipality in Mercer County, New Jersey, United States

label: Rastatt

label: Potsdam
scope_note: The city of Potsdam is located where the Nuthe River flows into the Havel, in the district of Potsdam in the eastern German state of Brandenburg. Founded by Slavs in 993, it received its first charter in 1317. It became an important medieval center, and flourished from the 17th century as a cultural and military center of Prussia. Under Frederick II the Great (1740-1786) is became the Prussian royal residence and practically the capital of Prussia. Many Dutch immigrants arrived in the18th century and created a distinctive Dutch quarter. The city was badly damaged in World War II, but much historic architecture has survived. Important historic structures include the Rococo Sans Souci Palace, 1745-47, the Nicolai Church, 1830-37, and the Brandenburg Gate, 1770. The modern city boasts educational and scientific institutions, and healthy industries in bootbuilding, food processing, locomotive building, and textiles. The 2004 estimated population was 131,900.
wikidata_description: capital city of the German state of Brandenburg

label: Bad Camberg
wikidata_description: town in Landkreis Limburg-Weilburg in Hesse, Germany

label: Offenbach
scope_note: Located on left bank of canalized Main river, very near Frankfurt; was part of imperial forest of Dreieich; mint was established here in 1407; prospered with influx of craftsmen in 17th century. went to Hesse-Darmstadt in 1816; was severely damaged in WW II.

label: Salzgitter
scope_note: The city of Salzgitter is located in the foothills of the Harz Mountains southwest of Braunschweig in Lower Saxony in north-central Germany. Beneath it lies the largest deposit of iron ore in Germany. And in 1937 a state company for iron mining and melting, owned by Hermann Göting, was established. In 1942 the town of Salzgitter and 27 nearby villages were incorporated into a single entity, known until 1951 as Waterstedt-Salzgitter. The city expanded in the later 20th century to become a huge center of the metallurgical industry. It also plays a role in the transport of coal from the adjoining district. Its industries include the production of steel, railway cars, trucks, heavy machinery, television sets, radios, pharmaceuticals, and textiles. Salt has been extracted from the mineral springs at Bad-Salzgitter since 800 CE. The 2004 estimated population was 110,400.

label: Pärnu
scope_note: Located at the mouth of the Pärnu river; city was recorded as member of Hanseatic League in 1251; ruled successively by Teutonic Knights, Poles, Swedes & Russians; today economy is driven by tourist trade & light industry.

label: Chambord
scope_note: Village N of Blois, site of the famous Château de Chambord built by Francis I, the largest château on the Loire.

label: Chinon
scope_note: Town on the Vienne River; an important stronghold even before the arrival of the Romans; 3 fortresses built 11th-15th cen.; besieged by Philip II of France 1204-1205; site of first meeting of Joan of Arc & Charles VII.

label: Ajaccio
scope_note: The birthplace of Napoleon; original settlement of Ajax founded by Romans is nearby; town moved to present site by Genoese 1492; became part of France 1768; economy is largely supported by tourism, yet there is light industry & shipping.
wikidata_description: French commune and prefecture of Corse-du-Sud and Corsica

label: Montpellier
scope_note: Montpellier was one of the pilgrimage sites on route to the Cathedral of Santiago de Compostela. Montpellier was originally known in the 10th century for having two Bourgs called Montpellier and Montpellieret; they were seperate until the 14th century. It is famous for the terraced 17th- and 18th-century Promenade du Peyrou  which offers spectacular views. Montpellier is the site of the oldest Botanical Gardens in France which was founded by Henry IV in 1593. It has an important French paintings museum called the Fabre Museum and is the seat of International Vine and Wine Fair. Historic sites include city walls, early churches, and hospitals.

label: Moissac
scope_note: Moissac was one of the pilgrimage sites on route to the Cathedral of Santiago de Compostela, home of the shrine dedicated to Saint James, the patron saint of Spain. French pilgrimage routes to Compostela tend to follow old Roman roads, many of which continued to be utilized as primary roads of communication during the Middle Ages. This location is situated on what once was a strategic point of the main land and water routes in the mid-Garonne region connecting Toulouse to Bordeaux. Moissac is the site of the Benedictine abbey of Saint-Pierre-de-Moissac, which was consecrated in 1180 and the former parish church of Saint Martin.

label: Kos
scope_note: Located on NE coast of island; was an important settlement in ancient times; badly damaged in earthquakes of146 and 554 CE.

label: Ely
scope_note: Small cathedral city on high fenland; Saxons took their last stand against the Normans here; Etheldreda, daughter of the king of the E. Angles, founded a monastery here in 673; sacked by Danes in 870; rebuilt in the 12th century as an abbey and made a cathedral in 1109 when the diocese of Ely was created; famous octagonal tower completed in 1342.

label: Grado
scope_note: Located on a small island between the Laguna di Grado & the Adriatic; renowned commercial port during Roman period; seat of the patriarchate of Nova Aquileia ca. 570-1451, when title was given to Venice; site of 6th cen. cathedral.

label: Tarquinia
scope_note: Ancient site located adjacent to the modern town of Tarquinia. Legendary founder was Tarchon (Strabo: Geography V); reputedly the oldest Etruscan city in Italy; noted as earliest settlement in Etruria of the Villanovans; came under Rome probably by late 4th century BCE; gained Roman citizenship in 90 BCE; ancient site was abandoned in 8th or 9th century CE, when modern Corneto (since 1922 known as Tarquinia too) was founded nearby; named part of an UNESCO World Heritage site with Banditaccia.

label: Praglia, Monastero di
scope_note: Founded by the Maltraverso in 1080, under the direction of the Benedictine monk Isalberto de' Tadi; site of church of the Assunta, built 1490-1548 after a design by Tullio Lombardo.

label: Rovigo
scope_note: First mentioned in a document from Ravenna in 838, ruled by the House of Este until it passed to Venice in 1482 & to Austria after 1797; annexed to Italy in 1866.

label: Monte Carlo
scope_note: Located NE of Nice, France, on an escarpment at base of Maritime Alps along the French Riviera, across harbor from town of Monaco; famous resort, site of the Casino by Charles Garnier, built in 1878.

label: Arnhem
scope_note: Probably located on site of Roman settlement of Arenacum; chartered and fortified in 1233 by Otto II, count of Geldern; joined the Hanseatic League in 1443; as residence of dukes of Geldern, was often attacked by Burgundian rivals; refortified in the 18th century.
wikidata_description: city, municipality and capital of province Gelderland, the Netherlands

label: Locarno
scope_note: Site of prehistoric settlement; first documented in 789; possession of dukes of Milan from 1342, taken by Swiss in 1513; part of Ticino since 1803; noted for castle dating to 14th cen.; population is Catholic & language is Italian.
wikidata_description: municipality in the canton of Ticino in Switzerland

label: Lugano
scope_note: Possession of Milan, town was occupied by French in 1499, taken by Swiss in 1512; part of Ticino since 1803; was seat of bishop of Italian-speaking Switzerland from 1888.
wikidata_description: city in the canton of Ticino, Switzerland

label: Qanawat
scope_note: Historically noted as city of the Decapolis at the end of Hellenistic period.

label: Salzburg
scope_note: Located 71 miles ESE of Munich, Germany, the site was long visited as a source of salt, the name meaning "salt fort." Ancient city of Neolithic, Celtic, Roman, and early Christian origins.  A Benedictine abbey was founded in the 7th century and was the seat of an ecclesiastic principality from 1278-1803. Secularized and absorbed into Hapsburg Austria in 1816. Birthplace of Wolfgang Amadeus Mozart (1756-1791) and home of the Salzburg Festival, an annual event featuring both music and drama started in 1920. The Historic Centre of the City of Salzburg was designated a World History Site by UNESCO.
wikidata_description: eponymous capital city of the Austrian federal state of Salzburg

label: Eberswalde
scope_note: The city of Eberswalde is located in the Thorn-Eberswalder glacial valley, at a natural ford in the Finow River. The site has been settled since the 11th century BCE. The margraves of Brandenburg built a castle on the site of a Slavic fortification in the 13th century CE. An early center of industry thanks to the availability of waterpower and bog-iron and the canalization of the Finow River, it was settled and further developed by Thuringian cutlers in the 18th century, who brought their craft to their new city. In the 19th century arose the production of marine and industrial cranes, Europe's largest factory for which still exists and operates in Eberswalde. The city also boats a medical school, a forest research institute, and a museum. The 2004 estimated population was 42,600. In 1970 Eberswalde was merged with the settlement of Finow to create Eberswalde-Finow. In 1993 the name Eberswalde was restored.

label: Görlitz
scope_note: The eastern German city of Görlitz is situated on the Neisse river, across from the town of Zgorzelec, Poland, which was part of the city prior to World War II. The site was initially the Slav town of Gorelić, first recorded in 1071. It was ruled by Bohemia in the 13th century, was chartered in 1303, and was a member of the Federation of Lusatian Cities after 1346. It passed to Saxony in 1635, then to Prussia in 1815. Surviving historic architecture includes a medieval representation of the Holy Sepulcher, the ruins of a fortress built in the 14th century, the Church of Saints Peter and Paul built 1423-1497, and many houses built in the Baroque style. Görlitz attained its economic peak in medieval times with the local industry of fine textile production, which in the Baroque era also included the production of linen. Today it still has a textile industry, and also produces railway cars, electrotechnical products, woodworking, and machinery. It is the commercial center of the region of Upper Lusatia, and a railway junction that makes it the transport center of a major lignite production area. The calculated population for 2005 was 57,097.

label: Lautenbach
scope_note: The town of Lautenbach is located on the edge of the Black Forest in the district of Freiburg, Baden-Württemberg, Germany, near the city of Offenburg. It was an important town in medieval times. There are several places nearby with the same name.

label: Göttingen
scope_note: The city of Göttingen is located on the Leine River in Lower Saxony in north-central Germany. It is first mentioned under the name Guting in 953. Receiving its charter in 1211, it became a powerful member of the Hanseatic League in the 14th century. It sustained severe damage during the religious wars of the 16th and 17th centuries, but revived with the founding of the University of Göttingen, which soon became known of one of the best in Europe. The dismissal of seven professors (including J and K Grimm) in 1837 caused a sharp decline in its academic reputation and hence the prosperity of the city. Strong math and physics faculties eventually restored its good name in the late 19th century. The university's library has one of the finest collections in Europe and draws many visitors. Largely undamaged during World War II, the city retains much of its historic architecture, including whole streets of medieval half-timbered buildings, the city ramparts, and several Gothic churches. Its industries include tourism, the production of optical and precision instruments and printing. Its 2004 estimated population was 123,100.

label: Lüdenscheid
scope_note: The city of Lüdenscheid is located between the Lenne and Volme Rivers in the hilly, wooded Sauerland area of North Rhine-Westphalia. Franks settled the site by the 9th century. It served as a prosperous iron production center in medieval times, and joined the Hanseatic League. It fell under Brandenburgian rule in 1609, passed to Prussia in 1815. A large town-wide fire severely damaged it in 1723. It has an old town with a church tower dating from 1072 at its center, and the moated castle of Neuenhof. The city's economy is driven by industrial manufacture of plastics and synthetics, aluminum, and metal products. Its 2004 estimated population was 80,200.

label: Oberhausen
scope_note: The city of Oberhausen is situated on the Rhine-Herne-Canal in the industrial Ruhr district in the northwestern German state of North Rhine-Westphalia. It touches the borders of Mülheim to the south, Essen to the east, and Duisburg to the southwest. It grew up on the heath of Lipperheide as the hub of radiating rail lines, developed first in the mid-19th century, to service coal and limonite iron-ore fields. The beginning of the town was a railway station named after the old Oberhausen Castle nearby. It received its charter in 1874 and developed rapidly with the industrial activity at the turn of the 20th century. It annexed two neighboring towns in 1929. Historic architecture includes the Sterkrade Abbey built in 1150, Holten Fortress built in 1307, and the 16th-century moated castle of Vondern. The modern city connects to the Netherlands via autobahn lines. As the producer of steel and bituminous coal, it hosts much heavy industry, including the historic St. Anthony's Iron Works active 1758 to 1876, the first developed in the Ruhr district. Notable 20th-century structures include the town hall built in 1930, the main railway station of 1938, and the city hall built in 1962. Cultural institutions include several technical schools a civic theatre, and an art museum. There are a large thermoelectric plant, dye works, zinc refineries, railway workshops, and factories that produce glass, sugar, porcelain, team boilers, chemicals, and cigars. The population estimate for 2004 was 220,600.

label: Ratingen
scope_note: The city of Ratingen is located north of Düsseldorf in the northwestern German state of North Rhine-Westphalia. It was an important medieval town, and received its charter in 1276. Its historic old town center still survives. Today its local industry produces textiles, pottery, glass, tile, boilers, and machinery. The population estimate for 2004 was 92,500.

label: Elne
scope_note: Surrounding countryside has been occupied since Neolithic times. Elne was an Iberian oppidum or fortified town. Scene of the murder of the Emperor Constans, youngest son of Constantine the Great, in 350 CE; he was killed by soldiers of Magnentius, who succeeded him as emperor.

label: Meaux
scope_note: Located in important agricultural region; has been an agricultural market center since medieval times; belonged to counts of Champagne 923-1361; was first diocese in France to shelter Reformers during Wars of Religion in late 16th cen.

label: Sutri
scope_note: Important Etruscan center; became Roman ally 391 BCE; 380 BCE reconquered by Etruscans, who were driven out by Furius Camillus on the same day (hence the saying 'ire Sutrium,' to indicate an undertaking quickly achieved). Noted for an Etruscan necropolis and Roman amphitheater excavated in the tuff rock.

label: Zagreb
scope_note: Located on Sava River; is largest city in nation; old town consists of two medieval settlements which were rivals until 19th cen.; Mongols invaded in 1241-1242; was chief city of Croatia & Slovonia in 13th cen., later became a province of Hungary.

label: Zadar
scope_note: Located on end of a low level peninsula in N Dalmatia; withstood many attacks by Turks; was most heavily fortified town in Adriatic until 19th cen.; held by Austria, France & Italy; damaged in WW II; in 1944 became part of Yugoslavia.
wikidata_description: city and settlement in Zadar County, Croatia

label: Delft
scope_note: Located on the canalized Schie River, it was founded in the 11th century and granted a charter in 1246. Severely damaged twice, once by a fire in 1536 and then by an explosion in 1654. It was rebuilt and became a thriving commercial center in the 16th and 17th centuries. It is known for its cloth, breweries, and faience delftware (tin-glazed earthenware), but it was later superceded by Rotterdam. In 1584, William of Orange was murdered here on the orders of Philip II of Spain. Birthplace of artist Jan Vermeer (1632-1675).
wikidata_description: city and municipality in the Netherlands

label: Kołobrzeg
scope_note: Located on Gulf of Pomerania; became a commercial center in 13th century; seized by Brandenburg in 1648 and during Seven Years' War; taken by Russia in 1761; almost destroyed in World War II; present-day city is completely reconstructed and modernized.

label: Braga
scope_note: Large city  on an ancient site. Probably founded by Carthaginians. Held by Suebi in 5th cen. CE, by Visigoths from 585 & Moors 716; former seat of Primate of All Spain; notable structures include 12th-cen. cathedral (reconstructed in 16th cen. in Manueline style), 17th-cen. church of Santa Cruz & 18th-cen. Raio Palace.

label: Calahorra
scope_note: SE of Logroño city; known for its resistance to Roman general Pompey 76-72 BC; birthplace of Roman rhetorician Quintilian 1st cen.; controlled by Moors 9th-10th cen.; captured by Christian king of Navarre 1054; Roman ruins lie near the town.

label: Estella
scope_note: Estella was one of the pilgrimage sites on route to the Cathedral of Santiago de Compostela, home of the shrine dedicated to Saint James, the patron saint of Spain. The symbol of Saint James, the scalloped shell, became the primary symbol representing pilgrims. Various pilgrimage routes in the autonomous communities of Aragon, Navarre, and León correspond to old Roman roads built in the northern portion of the Iberian Peninsula. In 1090, King Sancho of Spain founded this town exclusively for settlers of French origin and for pilgrimage crossing. Historic sites in Estella include the churches of San Miguel, San Juan Bautista, Nuestra Señora del Puy, San Salvador del Arenal, Santa María del Castillo, San Nicolás, and Nuestra Señora de Rocamadour. There are also the parish churches of San Pedro de Lizarra, Santo Sepulcro, and San Pedro de la Rúa. The Chapel of San Martin, the Palacio Real, the Puente de la Cárcel, and the Puente de San Martin are also here.

label: Tell Halaf
scope_note: Archaeological site of ancient Mesopotamia; became Aramaean town 1000 BC; destroyed by Adad-nirari III of Assyria 808 BC, when area became a province of the Assyrian Empire; mentioned in the Old Testament as a place to which Israelites were deported.

label: New Haven
scope_note: Located on Quinnipiac River in S central Connecticut; in 1643 merged with neighboring areas to form New Haven Colony; in 1664 merged with chartered Connecticut Colony; was co-capital with Hartford 1701-1875; sided with British during American Revolution.

label: San Francisco
scope_note: Located on peninsula between San Francisco Bay and Pacific ocean; was site of mission and fort, then village of Yerba Buena; under Mexican control after 1821; captured by US in 1846; destroyed by earthquake & fires in 1906; important port during WW II.

label: Bamberg
scope_note: Bamberg is a city in Oberbayern, Bavaria, located on the canalized Regnitz River just above its confluence with the Main. Historically, it was the ancestral seat of the Babenberg family from 10th century. It was a medieval trade center; and the first book in German was published here in 1459. It passed to Bavaria in 1802. The city has much historic architecture, including two bishop's palaces, a former Benedictine abbey, the St. Michael's Church that was consecrated in 1015, and the Imperial Cathedral, built in 1004. Modern economic activities include the production of electrical equipment, shoes, pianos, and porcelain, along with brewing and market gardening. The 2004 estimated population was 70,100.

label: Emden
scope_note: The city of Emden is located at mouth of Ems River, on the North Sea in the northern German state of Lower Saxony. Founded about 800 CE, it developed as a port for trade with the Baltic countries, and dominated Ems trade by the 15th century. It became the center for Dutch-German trade and a haven for Calvinist refugees during the Dutch war of independence in the 16th century. With a manmade change in the course of the Ems River that moved its estuary farther from Emden, the city's trade and prosperity declined. It was heavily bombed in World War II, but the port facilities escaped major damage. Some other surviving structures include the remains built in 1616, the Late Gothic Great Church of 1648, the 16th-century town hall, and the 17th-century East Friesland Museum. After the end of World War II the city grew and thrived again, becoming one of Germany's busiest ports. Major economic activities include shipbuilding, herring fishing, oil refining, and heavy industry. The 2004 estimated population was 51,500.
wikidata_description: biggest city in East Friesland, Lower Saxony, Germany

label: Lescar
scope_note: Lescar was one of the pilgrimage sites on route to the Cathedral of Santiago de Compostela, home of the shrine dedicated to Saint James, the patron saint of Spain. The symbol of Saint James, the scalloped shell, became the primary symbol representing pilgrims. French pilgrimage routes to Compostela tend to follow old Roman roads, many of which continued to be utilized as primary roads of communication during the Middle Ages. The former Cathedral of Notre-Dame is a noteworthy historic site here; construction on the current church began around 1125.  Lescar was one of the pilgrimage sites on route to the Cathedral of Santiago de Compostela, home of the shrine dedicated to Saint James, the patron saint of Spain. French pilgrimage routes to Compostela tend to follow old Roman roads, many of which continued to be utilized as primary roads of communication during the Middle Ages. Located in Lescar is the former Cathedral of Notre-Dame which was begun around 1125 and  was mostly finished around 1141. The building was destroyed in the 16th century and restored in the 19th century.

label: Saint-Pierre-le-Moûtier
scope_note: Saint-Pierre-le-Moûtier was one of the pilgrimage sites on route to the Cathedral of Santiago de Compostela, home of the shrine dedicated to Saint James, the patron saint of Spain. The symbol of Saint James, the scalloped shell, became the primary symbol representing pilgrims. French pilgrimage routes to Compostela tend to follow old Roman roads, many of which continued to be utilized as primary roads of communication during the Middle Ages. Located in Saint-Pierre-le-Moûtier is the former priory church of Saint-Pierre.

label: Évreux
scope_note: One of oldest towns in France; flourished during Gallo-Roman period; taken from Romans by Clovis; sacked or burned down five times 5th-14th centuries; site of one of largest cathedrals in France; alternated between English and French control in the 15th century.

label: Rodez
scope_note: Scene of struggle between bishops of Rodez & counts of Rouergue; a double wall was built between the 2 hostile parts; site of 13th/16th-cen. Gothic cathedral; Catholic stronghold during Wars of Religion 16th cen.

label: Angoulême
scope_note: Captured from Visigoths by Clovis, King of Franks 507; fought over by the French and English in the Hundred Years' War; ceded to England in 1360; restored to France in 1373; passed to the house of Orléans in 1394; united to crown in 1714; site of cathedral of Saint-Pierre.

label: Fréjus
scope_note: An ancient naval base; site of many Roman ruins including a 3rd-century amphitheater, aqueduct, and ancient fortifications; has 13th-century cathedral and 5th-century baptistry; birthplace of Roman poet Gaius Cornelius Gallus; was damaged in the flood of 1959.

label: Kallithéa
scope_note: When modern city was constructed, cemetery from 8th cen. BC was discovered on this site.

label: Castellammare di Stabia
scope_note: Located on Bay of Naples; revolted against Rome in social wars of 90 BCE, sacked by Sulla; luxurious Roman villas were built here; was destroyed by eruption of Vesuvius (with Pompeii and  Herculaneum) in 79 CE; modern town grew just to SW of ancient site.

label: Sessa Aurunca
scope_note: Leading city of the Aurunci, an ancient Italic tribe; later became a Roman municipium & an Augustan colony.

label: Monza
scope_note: Seat of Lombard kings during ancient times & Middle Ages; cathedral's iron crown used in coronations of Charlemagne, Charles V & Napoleon I; King Humbert I of Italy assassinated here in 1900; site of 13th-cen. town hall & palace of Lombard kings.

label: Loreto
scope_note: Located 15 miles S of Ancona; famous for the Casa Santa, said to be the house in which Jesus lived, brought by angels from Nazareth.

label: Grosseto
scope_note: Located on low-lying Maremma coastal plain near Ombrone river; site was once in a shallow gulf, now the marshy desert Maremma; was plagued by malaria until the marsh was drained. The origins of the town can be traced back to the High Middle Ages; it is noted for 13th-cen. Gothic cathedral, fortified citadel & Etruscan museum, having artifacts from nearby Rusellae.

label: Poreč
scope_note: Located on Istria peninsula adjacent to Adriatic Sea. Poreč was mentioned by Livy in battles between the Romans and Histri (178-177 BCE). Tiberius made the city Colonia Iulia Parentium. Before 1947, the city belonged to Italy, then later Yugoslavia, and finally independent Croatia. The city is the site of the 6th-century Euphrasian Basilica. The "Episcopal Complex of the Euphrasian Basilica in the Historic Centre of Poreč" was designated a World Heritage Site by UNESCO in 1997.

label: Gouda
scope_note: Located at the confluence of the Gouwe and IJssel rivers in fertile polder district (reclaimed land). It  was granted a charter in 1272, and was the center of medieval cloth trade. It was also noted for its clay pipes during the 17th and 18th centuries. Famous for Gouda cheese and weekly cheese market.

label: Gdańsk
scope_note: One of nation's oldest cities; seized by Teutonic Knights in 1308; prospered until Swedish wars in 17th century; seized by Prussia in 1772; free city in 1807 and 1919-1939; site of Hitler's 1 September 1939 invasion of Poland.
wikidata_description: city and capital of the Pomeranian Voivodeship on the Baltic coast of northern Poland

label: Hauterive
scope_note: Noted for former abbey, dating from 12th cen.; site of a hydroelectric plant.

label: Al-Bara
wikidata_description: one of the former "Dead Cities" in northwestern Syria

label: Znojmo
wikidata_description: major town in the South Moravian Region of the Czech Republic

label: Zalaegerszeg
scope_note: Located on right bank of Zala river, in area noted for peculiarities of its dialect; served as frontier fort during Turkish wars of 16th-17th cen., & was never occupied by Turks; noted today for important architecture, including Baroque church.

label: United States
scope_note: Settled 40,000 years ago by ancestors of Amerindians; diverse cultures developed; Spanish, French, British and others settled the region from 16th century, native cultures were largely destroyed. The nation expanded westward throughout the 19th century; had Civil War in 1860s; There is no official language of the United States, though English is the most widely spoken and an official language of 31 states as of 2024.
wikidata_description: country located primarily in North America

label: Sarasota
scope_note: Resort city in W central Florida on Sarasota Bay; around 1910 Chicago socialite Mrs. Potter Palmer promoted tourism & built a ranch here; in 1927 John Ringling chose site as winter headquarters for the Ringling Bros. & Barnum & Bailey Circus.

label: Deutschland
scope_note: The area of north-central Europe occupied by what is now modern Germany measures some 137,828 square miles in size. Teutons, Celts, Slavs, and Balts inhabited it by the first century BCE. Part of the area was ruled by Romans, then Carolingians. Through the centuries, it was often broken into various states based on ethnic groups including the Alemanni, Bavarians, Upper and Lower Franks, Thuringians, and Frisians. It undertook expansion during the 19th to mid-20th centuries. The official language is German, although Low German is still spoken in the rural North. The 2004 estimated population was 82,633,200.

label: Homberg
wikidata_description: town in Vogelsbergkreis in Hesse, Germany

label: Wiesbaden
scope_note: Located on the Rhein River W of Frankfurt; famed for thermal springs since Roman times; was site of Franconian palace by 9th century. was important medieval center; ruled by Nassau from 13th century. went to Prussia in 1866; was bombed in WW II.
wikidata_description: capital of the German state of Hesse

label: Wolfenbüttel
scope_note: The city of Wolfenbüttel is situated on the Oker River in the district of Braunschweig in Lower Saxony in north-central Germany. The town grew around a castle that became the Guelph (Welf) dukes' residence in the 13th century. It was captured by the Protestant Schmalkaldic League in 1542; went to Braunschweig in 1753. The old town contains the castle residence of the dukes of Braunschweig-Wolfenbüttel and the Church of St, Mary, built 1604-23. There are also many Renaissance and Baroque half-timbered houses. The ducal Herzog-August Library contains a large collection of medieval manuscripts. The ducal librarians have included such notable people as the philosopher Leibnitz and the playwright Gotthold Lessing. The modern city's industries include canning, the production of chemical and musical equipment, and agricultural machinery. The 2004 estimated population was 54,800.

label: Mainz
scope_note: The city of Mainz, the capitol of the German state of Rhineland-Palatinate, is located on the Rhine river at the mouth of the Main river, some 20 miles west southwest of Frankfurt am Main. Originally a Celtic settlement, a Roman military camp was founded here by the Roman general Drusus 14-9 BCE. It became self-governing from 1118 to 1462, when a rebellion caused it to lose its free city privileges, and the leader of the league of Rhenish towns from 1254. It was a French possession from 1797 to 1815, and occupied by the French army from 1918 to 1930. It was almost totally destroyed in World War II, but has been rebuilt. Surviving historic architecture includes an 11th-century Romanesque cathedral, a 17th-century elector's palace, and a 19th-century German fortress built on the site of the old Roman military post. Mainz had a university from 1477 to 1816, but a new one, the Johannes Gutenberg University, it in 1946, honoring its native son who invented movable type here. The city is an educational center, with the Max Planck Institute for Chemistry, the Institute for Economic Research, and the Academy of Sciences and Literature. There are many museums of art, history, and natural history, the Gutenberg Museum among them. The city's economic activities include the wine trade for the Rhineland, the manufacture of pharmaceuticals and other chemicals, machinery, glassware, and musical instruments. It is known for its wine and pre-Lenten festivals. The 2005 population was calculated at 187,940.
wikidata_description: capital of the federal state Rhineland-Palatinate, Germany

label: Suhl
scope_note: Located on the Lauter river in the Thüringer forest; was medieval center; went to Prussia in 1815; produces motorcycles, machinery, sporting guns, electrical appliances, tools, porcelain, and toys.

label: Mulhouse
scope_note: Mulhouse is an industrial city located on the plain of Alsace between the Jura and the Vosges Mountains, situated on the Ill River and on the Canal du Rhône au Rhin. It History first mentions it in the ninth century, and it became a free imperial city in 1308. It allied itself with the Swiss in the 16th century, joined the French Republic 1798; was taken by Germany 1871, and was restored to France in 1918. It was the founding place of a model workingmen's colony in 1853. Its notable architecture includes a 16th-century town hall, a 19th-century Protestant church that has original 14th century stained glass windows, and the restored 13th-century St. John Chapel. Its commercial products include organic chemicals, pharmaceuticals, machine tools, and electrical apparatus.

label: Bordeaux
scope_note: Bordeaux was the chief town of the Celtic group named Bituriges Vivisci. It was taken by Goths and Normans and later passed to King Louis VII of France. England took control of Bordeaux between the years of 1154 and 1451. Bordeaux was one of the pilgrimage sites on route to the Cathedral of Santiago de Compostela. French pilgrimage routes to Compostela tend to follow old Roman roads, many of which continued to be utilized as primary roads of communication during the Middle Ages. Bordeaux was a Girondist center during the French Revolution. It is famous for producing red and white wines and for its various important medieval structures.
wikidata_description: city and commune in Gironde, New Aquitaine, France

label: Gargilesse-Dampierre
scope_note: Gargilesse-Dampierre was one of the pilgrimage sites on route to the Cathedral of Santiago de Compostela, home of the shrine dedicated to Saint James, the patron saint of Spain. The symbol of Saint James, the scalloped shell, became the primary symbol representing pilgrims. French pilgrimage routes to Compostela tend to follow old Roman roads, many of which continued to be utilized as primary roads of communication during the Middle Ages. Located in Gargilesse-Dampierre is the Church of Notre-Dame which was originally the chapel of a castle. The church is dated to the 12th century and is constructed of limestone on granite bedrock.

label: Vincennes
scope_note: Suburb E of Paris, site of famous 14th-cen. chateau where Henry V of England died in 1422; the chateau served as a state prison during the 17th & 18th cen.

label: Náfplio
scope_note: Ancient city was constructed on Mycenaean foundations; mentioned in Homeric legends; fell to Argos in 7th cen.; site was deserted by 2nd cen. CE but later re-settled; was Venetian (11th cen.), Crusader, then Turkish.

label: Trieste
scope_note: Most important seaport of N Adriatic; ruled by Venice 1202, by Austria 1382; given to Italy in Treaty of Rapallo 1920; seized by Nazis 1943; made a Free Territory 1947, but zones of city were divided with Yugoslavia; entire city restored to Italy 1954.
wikidata_description: city and seaport in northeastern Italy

label: Novara
scope_note: Located on the Agogna river; was founded by Caesar on site of Celtic settlement; destroyed in 5th cen., but rebuilt in 6th cen.; burned by emperor Henry V in 1110; in Lombard League by 1167; ruled by Milan, then went to Austria 1714, to Savoy in 1738.

label: Gela
scope_note: Founded by Greek colonists from Rhodes & Crete in 689 BCE; flourished under Hippocrates; was home of poet Aeschylus; ruined by Carthaginians, rebuilt by Timoleon 340 BCE, but destroyed again in 282 BCE; modern city was site of American landings in WW II.

label: Trento
scope_note: On Adige River; was Roman military base; seat of Lombard duchy 6th cen.; passed to Austria 16th cen.; site of Council of Trent (1545-1563) where doctrines of Catholic Reformation were established; passed to Italy 1918 & badly flooded 1966.
wikidata_description: Italian city in the North-East of the country

label: Auckland
scope_note: Largest city & former capital (replaced by Wellington); principal port; monuments include City Art Gallery, War Memorial Museum (houses large collection of Maori artifacts); has largest concentration Maoris in nation, & large Polynesian population.
wikidata_description: city on the North Island, New Zealand

label: Schaffhausen
scope_note: Count Eberhard III of Nellenburg founded Benedictine monastery dedicated to All Saints here in 1049. It became a free imperial city ca. 1190, but came under Hapsburg domination from 1330 to1415. Present day town is predominantly Protestant and the language is German.
wikidata_description: Swiss city, capital of the canton of Schaffhausen

label: Laguardia
scope_note: home to archaeologically significant dolmens, or Neolithic burial mounds

label: Mérida
scope_note: Mérida, located in the province of Badajoz and the autonomous community of Extremadura, was founded by Romans in 25 BCE as Augusta Emerita. It was the capital of the Roman province Lusitania that encompassed modern Portugal. Mérida flourished under Visigoths in the 7th century and was later occupied by Moors in 713.  In 1228, Alfonso IX took over Mérida and gave it to the Knights of Santiago. Roman ruins include temples, bridges, theater, circus, and aqueduct. Mérida's economy is based on agricultural trade and tourism.

label: Imst
wikidata_description: town in Imst District, Tyrol, Austria

label: Baumburg
scope_note: The town of Baumburg in Upper Bavaria in southeastern Germany is located near the town of Altenmarkt. It grew up around the famous Augustinian monastery founded there in the 12th century.

label: Legau
wikidata_description: market municipality in the district of Unterallgäu, Bavaria, Germany

label: Schenklengsfeld
wikidata_description: municipality in Landkreis Hersfeld-Rotenburg in Hesse, Germany

label: Rheda-Wiedenbrück
wikidata_description: town in the district of Gütersloh, in North Rhine-Westphalia, Germany

label: Bad Kreuznach
scope_note: The western German town of Bad Kreuznach is situated on the Nahe river. It was the site of Roman and Celtic fortresses, and a Carolingian palace was built there in 819. The bishops of Speyer ruled it from 1065, then the counts of Sponheim were in power here from 1241. It received its town charter in 1290. It sustained heavy damage during the Thirty Years War of the 16th to the 17th century. In 1689 the French destroyed it. It was ceded to Prussia in 1815. Due to its mineral springs, it became a popular spa in the 19th century. Today it remains a well-known health resort and does a thriving commerce in wine. The 2005 population estimate was 43, 319.

label: France
scope_note: Area inhabited by Lower Paleolithic; Celt-speaking Gauls dominated by 5th century BCE; part of Roman Empire 125 BCE-5th century, then under Frankish influence; lost land to England 12th-16th centuries; monarchy fell in Revolution 1792; recurring expansion 16-19th centuries; official language is French, though Provençal, Breton, Flemish, Catalan, Corsican, Basque, and Germanic regional patois are also spoken.

label: Châteauroux
scope_note: Name derived from Chasteau Raoulx, a fortress built during end of 10th cen. by prince of Déols; site of 10th-cen. castle; site of 18th-cen. mansion housing Napoleonic collections; manufactures metal equipment, chemicals, paper, textiles & cigarettes.
wikidata_description: French commune in Indre, Centre-Val de Loire

label: Lusignan
scope_note: Lusignan is one of the pilgrimage sites on route to the Cathedral of Santiago de Compostela, home of the shrine dedicated to Saint James, the patron saint of Spain. The symbol of Saint James, the scalloped shell, became the primary symbol representing pilgrims. French pilgrimage routes to Compostela tend to follow old Roman roads, many of which continued to be utilized as primary roads of communication during the Middle Ages. Located in Lusignan is the Church of Notre-Dame begun around 1025 and the Fortress of the Kings of Jerusalem, which was destroyed during the 16th-century Wars of Religion.

label: Grenoble
scope_note: Occupied by Arabs in 9th cen.; passed to counts of Albon 10th cen.; ceded to France 1349; suffered in Wars of Religion; rebelled against royal decree to limit powers of local parliament 1788; was site of French resistance movement during World War II.

label: Birmingham
scope_note: Nation's second largest city; market town 13th cen.; devastated by plague 1665; as home of many steam engine pioneers, it became nucleus of Industrial Revolution in Britain; severely damaged in WW II; site of experimental town-planning in early 20th cen.
wikidata_description: city in the West Midlands, England

label: Stamford
scope_note: Ancient market town located on River Welland; Scandinavian settlement in the 9th century; Norman castle built in the 10th century; notable churches include St. Mary's, All Saints, and a 7th-century Benedictine Priory; there are also fine medieval gateways here as well as a marketplace; town was wealthy from the wool trade; town expanded during Industrial Revolution.

label: Pordenone
scope_note: Located on tributary of Meduna River; destroyed in battle between Trevisani & town of Aquileia 1233; later became fief of Holy Roman Empire & was passed to Venice 1508; became part of Kingdom of Italy 1866.

label: Oropa
scope_note: Roman Catholic devotional complex located on Alpine slopes above city of Biella; construction began in 1617, near the pre-existing sanctuary of Black Virgin of Oropa reputedly founded by St. Eusebius in 4th cen. CE; today is a famous pilgrimage resort.

label: Cortina d'Ampezzo
wikidata_description: town and comune in the Province of Belluno, in the Veneto region of Northern Italy

label: Lima
scope_note: Located just inland from central Peruvian coast; there were major pre-Incan and Incan urban centers in area; Spanish city was founded in 16th cen.; flourished as capital of viceroyalty of Peru; destroyed by earthquake in 1746, rebuilt in opulent fashion.
wikidata_description: capital and largest city of Peru

label: Viseu
scope_note: Taken by Moors in 893 CE; went to Ferdinand I of Castile in 1058; known for its Dão wine & yearly agricultural fair; Museu de Grão-Vasco contains local 16th-cen. paintings; produces handicrafts such as black pottery, bobbin lace & embroidery.

label: Sibiu
scope_note: Located on Cibin river, on Turnu Roșu pass through the Transylvanian Alps; was site of Roman colony; town was founded by German colonists from Saxony in 12th cen.; destroyed by Tartars in 1241; suffered in Turkish wars, & went to Austria in 1699.

label: Elche
scope_note: Founded by Iberians; later populated by Greeks, Carthaginians and Romans; held by Moors 8th-13th centuries; manufactures olive oil, soap, hempen sandals, and esparto fabrics.

label: Toledo
scope_note: Captured by general Marcus Fulvius Nobilior for Rome 193 BCE; residence of Visigothic court 6th cen.; captued by Alfonso VI 1085; King Ferdinand III & Archbishop Rodrigo Jimenez de Rada began construction of cathedral 1226; famous swords & marzipan.

label: Hattusa
scope_note: The ruins of the ancient Hittite capital, located near the town Boğazkale. In 1380 BCE, enemies destroyed the city, and it was later restored by King Suppiluliumas I, who made it the capital of his empire. The Phrygians and the Galatians occupied the city after the fall of the Hittite Empire, around 1200 BCE.

label: United States
scope_note: Settled 40,000 years ago by ancestors of Amerindians; diverse cultures developed; Spanish, French, British and others settled the region from 16th century, native cultures were largely destroyed. The nation expanded westward throughout the 19th century; had Civil War in 1860s; There is no official language of the United States, though English is the most widely spoken and an official language of 31 states as of 2024.
wikidata_description: country located primarily in North America

label: Minneapolis
scope_note: Located on Mississippi River's Falls of St. Anthony in SE central Minnesota; "Twin Cities" with St. Paul as region's largest economic center; named for Dakota Sioux word "minne" (water) & Greek "polis" (city); site visited by Father Hennepin in 1680.
wikidata_description: city in and county seat of Hennepin County, Minnesota, United States

label: Rio de Janeiro
scope_note: Located on coastal plain on Guanabara bay; traditionally, is said to have been charted by the Portuguese in 1502; French and Portuguese contended for settlement here 16th-18th centuries; thrived as shipping port for gold and diamonds in 18th century; today is a major commercial center.
wikidata_description: capital and largest city of the state of Rio de Janeiro, Brazil

label: Bad Grönenbach
wikidata_description: market municipality in the district of Unterallgäu, Bavaria, Germany

label: Neustadt am Main
scope_note: Noted for Benedictine monastery founded here by Bishop Megingoz from Würzburg in 8th century.

label: Schweinfurt
scope_note: Schweinfurt is situated on the canalized Main River in Bavaria in central Germany. It was an important medieval center, the seat of as margravate in the first century CE. It was occupied and fortified by Gustavus Adolphus in the Thirty Years' War in the 17th century. It fell under the rule of Bavaria in 1803. Due to its being a major ball bearing production center in Germany during World War II, it was heavily bombed. Its surviving historic architecture includes its Late Gothic town hall, built 1570-72, St Johannes' Church, built 1554-62, and the Old Gynasium (school), built 1581-83. It is an important industrial city, producing motor vehicles, steel, and electronics. Other economic activities include breweries and an important cattle and sheep market. Its 2004 estimated population was 54,800.

label: Bielefeld
scope_note: The German city of Bielefeld is located at the edge of the Teutoburg Forest in the district of Detmold in the state of North Rhine-Westphalia. It was mentioned in the 11th-century biography of Bishop Meinwerk of Paderborn, and chartered by Count Hermann of Ravensberg in the 13th century. It joined the Hanseatic League in the 14th century. It passed under the rule of several principalities, from the county of Ravensberg in the 13th century, to the duchy of Jülich in 1346, and to Brandenburg in 1647. The city was badly damaged in World War II, but was rebuilt. It nevertheless retains many historic structures, including St. Mary's Church documented in the late 13thcentury, Sparrenburg Castle, built in 1250 and rebuilt after a fire in 1877, the medieval Jodokus and Altstädter Nicolai Church, and the Gothic Crüwell House, dating from 1540. The modern city has a gallery of modern art, a concert hall, an opera, a playing card museum, and a university founded in 1969. Well-known for its linen since the 16th century, it also weaves plush and silk textiles. There are other manufactories,  including for paper, clothing, sewing machines, bicycles, and electronic equipment. In 1973, Bielefeld absorbed several neighboring towns, doubling its size. The estimated population for 2004 was 323,700.

label: Gummersbach
scope_note: The small western German city of Gummersbach is located some 28 miles east of Cologne. A manufacturing city, it produces textiles, leather, and lumber. It is also a busy tourist spot, known for its fine scenery.  Its population estimate for 2004 was 53,500.

label: Cahors
scope_note: Cahors is the main city of Quercy with a harbor for boat-traffic. In 1200 the city had not yet developed into the important mercantile center it would become in the 13th century. Cahors contains many roman ruins and Christian buildings including the Cathedral of Saint Étienne, Church of Saint Urcisse, Church of Saint Barthélemy, Chapel of Saint Martin, and many basilicas. Cahors was one of the pilgrimage sites on route to the Cathedral of Santiago de Compostela, home of the shrine dedicated to Saint James, the patron saint of Spain. The symbol of Saint James, the scalloped shell, became the primary symbol representing pilgrims. French pilgrimage routes to Compostela tend to follow old Roman roads, many of which continued to be utilized as primary roads of communication during the Middle Ages.

label: Lourdes
scope_note: Formed a strategic stronghold in medieval times; captured by French from English 1406; became famous through reputed apparitions of the Virgin Mary to a peasant girl in a grotto in 1858 & has since become one of chief shrines of pilgrimage in Europe.

label: Saintes
scope_note: In Roman times, Saintes was known as Mediolanum Santonum, the capital and later province of Santons. It was also the first capital of the Augustan province of Aquitania. There are various Roman ruins here, including a Roman amphitheater.The medieval site has a castle at its highest point with a defensive wall built around it. Saintes was the site of defeat of Henry III by Louis IX in 1242. Saintes was one of the pilgrimage sites on route to the Cathedral of Santiago de Compostela. Saintes is famous for producing brandy, tile, pottery, and iron goods.

label: Vaux-le-Vicomte, Chǎteau de
scope_note: Château near Melun built 1656-1661 by Louis Le Vau for Nicolas Fouquet, finance minister to Louis XIV; considered a masterpiece of French Baroque residential architecture; garden designed by André Le Nôtre was prototype for gardens at Versailles.

label: Kórinthos
scope_note: Was one of the most powerful cities of ancient Greece; settled in prehistoric times; modern city was founded by Dorian invaders; was important maritime power by 7th cen. BCE, & colonized widely; was destroyed several times by war & earthquakes, & rebuilt.

label: Metéora
scope_note: Site of medieval 6 Orthodox monasteries located atop natural stone pillars that have been eroded so they stand as individual columns; at one time there were 23 monasteries active here, though now only 4 are inhabited; formerly accessible only by ropes & nets.

label: Teramo
scope_note: Located at confluence of Tordino & Vezzola rivers; was established by ancient Praetuttii tribe; destroyed during Germanic invasions, but flourished again in Middle Ages; was part of medieval duchy of Spoleto, later went to Kingdom of Naples.

label: Teano
scope_note: Town on the site of an ancient city in N Campania of about the same size as the present town. Although tombs of the 7th century BCE have been discovered in the area, the first evidence of the Sidicini dates to period of the Samnite wars. It was the capital of the Oscan tribe of the Sidicini, who drove the Aurunci from Roccamonfina.

label: Forlì
scope_note: Located on Montone river; was a trading center on ancient Via Aemelia; allied with Ravenna in 12th cen.; seat of imperial count, was embroiled in medieval Guelph-Ghibelline conflicts; held by Ordelaffi family from 1315; annexed to Papal States in 1504.

label: Orte
scope_note: Town on a high tuff cliff, on an ancient Etruscan site located at the junction of the Nar and the Tiber. It is named after the Etruscan goddess Horta, whose temple at Rome always remained open. It was a military colony of Augustus. Orte was the site of battles between Etruscans and Romans in 310 and 283 BCE.

label: Savona
scope_note: On Rivera di Ponente; destroyed by Lombards in 639 CE & by rival city of Genoa in 1528; ceded to Napoleonic Empire 1805, to Kingdom of Sardinia 1815 & to Italy 1861; was heavily bombed during WW II; noted for Renaissance & Baroque architecture.

label: Caravaggio
scope_note: Located 13 miles S of Bergamo; a town formerly defended by walls, castle & a moat; birthplace of Baroque painter Michelangelo Merisi da Caravaggio.

label: Manfredonia
scope_note: Settled by inhabitants of nearby abandoned town of Siponto 13th cen.; although destroyed by Turks 1620, castle of San Domenico remains; economy based on tourism & hydroelectric plants; site of a museum with treasures from ancient Siponto.

label: Carrara
scope_note: Located on the Carrione river; gained importance as marble-quarrying center, noted for fine white marble suitable for sculpture; was important medieval center; was center of Massa-Carrara principality & duchy (after 1633).

label: Pula
scope_note: S tip of Istria on Adriatic Sea; was Roman military & naval base; fishing village during Middle Ages; taken by Venetians in 1148; ruled by Austria in 1797 & by Italy in 1919; assigned to Yugoslavia in 1947.

label: Caminha
wikidata_description: locality and former civil parish in Portugal

label: Viana do Castelo
scope_note: Situated at mouth of Lima river; port traded with Genoa & Venice in Middle Ages; became base of fleets travelling to catch cod at Newfoundland's Grand Banks; noted for Misericórdia church, Casa dos Medahões & Convento de São Bento.

label: Payerne
scope_note: Located 10 miles W of Fribourg. Once capital of Transjuran Burgundy and the seat of a Cluniac abbey founded in the 10th century by Queen Bertha. In 1536, it passed from the house of Savoy to Berne.

label: Alcalá de Henares
scope_note: Located on Henares river; was noted as center of learning from 15th cen.; university was founded by Archbishop of Toledo in 1498; the first polyglot Bible, Biblia Complutensis, was published here 1514/1517.
wikidata_description: city of Spain in the Community of Madrid

label: Zamora
scope_note: Passed among Christians & Moors several times 8th-11th cen.; under rule of Alfonso VI of León & Castile 1073; controlled by Portuguese advocates of Princess Juana's claim to throne of Castile 15th cen.; fell to Ferdinand II the Catholic 1475.

label: Ried im Innkreis
wikidata_description: municipality in Ried im Innkreis District, Upper Austria, Austria

label: Apollonia Illyrica
scope_note: Apollonia was an ancient city near the mouth of the Aous (Vojussa) River. Its ruins are located over the hill of Pojani near a monastery; probably founded by colonists from Corinth and Kerkyra. It thrived during the Roman Empire and its school of philosophy became celebrated.

label: Gaochang
scope_note: Historic kingdom, with the ruins of its ancient city located in Xinjiang on the northern rim of the Taklamakan Desert.

label: Hirsau
scope_note: The town of Hirsau in Baden-Württemberg, Germany, was an important medieval center of monastic reform. Under the reforming abbot William of Hirsau, the abbey there in 1079 the Clunaic discipline. The modern town is a health resort and popular tourist destination.

label: Schwedt an der Oder
scope_note: The city of Schwedt an der Oder is situated on the Westoder River, southwest of Szczecin (Stettin), Poland. First mentioned in 1265, it passed from Pomerania to Brandenburg in the 15th century. French Huguenots settled here in the 17th century, and introduced tobacco growing. It was extensively damaged in World War II, the only historic building surviving being the Hohenzollern palace built 1719-23. Since war's end, the city has grown significantly and has become a busy industrial center, with oil refining, papermaking, and fertilizer production being the principal industries. The 2004 estimated population was 37,700.

label: Oldenburg
scope_note: The city of Oldenburg is located at the junction of the Hunte River and the Küstenkanal in the Weser-Ems district of the northwestern German state of Lower Saxony. First mentioned in 1108, it was chartered in 1345, it was an important medieval center, the seat of the powerful counts and dukes of Oldenburg. Destroyed by fire in 1615, it was neutral in the Thirty Years' War. In the first half of the 20th century it was the capitol of the now-defunct state of Oldenburg. Surviving historic architecture includes the Lambert Church, built in 1270 and rebuilt in 1794, and the ducal palace, built 1607-15. The city has a university, a state theater, and many art galleries. The major economic activities include textile manufacturing, shipbuilding and shipping, agricultural marketing, meat processing, and glassmaking. The 2004 estimated population was 158,600.

label: Bochum
scope_note: The city of Bochum lies in the middle of the industrial Ruhr district in the west-central German state of North Rhine-Westphalia, located between Dortmund to the east and Essen to the west. Receiving charters in 1298 and 1321, it was ruled by the duchy of Cleves from 1461, then by Brandenburg from 1609. It functioned as a small agricultural town until 19th-century industrial development began to exploit its coal and iron reserves and steelmaking began. Due to its industrial importance it was heavily bombed and damaged in World War II. Surviving historic buildings are limited to three: the Propsteikirche of 1599, and, in the suburbs, the 13th-century Blankenstein Castle and an 11th-century church. The city today has a modern look, having been extensively rebuilt and expanded since 1946, and acquiring within its borders the neighboring city of Wattenscheid in 1975. Coal mining, once the main industry, ceased in 1973, and automobile manufacturing now dominates the economy. The city serves as the cultural, educational, and commercial center for the surrounding part of the Ruhr district. Its 2004 estimated population was 388,200.

label: Velbert

As it has done since the 16th century, it manufactures locks, keys, and other iron goods. It hosts a well-known state art museum, Schloss Hardenberg. Its estimated population for 2004 was 89,800.

label: Frómista
scope_note: Frómista was one of the pilgrimage sites on the route to the Cathedral of Santiago de Compostela, home of the shrine dedicated to Saint James, the patron saint of Spain. The symbol of Saint James, the scalloped shell, became the primary symbol representing pilgrims. Various pilgrimage routes in the autonomous communities of Aragon, Navarre, and Castilla y León correspond to old Roman roads built in the northern portion of the Iberian Peninsula. Frómista became and important stop for pilgrims because there were four pilgrim-hospices, including one for the ill. A noteworth historic site in Frómista is the Church of San Martin.

label: Sangüesa
scope_note: Sangüesa was one of the pilgrimage sites on route to the Cathedral of Santiago de Compostela, home of the shrine dedicated to Saint James, the patron saint of Spain. The symbol of Saint James, the scalloped shell, became the primary symbol representing pilgrims. Various pilgrimage routes in the autonomous communities of Aragon, Navarre, and León correspond to old Roman roads built in the northern portion of the Iberian Peninsula. Instead of being on the actual route, Sangüesa is more of a detour for pilgrims. Historic sites in Sangüesa include the church of Santa María la Real, the parish church of Santiago, the church of La Magdalena, and the church of San Nicolás.

label: Toro
scope_note: Located on N bank of Duero river; was established in Roman times; was meeting place of Cortez (parliament) 14th-16th cen., making the code of Toro Laws famous; noted for Romanesque & 18th-cen. architecture.

label: Samarqand
scope_note: City located in east-central Uzbekistan, Samarkand dates from the 4th century BCE, when it was known as Maracanda. The city was captured by Alexander the Great in 329 BCE and was subsequently ruled by the Turks (6th century CE), the Arabs (8th century), the Samanids, and later was destroyed by Genghis Khan in 1220. By 1365, Samarkand had become part of the Timur empire, and was a flourishing city in the region. In 1500, the city was conquered by the Uzbeks, becoming part of the khanate of Bukhara. Samarkand had declined by the 17th century, becoming virtually uninhabited from ca. 1720-ca. 1780. Once the Russians had conquered the region, the city began to recover. Present-day Samarkand consists of an old city (containing many examples of 14th-20th century Central Asian architecture), and a 19th century section built by the Russians. In ancient times, the city had been on the Silk Road from India and China, and today its economy is largely agriculture-based.

label: Brugge
scope_note: The city of Brugge is the capital of the northwestern province of West-Vlaanderen in Belgium. Originally founded as landing on the Zwijn estuary, it was named for a Roman bridge over the Reie River and known as a settlement since the seventh century. St. Eloi, bishop of Noyon-Tournai converted the town to Christianity, and the first counts of Flanders built a castle here in the9th century to guard against Norman invaders. It reached its height of commercial greatness in the 14th century, as one of the most important members of the Hanseatic League of trading cities. It remained rich an powerful as the site of the court of the dukes of Burgundy, rulers of Flanders, and the artistic center of the Flemish school of painting, until the religious and political turmoil of the 16th century brought about its decline. It revived with the construction ten miles away of the North Sea port of Zerbrugge and the opening in 1907 of a canal linking it to the port. It is famed for its medieval architecture and hanseatic buildings, and enjoys a thriving tourist industry in the 20th and 21st centuries. The 2003 population estimate was around 117,200.
