label: Maubeuge
scope_note: Grew around monastery of Sainte-Aldegonde built in 7th cen.; formerly part of medieval county of Hainaut & later of Spanish Netherlands; ceded to France by Peace of Nijmegen 1678; has 17th-cen. fortifications; manufactures firearms, iron & steel goods.

label: Compiègne
scope_note: Flourished duringthe Middle Ages; site of assemblies and councils under Merovingian kings; taken from duke of Burgundy by Charles VI in 1415; scene of capture of Joan of Arc by English in 1430; headquarters of Germany 1870-1871; site of noted 18th-century palace.

label: Montdidier
scope_note: Name refers to the imprisonment of the Lombard king Didier in the 8th cen.; devastated in several battles during World War I.

label: Ligugé
scope_note: Ligugé was one of the pilgrimage sites on route to the Cathedral of Santiago de Compostela. French pilgrimage routes to Compostela tend to follow old Roman roads, many of which continued to be utilized as primary roads of communication during the Middle Ages. An important historic site located in Ligugé is the Abbey of Saint-Martin which is the oldest monastery of the Gauls. It was founded ca. 360.

label: Poitiers
scope_note: Poitiers is located on high ground where the Clain and Boivre rivers meet. It takes its name from the sites first settlers, a Gallic tribe called the Pictones, or Pictavi. It became a Christian center in the 4th century. The Visigoths settled in Poitiers in the 5th century but the site was taken over in 507 by the Frankish king Clovis. Poitiers was one of the pilgrimage sites on route to the Cathedral of Santiago de Compostela. Control of Poitiers alternated between France and England between the 12th and 14th century. The French heroine Saint Joan of Arc was interrogated there in 1429. Poitiers suffered severely during the 16th-century Wars of Religion. Parts of Poitiers were destroyed during World War II. It contains many ancient monuments dispersed throughout the town. The Notre-Dame-la-Grande church is an example of Romanesque architecture, with a 12th century facade containing many sculptures. Located in Poitiers is the 4th-century rectangular Baptistère Saint-Jean, which is estimated to be the oldest Christian edifice in France; it now houses an archaeological museum containing tombs dating from the 5th to the 8th century. There has been recent industrial growth in the area of printing, rubber, electrical machinery, and chemical industries.

label: La Rochelle
scope_note: Located on Bay of Biscay, SW of Tours; industries include aircraft, automobile & chemical manufacture; chief Huguenot stronghold 16th cen.; besieged by Richelieu & forced to capitulate through famine 1627-1628.

label: Carpentras
scope_note: Carpentras was a Roman center, still marked by a triumphal arch. It was an important religious center, first as an episcopal see and then as a center of heresy in the late Middle Ages; Pope John XXII was elected by the conclave that met here 1314-1316.

label: Embrun
scope_note: A military stronghold in Roman times; archiepiscopal see from 800 to 1791.

label: Vaison-la-Romaine
scope_note: Was important Celtic city; occupied by Romans during the Augustan period; was bisopric from 3rd cen.; enjoyed productive autonomy until invaders drove population across nearby Ouvèze river; was resettled in 17th cen.; noted for extensive Roman ruins.

label: Roanne
scope_note: Located WNW of Lyons; a crossroads in Gallo-Roman times; a major industrial center; traditional industries include hatmaking, textiles, machine tooling, metal industries, construction equipment & leather goods; has Roman & medieval remains.

label: Corbeil-Essonnes
scope_note: Located at a confluence of the Seine and Essonne rivers; flourished as capital of countship under Carolingian kings; annexed to France by Louis VI in 1108; noted as site of treaty between Louis IX of France and James I in 1258.

label: Mâcon
scope_note: A communications & railroad center; site of international wine fair; a wine trading center; industries include copper founding, printing & rope making; has remains of 12th-cen. cathedral; a Huguenot stronghold during 16th cen.

label: Arpajon
scope_note: Arpajon was one of the pilgrimage sites on route to the Cathedral of Santiago de Compostela, home of the shrine dedicated to Saint James, the patron saint of Spain. The symbol of Saint James, the scalloped shell, became the primary symbol representing pilgrims. French pilgrimage routes to Compostela tend to follow old Roman roads, many of which continued to be utilized as primary roads of communication during the Middle Ages. Located in Arpajon is the 12th-century church of Saint-Germain-lès-Arpajon.

label: Clamart

label: Neuilly-sur-Seine
scope_note: Located in N France; a NW suburb of Paris near Bois de Boulogne; noted for its automotive industry; site of signing of Treaty of Neuilly between Allies & Bulgaria after World War I, 1919.

label: Saint-Maur-des-Fossés
scope_note: Abbey was founded here by Benedictine monks from Saint-Maur-sur-le-Loire, who fled from Norman invaders in 7th cen.; abbey was powerful in Middle Ages, secularized in 16th cen., destroyed 1973; is now a residential area; produces felt, cork & chemicals.

label: Vaux-le-Vicomte, Chǎteau de
scope_note: Château near Melun built 1656-1661 by Louis Le Vau for Nicolas Fouquet, finance minister to Louis XIV; considered a masterpiece of French Baroque residential architecture; garden designed by André Le Nôtre was prototype for gardens at Versailles.

label: Tbilisi
scope_note: Tbilisi was founded ca. 458, and is located on the Mtkvari River. Due to its strategic location, the city was sacked numerous times. It was controlled by the Persians in the 6th century and by the Byzantines and Arabs in the 7th century. The city was later taken by David IV the Builder of Georgia in 1122. Tbilisi passed to the Mongols in 1234, and was pillaged by Timur in 1386, then captured several times by the Turks. In 1795, Tbilisi was burned by the Persians. From 1801, it was under Russian rule 1801, and was connected by rail to Poti by 1872. In 1921, it became the capital of the Georgian Republic. Georgia declared independence in 1991.
wikidata_description: capital and the largest city of Georgia (country)

label: Gori
scope_note: Located on Kura river; was an ancient center; was fortress for Armenians in 12th century; was destroyed by Nadir Shah of Persia in 18th century; noted as birthplace of Joseph Stalin (1879-1953, dictator of the USSR.

label: Amykles
scope_note: Site of ancient settlement, located near a hill 5 km S of Sparta; prehistoric Bronze Age settlement was confined to the hill, though the early historical site probably extended to the modern village of the same name; the ancient city reached its zenith in 7th-6th cen. BCE, as did Sparta.

label: Erétria
scope_note: Was an important city of ancient Greece; founded by Ionians, was destroyed by Persians in 490 BCE in revenge for its having assisted the Ionian Greek revolt; again destroyed by Romans in 198 BCE; the settlement was rebuilt, but on a smaller scale.

label: Górtys
scope_note: Was important Late Minoan center; mentioned in the Iliad; suffered civil war in 221 BCE; was destroyed by the Saracens in the 9th century CE. Was an impressive fortress in ancient times; was member of the Achaean League; was no more than a village when recorded by Pausanias in the 2nd cen. CE; inhabitants were finally driven out by Slavs, an founded a new town at Karítaina.

label: Kalymnos
scope_note: Located south of Leros; was probably one of Kalydnian Isles of Homeric Catalogue of Ships (other was Leros); earliest inhabitants were probably Carians; later Dorians from the Argolid colonized; in modern times, vehemently opposed Italian rule in 1930s.

label: Kárpathos
scope_note: Is the port of the town of Karpathos; site of tombs containing Minoan and Mycenaean ceramics.

label: Límnos, Nísos
scope_note: Mountainous and fertile island off W coast of Turkey; long noted for its medicinal soil, Lemnian bole or earth, used as an astringent; was important in Greek mythology, was especially sacred to Hephaestus.

label: Nikópolis
scope_note: City of ancient Epirus. Founded by Emperor Augustus opposite site of Battle of Actium in 31 BCE; inhabitants came from towns of Aetolia and Akarnania; St. Paul wrote epistle to Titus here; was seat of an early bishopric; damaged in earthquake of 375, but refortified by Justinian in 550.

label: Páros, Nísos
scope_note: Settlements here were founded by Ionians from Athens; was Aegean maritime & commercial center from 7th cen. BCE; noted for marble quarries favored by ancient sculptors.

label: Páros, Nísos
scope_note: Settlements here were founded by Ionians from Athens; was Aegean maritime & commercial center from 7th cen. BCE; noted for marble quarries favored by ancient sculptors.

label: Pella

label: Ptoion
scope_note: Site of ancient sanctuaries of Ptoan Apollo & the Hero Ptoios; was site of dwellings & fortifications from Mycenaean times.

label: Sikión
scope_note: The modern village of Sikión occupies the lower part of the ancient city of Sicyon, built on a low triangular plateau about two miles from the Corinthian Gulf. The ancient city joined the Achaean League in 251 BCE, declined after 146 BCE, and was nearly deserted in 2nd century CE.

label: Aléa
scope_note: Modern town on the site of Tegea, an important ancient city documented in Catalogue of Ships of Homer's Iliad; was long the rival of Mantinea; was allied with Sparta in Peloponnesian League from 550 BCE. Was an important religious center of ancient Greece, site of the Temple of Athena Alea. Flourished into the Hellenistic period through the 6th cen. CE.

label: Vafíon
scope_note: Village located on Eurotas river, around 5 miles S of Sparta; noted for fine gold cups found just outside the village, in a Minoan tomb dating from ca. 1500 BCE.

label: Bath

wikidata_description: city in Somerset, England, United Kingdom

label: Bergh Apton
scope_note: There are 6th- and 7th-century barrows and ring ditches here.

label: Berkshire
scope_note: Inhabited by Iron Age peoples, Romans and Saxons; crossed by Roman roads and many railways, due to strategic location on Thames river and proximity to London; cities developed during Industrial Revolution; area is known for its breed of black and white pig; Berkshire County Council abolished in 1998 although Berkshire is sometimes still referred to as a county; broken into six unitary authorities: Bracknell Forest, West Berkshire, Reading, Slough, Windsor and Maidenhead, and Wokingham.

label: Blenheim Palace
scope_note: Royal manor built by Sir John Vanbrugh in 1704 for Duke of Marlborough, to honor his victory over French & Bavarians; built in heavy, ornate English Baroque style; includes a man-made lake by Capability Brown, a deer park & private chapel.

label: Blenheim Palace
scope_note: Royal manor built by Sir John Vanbrugh in 1704 for Duke of Marlborough, to honor his victory over French & Bavarians; built in heavy, ornate English Baroque style; includes a man-made lake by Capability Brown, a deer park & private chapel.

label: Bodmin
scope_note: Originally a religious settlement, founded by St. Guron and surrendered to famous St. Petroc in about 530; only a few fragments of the Norman abbey remain.

label: Chester
scope_note: Located on the River Dee; Roman camp of Deva; amphitheatre and ramparts remain; after Romans departed ca. 380, occupied by Danes and Saxons; important under Mercian kings in the 10th century; last town to surrender to William the Conqueror in 1070; medieval galleried streets; Tudor houses; a cathedral and castle; port was important 13th-14th centuries but declined with growth of Liverpool.

label: Fife
scope_note: Consists of former county of Fife; area comprises lowlands and fluvioglacial deposits with coalfields to the south; although remote during Middle Ages, contained many royal burghs and important centers during the 16th century; industries include mining and fishing.

label: Gloucester
scope_note: Located on the site of Roman town of Glevum; center for leather and cloth trade from 12th-16th centuries; Perpendicular style cathedral, begun in 1089, contains grave of Edward II; world's first Sunday school was founded here by Robert Raikes in 1780; the New Inn is a 15th-century pilgrims' hostel; William I commissioned the 'Domesday' survey here at his Christmas council of 1085.

label: Lincoln
scope_note: Important Roman town on line of Fosse Way and Ermine Sreet; Roman remains include stone gates, fountains, and baths; there is also a large 12th-century cathedral; castle built by William I; site of rebellion during reign of Henry VIII; industry began in the 18th century; birthplace of tanks during World War I.

label: Newcastle upon Tyne
scope_note: Was station on Hadrian's Wall; was important fortress town in the 12th century and wool center in the 14th century; prospered in shipbuilding, ironworks, and banking by 1800; noted for 14th-century Church of St. Nicholas and 17th-century Guild Hall; has many fine universities.
wikidata_description: city in Tyne and Wear, England, UK

label: Norfolk
scope_note: Low-lying area crossed by rivers Yare, Wensum, and Bure; noted for Paleolithic, Mesolithic, and Neolithic remains; occupied by British Inceni people in the 3rd century; was wealthy and densely populated in the 11th century; economy based on food-processing, fishing, and shoes.
wikidata_description: county in East Anglia, England, UK

label: Northampton
scope_note: Located on the River Nene. Danes lived here from the 9th to the 11th century. 11th-century Norman castle here was the site of parliamentary meetings from the 12th to the 14th century. There are also Norman churches and a medieval marketplace. Northampton was the scene of the trial of Thomas Becket in 1164 and also where Henry VI was defeated during the War of the Roses in 1460. It was destroyed by fire 1675 and rebuilt in the 18th century. Northampton was noted for its boot and shoe manufacturing.

label: Peterborough
scope_note: On the River Nene 75 miles north of London. The town grew around a monastery dating to 656 CE and is noted for its cathedral in the Norman style (begun 1118, completed 14th century) containing the grave of Catherine of Aragon. Town used to be a brickmaking center; modern economy is based on diesel engines, steam turbines, bricks, and foodstuffs. Peterborough was once considered within the boundaries of Northamptonshire.

label: Saltwood
scope_note: Hilltop village with a moated castle; now a suburb of Hythe; name is said to derive from the seaside woods at the base of its promontory; stronghold built here in 488 by Aesc, son of Hengist of Kent; Thomas à Becket's murderers supposedly plotted in the castle's great hall; castle restored in the 1930s; the best-preserved parts of the castle date to the time of William Courtenay, who became archbishop of Canterbury in 1390.

label: Stonyhurst
scope_note: Seat of a Roman Catholic college.

label: Winchcombe
scope_note: Was once an Anglo-Saxon walled city prosperous from wool, then tobacco, & then paper; there is a mill at Postlip & a row of almshouses by Sir Gilbert Scott.

label: Aqar Quf
scope_note: Was located near the confluence of the Tigris and Diyala rivers, west of modern Baghdad. Site is noted for temples dedicated to Sumerian gods, a royal palace, and one of the best preserved ziggurats of the Kassite period. It was founded by a Kassite king of Babylon, Kurigalzu I, some time in the 14th century BCE; abandoned after the fall of the Kassite dynasty.

label: H̲efa
scope_note: Located on Mt. Carmel; conquered by Crusaders 1100; taken by Napoleon 1799; captured by Egypt 1839; surrendered to Turkey 1840; occupied by British 1918 & became part of Palestine mandate 1922; has steel mill, chemical plants & oil refinery.

label: Megara Hyblaea
scope_note: Was Late Neolithic settlement of the Stentinello period; one of first Greek colonies in Sicily, founded by Megarians ca. 750 BCE as described by Thucydides; was Selinuntian metropolis 7th cen. BCE; destroyed by Gelon 481 BCE, later fortified but destroyed by Romans in second Punic War; rural setlement grew up on site, but now abandoned.

label: Tagliacozzo
scope_note: Site of battle (August 1268) in which Charles I of Anjou defeated Conradin.

label: Melfi

Various pilgrimage routes in the autonomous communities of Aragon, Navarre, and León correspond to old Roman roads built in the northern portion of the Iberian Peninsula. It is estimated that Mansilla de las Mulas must have existed prior to 1188, when it received a town charter.

label: Mnichovo Hradiště
scope_note: Mnichovo Hradiště is a small town north of Prague in the Středočeský region of the north-central Czech Republic. It is famous for its landmark castle, built by Wallenstein in the late 17th century. In the Baroque style, a rebuilding of a Renaissance castle itself built upon the ruins of a medieval fortress. It houses a collection of Delft pottery and Japanese and Chinese porcelain and miniatures. The castle is attached to a former monastery, of which there remains the Church of Three Kings, built from 1694 to 1699, connected with the richly decorated St. Ann's Chapel. It also has a theatre built in 1833 for the presentation of court spectacles. The castle is set within a large park in two different portions, one in the French style and one in the English. The town's museum contains artifacts from nearby prehistoric settlements. Tourism is the major economic activity of the town.

The village is the birthplace of the famous composer Antonín Dvořák, whose former home is a short distance from the castle.

label: Al Iskandarīyah
scope_note: The city is located on a narrow strip of land between the Mediterranean Sea and Lake Mariut; it is now partially submerged. It was the renowned capital of the Ptolemies when they ruled Egypt. It was noted for its library and a great lighthouse on the island of Pharos. It was captured by Caesar in 48 BCE, taken by Arabs in 640 and by Turks in 1517. The city was famed for being the site of convergence of Greek, Arab and Jewish ideas. It was occupied by the French 1798-1801, by the British in 1892; evacuated by the British in 1946.

label: Mauthausen
scope_note: Town on the Danube River, notorius for being the location of a Nazi concentration camp of the same name, situated next to an abandoned stone quarry near the village. Established in 1938 and built with slave labor, the camp primarily housed political prisoners, "anti-Nazis," criminals, and some Jews, until 1944, when Jews in large numbers were sent to Mauthausen from Hungary and Poland. Mauthausen was one of the most notorious of all concentration camps, with prisoners routinely being starved, beaten, used for medical experiments, forced into brutal labor, and gassed. Approximately 119,400 people died at Mauthausen. The camp was liberated in May of 1945.

label: Frankfurt am Main
scope_note: Frankfurt am Main is the largest city in the state of Hessen in western Germany, lying some 19 miles upstream on the Main River from the city of Mainz. Celts and Germanic people occupied the site in the first century BCE and by the Romans in the first and second centuries CE. The Franks took it over around 500, when if probably gained the name Frankfurt, meaning "ford of the Franks, but was first mentioned as such by Charlemagne's biographer in the late 8th century. In 1356 it was designated the official site of the election of the German kings. It was a free imperial city from 1372 to 1806, then Napoleon I made it first the seat of government for the Confederation of the Rhine, then the capital of the Grand Duchy of Frankfurt. From 1816 to 1866 it was the seat of the Germann Federal Diet and thus de facto the capital of the German states. Following the Seven Weeks' War in 1866, it fell under Prussian rule where it remained until after World War I. It suffered heavy damage from bombardment in World War II, and most of its medieval Old City was destroyed. Historic structures that survived include the 8th-century Benedictine monastery, the Römer or medieval city hall, the 155-foot Eschenheim Tower, St. Bartholomew's Cathedral dating from 1239, and the Church of St. Paul. Modern Frankfurt am Main is a commercial and industrial center, famous for its many trade fairs, including the international book, car, and computer fairs. It is known for the manufacture of motor vehicles, pharmaceuticals, printing materials, and processed foods, especially sausages. It is a transportation center with a busy railway hub and the largest airport in Germany. The 2004 estimated population was 646,000.

label: Freising

It was an early seat of religious and temporal rule of bishops in the area, and was famed as Bavaria's first ecclesiastical and cultural capital. Its historic architecture features the Cathedral Hill, with the cathedral built in the 12th century, the Benedict Church built 1160 and renovated 1716, and St. John's Church built from 1319 to 1321.  manufactures agricultural machinery glass, pottery, and beer, the brewery having been licensed in 1146. The 2004 estimated population was 42,700.

label: Ostrava
scope_note: Ostrava is the capital city of the region of Severomoravský in the northeastern Czech Republic, situated in a coal-mining region near the junction of the Ostravice and Oder Rivers. Founded as a fortified town in 1267, it was a prosperous medieval center. Its castle was destroyed in 1495, but the 13th-century St. Wenceslaus' Church and the 17th-century Old Town Hall tower survive today. It is a culturally active community, with a philharmonic orchestra and an opera house. It is also an industrial center, taking advantage of the rich black coal mines of the surrounding area (some extending into the city limits) to create thriving mining and metallurgical industries. Chemical fertilizers, mining equipment, automobiles, and coal-fired electrical power are also produced. The 2003 estimated population was 317,700.

label: Sorø
scope_note: The town of Sorø is the county seat of Vestsjælland in Denmark. This famous school, Sorø Academy, educated many Danish kings and princes over the centuries. The town's historic architecture features the former abbey church. Built by Bishop Absolon in the 12th century and which contains his tomb as well as those of two 14-century kings. The economic activities of the modern town consist mainly of meat processing, wood, and machinery. The 2004 estimated population was 7,000.

label: Yerevan
scope_note: The city of Yerevan was formed in 783 BCE, although the area had been settled several thousand years previous. Located on an ancient crossroads of caravan routes along the Razdan River, Yerevan was annexed to the Armenian kingdom in the 6th century BCE. Due to the city's strategic location, it has been conquered at various turns by, among others, the Romans, Mongols, Arabs, Persians and the Russians, under whom the city became the capital of the Armenian Soviet Socialist Republic in 1920. Under the Soviets, Yerevan became the modern, industrial center of the country. It remained the capital when Armenia became independent in 1991.

label: België
scope_note: The modern kingdom of Belgium lies at the  crossroads of northeastern Europe, bounded on the northwest by the North Sea, on the north and northeast by The Netherlands, on the east by Germany, on the southeast by Luxembourg, and on the southwest and west by France. The area has historically been held by Celtic Belgae and Germanic tribes, Romans, Frankish-Merovingians, Carolingians, then various feudal states. Many independent cities evolved there in medieval times. Burgundy ruled it in the 14th century, then the Hapsburgs from 1482. Since 1831 it has been a representative, and constitutional monarchy. Densely populated and heavily urbanized, it has a rich mix of cultures. The official languages are Dutch (or Flemish), mainly spoken in the north, French, mainly spoken in the south, and German.

label: Uccle

An historic inn, the Auberge du Cornet, dates from 1570, and lies near a wooded park, a remnant of the great Soigne Forest The modern town serves as a residential suburb for Brussels, with some light industry. It is the site of the Belgian Royal Observatory and several historic châteaux.

label: Forest

It encompasses two wooded parks on the slopes of the Zenne Valley that were once part of the Forêt de Soignes, hence the town's name. It is home to the Abbey of Saint-Benoit, built in 1106, which includes monastic buildings built in the 18th century. The modern town is a suburb of Brussels, and has many industries including leather goods, soap, clocks, and beer.

label: Leuven
scope_note: The city is the capital of the Belgian province of Brabant, situated on the Dijle River and connected by canal with the Schelde River. It is about 16 miles east of Brussels. The settlement was founded in the ninth century at the site of a fortress built by the German emperor to halt advancing Normans. In the eleventh century it was the residence of the counts of Leuven, and later of Brabant from 1190. It grew to be a major cloth producer and one of the largest cities in Europe in 14th century, but declined after a citizens' revolt in 1379 was put down and many of its weavers fled to England and Flanders. The Catholic University of Leuven was founded in 1425, making the city famous as a seat of learning. In1914, when Germany invaded it, the university's famous library and the Cloth Workers' Hall, built1193, were burned. It sustained much damage in both World Wars. It nevertheless continues to be a center of culture, famed for its pointed Gothic town hall, built by Mathieu de Layens, the master mason, from 1448 to 1463. The Church of St. Peter, built first in the early 11th century, was twice destroyed before being rebuilt as a Gothic structure in1425-97, and it was again damaged in both world wars. The church contains two fine paintings by Dirck Bouts and fine ironwork and brasswork, much of it by Quentin Massys. Other notable medieval buildings include the "Round Table," churches of St. Gertrude, St. Quentin, Saint-Michel, and St. James, two monasteries, and a béguinage, or retreat for secular nuns, with a 1305 church. The city's manufactures include food processing, beer brewing, leather goods, machinery, and chemicals, as well as sawmilling and bell founding. The population by a 2003 estimate is around 89,400.

label: Arlon
scope_note: Located near border of Grand Duchy of Luxembourg; founded and fortified by Romans, again fortified in 1671; occupied by French 1684-1697; site of victories of French General Jourdan over Austrian Imperial forces 1793 and 1794; Belgian since 1831.The capital of the Belgian province of Luxembourg, it lies near the border of the Grand Duchy of Luxembourg. It is the oldest known inhabited place in Belgium. Under the name Orolaunum it was founded and fortified by the Romans. It became a countship in the 10th century. Richard I of England, who was also the Marquis of Arlon, left for the Third Crusades from its castle in 1190. Again fortified in 1671; it was occupied by the French from 1684 to 1697. In 1793 and 1794 it was the site of victories of the French under General Jourdan over Austrian Imperial forces. In 1830 it became the provisional capital of Luxembourg province, and was confirmed in this position in 1839. Having seen so much warfare over the centuries, little physically remains of its past, except for the Roman Tower from the 4th-century fortifications that were torn down by the French in 1670, and the 17th-century Church of St. Donatus. It also has an archaeological museum containing valuable Roman tomb reliefs. The town is a major livestock and agricultural market. The 2003 estimated population was 25,300.

label: Stavelot

Its extensive buildings, dating from the 18th century, still exist and serve secular purposes. The place has become infamous for the nearby massacre of American prisoners of war in the Second World War.

label: Verviers

label: Veurne
scope_note: The town lies at the junction of four canals, northeast of Dunkerque in the Belgian province of West-Vlaanderen. Founded by Baldwin I of Flanders around 870, it was a strategic town of the Spanish Netherlands. During the First World War it was the chief town of unoccupied Belgium. It is famous for its annual processions of the Holy Cross in May, and of the Penitents in July, both dating from medieval times. It was a significant amount of surviving historic architecture, including the 15th-century Gothic-style Spanish Pavilion, the Meat Market built1615 and now a theatre, the 15th-century St. Nicholas Church with its massive tower, the Spanish Guard House of1636, the Gothic Belfry, built 1628, burned 1940, since restored, and St. Walburga's Church, begun 1230-8. The 2003 estimated population was 11,800.

label: Sofiya
scope_note: Sofiya is the capital and the largest city of Bulgaria, situated in the Sofiya Basin in the Geographical center of the Balkan region. Founded by Thracian tribe of Serdi in the 8th century BCE, it was conquered by Rome after 29 BCE. It thrived under the Emperors Trajan (98-117) and Constantine. It was the site of the Christian condemnation of the Arian heresy in 343. Attila the Hun sacked it in 441. It was seized by the Bulgarian tsar in 809, by the Byzantines in 1018, the Second Bulgarian Empire in 1185, then Turks in 1382. The Russian drove out the Turks in 1878 and it was named the capital of the new Bulgarian state in 1879. The Germans occupied it in World War II, but it was liberated by Russia in 1944. Since 1947, Sofiya has become a major industrial city, with food processing, metallurgy, printing, engineering, and the manufacture of textiles and clothing. The city is also a cultural and educational center, with the University of Sofiya, founded 1888, a national theater and opera house, several museums, the national library, and an astronomical observatory. It has several historic churches, notably the Alexander Nevsky Cathedral. The 2003 estimated population was 1,088,700.

label: Baden-Württemberg
scope_note: Baden-Württemberg is a state in southwestern Germany, bordered by Switzerland in the south, France to the west, the state of Bavaria on the east, Rhineland-Palatinate on the northeast, and Hesse to the north. It measures some 13,804 square miles in area. Most of its people are Alemanni, relatives of the French Alsatians, plus Franconians, Palatinate people, and Swabians. Before the Romans occupied it, the main European trading artery was the River Rhein which runs through Baden-Württemberg. It also had immense hardwood forests, now largely cut. To the south are the Alps. The state was formed in the post-World War II occupational period from three former states in the American and French zones; this arrangement was ratified by a referendum in 1951 and made official in 1952. Its capital is Stuttgart. The 2004 estimated population was 10,721,600.

label: Esslingen
scope_note: The town of Esslingen is located on the Neckar River in the district of Stuttgart in southwestern Germany at a site of commanding, strategic height. It lies at the center of a fertile wine-producing and fruit-growing area. Documented in 777 as Cella and in 866 as Hetsilinga, it was fortified and chartered about 1219. It was a free imperial city until it passed to Württemberg in 1802. Historic architecture includes three town halls, the old citadel standing upon a high crest, and the Church of Our Lady, built between 1321 and 1516, the first structure to be designed in the Swabian gothic style. The 2004 estimated population was 91,600.

label: Friedrichshafen
scope_note: The town of Friedrichshafen is located on north shore of Lake Constance in the state of Baden-Württemberg in southwestern Germany. The site was settled by at least the 9th century and came to be known as Buchhorn. Close by was the monastery of Hofen, dating from the 11th century. Friedrich I of Württemburg united the town and the then-suppressed monastery in the 19th century and created the new town of Friedrichshafen. A Zeppelin factory was established here, which may have been the main reason for the town being bombed in World War II. The 2004 estimated population was 58,000.

label: Reichenau
scope_note: The island of Reichenau is located in the west arm of Lake Constance in southwestern Germany. It was famed in the Middle Ages as a center of art and culture, having a college known for producing many bishops and archbishops, and a rich Benedictine monastery that lasted from 724 until 1803. It remained independent until 1540. It is now part of the city of Konstanz.

label: Tübingen
scope_note: The city of Tübingen is situated on the Neckar River at its junction with the Ammer and Steinach Rivers, in the state of Baden-Württemberg in southwestern Germany. The settlement grew around the castle of the counts palatine of Tübingen in the 11th century, and was first documented as a town in 1231. The town went to Württemberg in 1342, but changed hands among the Swabian League, Swedes, French, and Holy Roman Empire in the 17th century. Long renowned as a seat of learning, it was home to astronomer J Kepler, poet J Hölderllin, and philosopher G Hegel. The most notable of its historic structures is the Hohentübingen ducal castle, built in the 16th and 17th centuries and now housing several institutes belonging to the University of Tübingen. Modern industries include metal and machinery, textile, and paper manufactures. It is also a publishing center. The 2004 estimated population was 83,300.

label: Bayreuth
scope_note: The town of Bayreuth in Bavaria developed around the castle of the counts Andechs-Meran in the 11th century. It passed to the Hohenzollerns in 1248 and became the capital of Upper Franconia; and was the residence of the margraves from 1603 to 1791 when it was ceded to Prussia. In 1810 it was ceded to Bavaria. It is famed around the world as the home of the summer festival of Wagnerian opera. The 2004 estimaed population was 74,600.

label: Hof
scope_note: The city of Hof is located on the Saale River in northern Bavaria near the border between Germany and the Czech Republic. First mentioned in 1214, it was founded by the dukes of Andechs-Meran, chartered in 1319, passed to the Hohenzollerns of Nürnberg in 1373, then to Prussia in 1792, and to Bavaria in 1810. It was nearly completely destroyed by fire in 1823, but its principal older buildings, including its medieval churches were rebuilt in the following years. The commercial and industrial center of northern Upper Bavaria, Hof produces woolens, carpets, porcelain, beer, machinery, and iron goods. It is also a cultural city, with a symphony orchestra, a museum, and several institutions of higher learning. The 2004 estimated population was 49,900.

label: München
scope_note: Capital of Bavaria and the third-largest city in Germany; situated on both sides of the Isar River, north of the Alps. Henry the Lion, duke of Bavaria, established Munich in 1157 as a mint and market for Benedictine monks from Tegernsee. It suffered declined during the 17th century under the Swedish occupation and the plague epidemic of the Thirty Years' War. It revived under the Bavarian king Ludwig I, whose building and urban planning activities defined the character that the city has today. The city witnessed the rise to power of the Nazi party in the 1920s and 1930s, and was heavily damaged in World War II, when Allied bombing destroyed about 40% of its buildings. Still, a great deal of historic architecture survives, much of its rebuilt or restored, including the church the Frauenkirche, built 1468-1488. The city boasts seven old city gates, and many fine building built in the 19th century under Ludwig I. Munich is an active cultural center for the whole of Europe, with many libraries, theaters, museums, art galleries, and concert venues. It has several of the largest breweries in Germany and is renowned for its annual Oktoberfest celebrations. Light industry and tourism are major economic activities. The 2004 estimated population was 1,241,100.

label: Berlin
scope_note: The city of Berlin, coextensive with the state of Berlin, lies on both sides of the Spree River in its wide glacial valley in the center of unified Germany. Comprises 12 bezirke (boroughs), each of which contains a number of localities that may have historic roots in older municipalities that predate the formation of Greater Berlin in 1920. The area was originally two Wendish villages, Kölln and Berlin, were founded there in the 13th century, merged in the 14th century, and was named Berlin by the Hohenzollerns. It was strategically located at the center of the canal system of the Oder and Spree Rivers. Severely damaged in World War II; after the war, was divided into four occupation zones, each governed by one of the Allies. The Soviet-ruled East Berlin, together with the rest of East Germany, and West Berlin, a western enclave within East Germany, were governed separately from 1949. A concrete wall physically divided the city in 1961. The Berlin Wall and the political separation of the two parts of the city ended in 1989 as the communist eastern government collapsed. In 1990 the united Berlin became once again the capital of a united Germany. The largest city in Germany, its 2011 estimated population was 3.5 million.

label: Hamburg
scope_note: The northern German city of Hamburg is located on Elbe River, which connects it to the North Sea. It is one of Europe's busiest ports and Germany's largest port and commercial and industrial city. The site was first used for a fortress against the Slavs built by Charlemagne in 825. With Lübeck, it formed the Hanseatic League in 1241, and grew steadily over the next several centuries as a trade center. It accepted the Reformation in 1529 and became Protestant. Hamburg went its own way as the Hanseatic League gradually faded from existence; a stock exchange was founded there in 1558 and the bank of Hamburg was established in 1619. Napoleon I annexed it to the French Empire in 1810, and after his fall it joined the German Confederation, all the while retaining its traditional self-government to a large degree. The city was devastated by fire in 1842, but was rebuilt. It suffered terrible destruction by bombing in World War II, but its value as a port soon lead to its restoration and the resumption of its busy economic life. It is cosmopolitan in character with fine art collections in its museums, a world famous opera and two symphony orchestras, and a famous red-light district where prostitution is legal. The 2004 estimated population was 1,731,200.

label: Marburg
scope_note: The city of Marburg is situated on the Lahn River in central Germany. First mentioned under this name in 1130, it was a fortress of the landgraves of Thuringia in the 12th century. It later became the seat of the landgraves of Hesse. St. Elizabeth of Hungary spent the last three years of her life in Marburg, and until the Reformation her bones lay in a shrine in St. Elizabeth's Church. Marburg was the site of debates between Martin Luther and other reformers in 1529 over the nature of the Eucharist. The city is known for the Gothic castle of the Hessian landgraves with its famous Rittersaal and chapel, begun in 1277 and completed in 1493. It was also the site of Europe's first Protestant University, founded 1527. Today its economy is driven largely by tourism, plus a few industries such as chemical and precision instrument manufacture. The 2004 estimated population was 77,700.

label: Mecklenburg
scope_note: Mecklenburg is a region in northeastern Germany bordering the Baltic Sea from the bight of Lübeck 100 miles eastward. The original Germanic settlements were occupied by Slavic Wends around 600 CE, who in turn were invaded by Saxons in the 12th century. The region was ruled by Danes in the 13th century, then by Swedes in the 17th century. It was divided into various states in the 16th- and 17th centuries, and in the 19 and 20th centuries. Following the First World War, the two grand duchies that then occupied the territory of Mecklenburg were abolished and replaced by elected governments. In 1934, the Nazi government unified the two parts into one state. Between 1945 and 1952 Mecklenburg was a state of East Germany, then was divided into three smaller official districts. Shortly before German reunification, the three separate districts were reunited as the state of Mecklenburg-West Pomerania.  It is now part of the district of Neubrandenburg in the state of Mecklenburg-Vorpommern.

label: Moringen
scope_note: Town in Lower Saxony, known as the site of three Nazi concentration camps during World War II. In 1933, the first camp was established, for male inmates, most of whom were political prisoners. It closed in late 1933, with the inmates being moved to other camps. A camp for females was in operation from 1933-1938, and included political prisoners, as well as those who were pursued for racial or religious reasons. When the camp closed, many of the inmates were moved to Ravensbrück concentration camp. From 1940 to 1945, a youth concentration camp operated at Moringen, where pseudoscientific medical experimentation occurred and the inmates were subjected to inhumane treatment and conditions. There is a memorial on the site today.

The people share a common Saxon origin and a common language, Plattdeutsch, related to Dutch, Frisian, and English. It received an influx of refugees during and after World War II. The modern state is a merger of four older districts: Hannover, Braunschweig, Oldenburg, and Schaumburg, created on November 1, 1946. The 2004 estimated population was 8,004,300.

label: Bonn
scope_note: The German city of Bonn is located some fifteen miles south of Cologne on the Rhine river. Romans documented a river crossing here in the 1st century BCE, and occupied a fortress here from the 1st to the 5th century CE. It was a Frankish town from the 9th century, and from the 13th century was a prosperous town, the capital of the electorate and archbishopric of Cologne. It was occupied by the French from 1794, and then annexed to Prussia in 1815. In the 19th century it grew famous as a rich, fashionable cit y, remaining as such until World War II, when it was heavily damaged. From 1949 to 1990 it was the capital of West Germany and grew in size and importance, annexing several nearby towns in 1969. Efforts were made to preserve the residential look of the city and so only restricted light industry was allowed, Bonn is a cultural center, famed as the birthplace of the composer Ludwig van Beethoven. It has many musical institutions, including an orchestra, and hosts many national and international concerts, mainly in its modern concert hall, the Beethovenhalle. There are many private theaters and performance halls and a large municipal theater that hosts opera, drama, ballet, and musicals. There are two major museums. Its historic architecture includes a Romanesque basilica surmounted by five towers, and three old churches dating from the 10th, 11th, and 12th centuries respectively. There is also the former Electorate Palace, now the Rhenish Friedrich Wilhelm University of Bonn, founded 1786 and the Poppelsdorf Palace, which has botanical gardens. Generally the city is well provided with green open spaces and broad tree-lined streets. The estimated population for 2004 was 311,000.

label: Dinslaken
scope_note: The city of Dinslaken is located in the Ruhr region some 22 miles north of the city of Düsseldorf in northwestern Germany. First mentioned in 1163, the town developed around an existing castle, and received its charter in 1273 from the count of Cleves. Throughout its history, it has served as a regional administrative center. It was severely damaged in World War II, but has been rebuilt as a modern industrial and residential city. Its economic activities include sawmilling, coal mining, and the production of a wide variety of products such as wine, shoes, garments, steel-rolling equipment, and electrical equipment. The population estimate for 2004 was 71,300.

label: Duisburg
scope_note: The German city of Duisburg is situated at the confluence of the Rhein and the Ruhr. It is an important inland port, being connected to the North Sea German ports by the Rhine-Herne Canal. The Duisburg-Neuenkamp Bridge crosses the Rhine here, one of the world's longest span truss structures. The ancient settlement on the site, known to the Romans as Castrum Deutonis, became the seat of the Frankish kings in the 8th century. It was a free city of the Holy Roman Empire until taken over by Cleves in 1290, then by Brandenburg in 1614. It declined in the wars of the 17th century, but came back into prosperity as the seat of a Protestant university from 1655 until 1818. After 1880 it became industrialized and grew in the early to mid-20th century by annexing several surrounding towns and by acquiring a harbor. Severely damaged during World War II, it became one of western Europe's major iron and steel production centers, and in 1975 absorbed four more outlying cities. The modern city retains little of its historic architecture, but for the 12th-century Romanesque Premonstratensian Abbey Church and the 14th-century Gothic Salvator Church. Other cultural entities are art museums, including the Lehmbruck Museum in honor of famous local sculptor Wilhelm Lehmbruck, local history museums, and a zoo containing Germany's largest aquarium.  Besides iron and steel production, Duisburg has coal mining and the manufacture of heavy machinery, textiles, and metal and wooden items. The population estimate for 2004 was 506,700.

In 1975 it absorbed the neighboring town of Wanne-Eikel, also an industrial center. Today the local economy is based on coal mining, foundries and textile factories. label: Iserlohn
scope_note: The city of Iserlohn is located at edge of the wooded, hilly Sauerland area southeast of Dortmund in the German state of North Rhine-Westphalia. Documented in the 11th century, it received its town charter in 1237. In medieval times it was famous as producer of light metalware and armor. The community suffered from a large-scale fire in 1712 and a rebellion in 1849. Of its historic structures, there remains the 11th-century St. Pankratius Church and the 1350 Oberste Stadtkitche. Today the city is an industrial center, producing machinery, chemicals, rubber, leather, and metal products. The 2004 population estimate was 98,800.

label: Mülheim an der Ruhr
scope_note: The city of Mülheim an der Ruhr is situated on the Ruhr river just southwest of Essen in the northwestern German state of North Rhine-Westphalia. First documented in 1093, the town developed below the ancient castle of the counts von Broich, later going to the duchy of Berg, then to Prussia in 1814. It only received its charter in 1808. It grew much larger through the annexation of several nearby towns between 1878 and 1929. Historic architecture includes the 11th-century St. Peter's Church, which has been completely restored, Styrum Castle of the 13th century, a 13th-century Cistercian convent, and the residence of Gerhard Tersteegen, a famous hymn author who died in 1769. The city sustained heavy damage in World War II, and was rebuilt along modern plans with many parks and other open-air leisure and sports facilities. The city is a transportation center for road and rail, and an important river port. It is also a center of heavy industry, which is regulated by strict ordinance to preserve the human look and orientation of the city. Industries include iron founding, machine works, blast furnaces and rolling mills, and chemical and electronics manufactories. Mülheim houses the Max Planck Institute for Coal Research, where the Fischer-Tropsch process for liquefying coal and the Ziegler process for the production of polyethylene plastics were first invented. The population estimate for 2004 was 172,100.

label: Nordrhein-Westfalen
scope_note: The state of North Rhine-Westphalia is located in west central Germany. It lies bordered by Belgium and the Netherlands to the west, Hesse to the east, Lower Saxony to the north, and Rhineland-Palatinate to the south.  It was formed after World War II of an amalgamation of Prussian Westfalen, the Northeim province of Prussia, and the state of Lippe. The area suffered extensive damage during World War II. The state has since grown and developed into Germany's industrial heartland, including the Saarland region, and contains one-fifth of its total population, 18,100,000 by a 2004 estimate.

The shrine of St. Agnes there has a reliquary said to be by the noted 12th-century goldsmith and enamellist Nicholas of Verdun. Famed German composer Engelbert Humperdinck was born here in 1854. label: Witten
scope_note: The city of Witten is located in a heavily wooded recreational area on the Ruhr river in the Arnsberg district of the German state of North Rhine-Westphalia. Chartered in 1825, it touches Dortmund to the north and Bochum to the northwest. It is an industrial center that produces steel, glass, machines, coal-tar products, and chemicals. As a producer of products used in the German World War II effort, it was heavily bombed and severely damaged, but has been rebuilt as a planned modern city. Its 2004 estimated population was 103,000.

label: Zweibrücken
scope_note: The town of Zweibrücken is located on the Schwarzbach river some 53 miles west southwest of Mannheim. It was an independent countship and noted medieval center, receiving its charter in 1352/ It passed to the Wittelsbach family in 1385. It produced famous early editions of Roman and Greek classic texts, the Editiones Bipontinae. In 1410 it became a duchy and in 1477 passed into the possession of the house of Pfalz-Zweibrücken. Possession passed to Bavaria in 1816. The town was almost totally destroyed in World War II, but has been mostly rebuilt. Its surviving historic architecture includes the late Gothic Church of St. Alexander, the castle built in 1720-1725, and the Baroque town hall built 1779-1785. The modern town bears the nickname "the town of roses and horses" after its famous Garden of Roses east of the town and its local horse breeding and racing industry. Other industries include metalworking and the production of wood products, textiles, machinery, and footwear. The calculated population for 2005 was 35,970.

label: Borna
scope_note: The eastern German town of Borna lies due west of another, smaller town with the same name in the Leipzig district. It was chartered as a city in the 13th century. Its calculated population for 2005 was 18,504.

label: Hosterwitz
wikidata_description: named part of the German city Dresden

label: Riesa
scope_note: The eastern German city of Riesa is situated on the Elbe river about 39 miles east of Leipzig. The town developed around a 12th-century Benedictine monastery, and in 1170 a convent was founded there also. The town was chartered in 1623 but soon lost its status, and was rechartered only in 1859, when the town again flourished due to industrial development and railway connections. Its major piece of historic architecture is its town hall, built as a castle in the 16th century. The modern city is a transportation hub, being at the junction of the Leipzig-Dresden and Berlin-Chemnitz rail lines. It is also a busy river port, the most important in northern Saxony. The city is an industrial center with an oil refinery, rolling mills, steelworks, a cotton mill, and factories for the production of foodstuffs, wood products, and tires. The calculated population for 2005 was 36,788.
wikidata_description: town in the district of Meißen in the Free State of Saxony, Germany

label: Görlitz
scope_note: The eastern German city of Görlitz is situated on the Neisse river, across from the town of Zgorzelec, Poland, which was part of the city prior to World War II. The site was initially the Slav town of Gorelić, first recorded in 1071. It was ruled by Bohemia in the 13th century, was chartered in 1303, and was a member of the Federation of Lusatian Cities after 1346. It passed to Saxony in 1635, then to Prussia in 1815. Surviving historic architecture includes a medieval representation of the Holy Sepulcher, the ruins of a fortress built in the 14th century, the Church of Saints Peter and Paul built 1423-1497, and many houses built in the Baroque style. Görlitz attained its economic peak in medieval times with the local industry of fine textile production, which in the Baroque era also included the production of linen. Today it still has a textile industry, and also produces railway cars, electrotechnical products, woodworking, and machinery. It is the commercial center of the region of Upper Lusatia, and a railway junction that makes it the transport center of a major lignite production area. The calculated population for 2005 was 57,097.

label: Bitterfeld

label: Roskilde
scope_note: The town of Roskilde in the county seat of the county commune of Roskilde, situated at the head of Roskilde Fjord in eastern Zealand, Denmark, in an area renowned for its ancient sacred springs. From ca. 1020 to 1416 it was the seat of the Danish kings and until 1443 the capital of Denmark. It was the most important ecclesiastical center in Denmark until the Protestant Reformation. In 1658 the Treaty of Roskilde was signed there, ending war with Sweden. Historic architecture includes the cathedral, partly Romanesque and partly Gothic, begun in 1170 and finished in 1464. A long line of Danish kings and queens are buried there. The modern town is a major railway center and its industrial activities feature bacon factories, tanneries, distilleries, and a high school for industrial workers. It serves as a residential suburb of Copenhagen. The 2004 estimated population was 43,700.

label: Natzwiller
scope_note: Town located approximately 31 miles southeast of Strasbourg. Nearby was the location of a Nazi concentration camp in World War II, known as Natzweiler-Struthof. The camp was built in 1941, and by March of 1945, had been evacuated by the Germans in advance of Allied forces. At least 17,000 prisoners died or were killed in the Natzweiler-Struthof camp and its subcamps.

label: Pau
scope_note: Pau was one of the pilgrimage sites on route to the Cathedral of Santiago de Compostela, home of the shrine dedicated to Saint James, the patron saint of Spain. The symbol of Saint James, the scalloped shell, became the primary symbol representing pilgrims. French pilgrimage routes to Compostela tend to follow old Roman roads, many of which continued to be utilized as primary roads of communication during the Middle Ages. The towns name Pau means "Palisade" in Béarnais. Archaeological studies indicate that in the beginning of the 13th century there were several palisades on the various levels of the cliff which overlooked the Gave de Pau. Located in Pau is a castle and the church of Saint-Martin.

label: La Réole
scope_note: La Réole was one of the pilgrimage sites on route to the Cathedral of Santiago de Compostela, home of the shrine dedicated to Saint James, the patron saint of Spain. The symbol of Saint James, the scalloped shell, became the primary symbol representing pilgrims. French pilgrimage routes to Compostela tend to follow old Roman roads, many of which continued to be utilized as primary roads of communication during the Middle Ages. Located in La Réole is the Priory of Saint-Pierre, a castle, and the Hôtel de Ville.

label: Clermont-Ferrand
scope_note: It began as a Roman settlement, and was the capital of the Arverni tribe, the original holders of the Auvergne region. Clermont was an important medieval ecclesiastical center from which Pope Urban II preached the First Crusade in 1095. It was the capital of the French duchy of Auvergne from 1556. The city in its present configuration and name was created in 1731 by the union of Clermont and Montferrand. IT sits on the Tretaine River, surrounded on three sides by mountains. In modern France it is the capital of the department of Puy-de-Dôme. It is a university town, and also a tourist and commercial center.

label: Riom
scope_note: A former fortified town, Riom was in medieval times a pilgrimage site, housing relics of the saint Amable. Under the rule of the Duc de Berry in the 14thcentury, it reverted to the French crown in 1531, after which it flourished as a royal judicial center. After the revolution it continued to be a judicial seat. It torn down its city walls in the 18th century. Site of many historic structures and inscriptions, in 1985 it was given the status of "Ville d'Art et d'Histoire." Its population is 19, 324 by a 2003 estimate.

label: Vichy
scope_note: A noted health spa & resort; has many thermal alkaline springs used since Roman period; exports its water & salts in large quantities; taken by Charles VII in 1440; seat of French government until complete occupation of France by Germany in 1942.

label: Bayeux
scope_note: First town to be liberated by Allied Forces in World War II.

label: Cherbourg
scope_note: A strongly fortified major French naval station; on site of ancient Roman station; ruled by English until 1200; pillaged by English in 1295; withstood sieges 1378, 1418 and 1450; held for ransom by English in 1758; birthplace of painter Jean-François Millet.

label: Saint-Lô
scope_note: Fortified by Charlemagne; pillaged by Normans 889, by Plantagenet 1141 & Edward III of England 1346; an important fortress & noted for its weaving in Middle Ages; almost completely destroyed in World War II; reconstruction began in 1948.

label: Saint-Lô
scope_note: Fortified by Charlemagne; pillaged by Normans 889, by Plantagenet 1141 & Edward III of England 1346; an important fortress & noted for its weaving in Middle Ages; almost completely destroyed in World War II; reconstruction began in 1948.

label: Alise-Sainte-Reine
scope_note: Modern town near the ancient site of Alesia.

label: Autun
scope_note: Residence of the Roman prefects of Gaul and an important center of learning in Roman times; sacked by Tetricus in 269 CE; destroyed during Germanic invasions; restored in the 9th century; was burned by English during the Hundred Years' War in 1379.

label: Chalon-sur-Saône
scope_note: An important town of the Gallic tribe of Aedui; exchanged for other fiefs in the Jura by Jean le Sage 1237; granted a charter 1256; held out against Austrian troops 1814; has 12th/15th-cen. cathedral, 14th-cen. church & 15th-cen. episcopal palace.

label: Clamecy
scope_note: Clamecy was one of the pilgrimage sites on route to the Cathedral of Santiago de Compostela, home of the shrine dedicated to Saint James, the patron saint of Spain. The symbol of Saint James, the scalloped shell, became the primary symbol representing pilgrims. French pilgrimage routes to Compostela tend to follow old Roman roads, many of which continued to be utilized as primary roads of communication during the Middle Ages. Located in Clamecy is the Chapel of Bethléem and the former Castle-Chaper.

label: Fleury
scope_note: Former inhabited place, located near the present-day memorial for the Battle of Verdun. The town was one of the defenses of Verdun in World War I; bloodiest battle of the war was fought here in 1916.

label: Nevers
scope_note: Nevers was one of the pilgrimage sites on route to the Cathedral of Santiago de Compostela, home of the shrine dedicated to Saint James, the patron saint of Spain. The symbol of Saint James, the scalloped shell, became the primary symbol representing pilgrims. French pilgrimage routes to Compostela tend to follow old Roman roads, many of which continued to be utilized as primary roads of communication during the Middle Ages. Nevers was constantly controlled by various powerful European families in the Middle Ages; for example, it was acquired by the Gonzaga family of Mantua in 1538 and later, in 1659, Nevers was given to the Mancini family by Cardinal Mazarin. Located in Nevers is the 11th-century Romanesque Cathedral of Saint-Cyr-et-Sainte-Julitte and many 13th-18th-century buildings.

label: Vézelay
scope_note: Vézelay is located on a hill on the left bank of the Cure River where a Benedictine abbey was founded in the 9th century; the town population increased after the reputed remains of St. Mary Magdalene were deposited at the abbey. Vézalay was also an important site for recruitment for the Second Crusade in the mid-12th century and it was one of the pilgrimage sites on route to the Cathedral of Santiago de Compostela, home of the shrine dedicated to Saint James, the patron saint of Spain. The symbol of Saint James, the scalloped shell, became the primary symbol representing pilgrims. French pilgrimage routes to Compostela tend to follow old Roman roads, many of which continued to be utilized as primary roads of communication during the Middle Ages.

label: Carnac
scope_note: Village on Quiberon Bay; site of thousands of megalithic monuments from the Neolithic Age (ca. 1800 BC); the most important are menhirs or standing stones (the so-called Alignements de Carnac), which may have served a religious or astronomical purpose.

label: Saint-Malo
scope_note: Named after Maclou, a Welsh monk who fled to Brittany; became part of France in 1491; prospered as center for navigators, traders & privateers 17th-18th cen.; birthplace of 16th-cen. explorer Jacques Cartier; largely destroyed during WW II, later rebuilt.

label: Bourges
scope_note: Bourges is located almost exactly in the center of France and lies on the Canal du Berry, at the convergence of the Yèvre and Auron rivers. It was one of the pilgrimage sites on route to the Cathedral of Santiago de Compostela. The  hill on which the city is built is crowned with the 12th-century Gothic cathedral of Saint-Étienne. The palace of Jacques Coeur, chief financier to Charles VII, is an exellent source of French 15th-century civil architecture. Bourges is the sheep, cattle, wine, and cereals marketing center for the region. In 52 BCE, Julius Caesar recognized the city as one of the most beautiful cities in Gaul. Saint Ursin brought Christianity to Bourges in the 3rd century.  During the Hundred Years' War, Charles VII resided there between the years of 1422 and 1437, and Joan of Arc wintered there between the years of 1429 and 1430. Louis XI,  was born in Bourges and endowed the city in 1463 with a university, which was abolished during the French Revolution.

label: Montargis
scope_note: Has remains of castle which was former royal residence; site of bronze statue of "Dog of Montargis," legendary dog of Aubry de Montdidier, which tracked down his master's murderer & vanquished him in judicial duel arranged by Charles V in 1371.

label: Montbazon
scope_note: Montbazon was one of the pilgrimage sites on route to the Cathedral of Santiago de Compostela, home of the shrine dedicated to Saint James, the patron saint of Spain. The symbol of Saint James, the scalloped shell, became the primary symbol representing pilgrims. French pilgrimage routes to Compostela tend to follow old Roman roads, many of which continued to be utilized as primary roads of communication during the Middle Ages. Located in Montbazon is an 11th-century castle which was modified in the 12th century.

label: Cérès
wikidata_description: tapestry and heritage monument (PM75003536) in the Hôtel de la Marine, Paris, France

label: Bonifacio
scope_note: Located on a narrow peninsula with steep limestone cliffs facing the sea on three sides; according to legend, it was founded and named by Boniface, marquis of Tuscany, in 828; taken by the Genoese in 1187; a Genoese dialect is still spoken here.

label: Belfort
scope_note: Belfort is the capital of the department of Belfort, located on the Savoureuse River. History first records it in the 13th century as a possession of the counts of Montbéliard, who granted it a charter 1307. It passed to the archdukes of Austria; then was ceded to France in 1648.It was occupied by Germans in the 1870s and 1940s. The town features a huge outdoor sculpture, the "Lion of Belfort," created 1871-80, carved out of the red sandstone of a hill overlooking Belfort by Frédéric-Auguste Bartholdi, the designer of the Statue of Liberty.

label: Roppe
wikidata_description: commune in Territoire de Belfort, France

label: Elbeuf
scope_note: Built on site of Roman city; occupied by English during Hundred Years' War; passed to House of Lorraine; traditional center of wool and cloth manufacture; has automobile, chemical, electrical, and rubber industries; site of many Renaissance churches.

label: Béziers
scope_note: Surrounded by old walls; has ancient Gallic fortress; captured by Romans 120 BC; a stronghold of viscounts of Carcassone 12th cen.; scene of massacre of 20,000 people for having harbored Albigenses 1209; seat of episcopal see until 1790.

label: Carcassonne
scope_note: Was important medieval fortified center; was taken by Saracens in 728; flourished as seat of viscountship 11th-13th cen.; taken by Simon de Montfort 1209; went to France 1247; destroyed by Black Prince 1355; mix of Iberian, Celtic & Roman influences; an immense stone arch is a reminder of the Visigoth Empire.

label: Saint-Guilhem-le-Désert
scope_note: Saint-Guilhem-le-Désert was one of the pilgrimage sites on route to the Cathedral of Santiago de Compostela, home of the shrine dedicated to Saint James, the patron saint of Spain. French pilgrimage routes to Compostela tend to follow old Roman roads, many of which continued to be utilized as primary roads of communication during the Middle Ages. Important historical structures located in Saint-Guilhem-le-Désert include the former Abbey-Church of Saint-Guihem and Saint-Sauvear, the village with several houses with Romanesque facades of the 12th century, and a bridge called the Pont du Diable.

label: Brive-la-Gaillarde
scope_note: Rock caves show evidence of prehistoric culture leaving great stone monuments; has monastery founded by St. Anthony of Padua 1226; site of Romanesque church of Saint-Martin, an example of 12th-century Limousin art; agrarian and industrial economy prevail.

label: Nogaro
scope_note: Nogaro is one of the pilgrimage sites on route to the Cathedral of Santiago de Compostela, home of the shrine dedicated to Saint James, the patron saint of Spain. The symbol of Saint James, the scalloped shell, became the primary symbol representing pilgrims. French pilgrimage routes to Compostela tend to follow old Roman roads, many of which continued to be utilized as primary roads of communication during the Middle Ages. Historic sites in Nogaro include the church and monastery of Saint Nicolás.

label: Tarbes
scope_note: The town was occupied by Romans. It was seized for a time by the Saracens (Arabs). In the 10th century it became the capital of the ancient countship of Bigorre, and it was captured by the English during the Hundred Years' War (1337-1453). It suffered greatly in the Wars of Religion in the late 16th century. It was the scene of an English victory over the French 1814. It is noted as the birthplace of the poet Théophile Gautier and Marshall Ferdinand Foch.

label: Boulogne-sur-Mer
scope_note: Destroyed and inhabitants massacred by Normans in 882; the prize in disputes between Flanders and Ponthieu; held by England 1544-1550; destroyed by Emperor Charles V; site where Napoleon's army prepared for attack on England in 1805.

label: Calais
scope_note: Village was improved by Count of Flanders in 997; fortified by Count of Boulogne 1224; withstood long siege by English in 1346, until it was starved out; retrieved from English 1558; occupied by Spanish 1596-1598; returned to France by Treaty of Vervins.

label: Cambrai
scope_note: Was a Roman center on Escaut river; was a Frankish capital by 445 CE; obtained rights from bishop in 1227; was longtime pawn of contending rulers; league against Venice was formed here 1508; site of signing of Peace of Cambrai 1529; ceded to France 1678.

label: Valenciennes
scope_note: Ruled by Charlemagne 811; part of Holy Roman Empire; passed to counts of Hainaut 1047; famous for lacemaking 15th cen.; taken by Louis XIV 1677; ceded to France 1678; besieged 1814; captured by Germans 1914-1918; birthplace of Jean Watteau 1684.

label: Cholet
scope_note: Name derived from Latin "cauletum" ("cabbage"), for the local cabbage crop; old buildings were destroyed during Wars of the Vendée in 1793-1794, rebuilt in 19th cen.; site of Romano-Byzantine style church of Sacred Heart; an important cattle market.

label: La Fère
scope_note: An important town on the Hindenburg Line, under German occupation 3 September 1914 to 10 October 1918.

label: Cannes
scope_note: Occupied by Phocaeans, Celts & Romans; under protection of Monks of Lérins 4th cen.; twice destroyed by Moors; Napoleon's landing spot on his escape from Elba 1815; marked E limit of US landing in World War II; site of International Film Festival.
wikidata_description: French commune and city in Alpes-Maritimes, Provence-Alpes-Côte d'Azur

label: Menton
scope_note: Located close to Italian border; famous health & winter resort; originally belonged to counts of Ventimiglia, a noble Genoese family; purchased in 14th cen. by princes of Monaco who governed it until 1848; purchased by France 1860; Grimaldi caves nearby.

label: Orange
scope_note: Located in a fertile plain on the right bank of the Rhône River, north of Avignon; the Battle of Arausio was here in 105 BCE in which the Romans were defeated by the Cimbri and Teutones; later conquered by Rome; became episcopal see in the 3rd century; an earldom ca. 800; independent in the 11th century; inherited by William the Silent in 1554; conquered by Louis XIV in 1672; ceded to France in 1713 by the Treaty of Utrecht; famous today for its Roman ruins including a semicircular theater that is the best preserved of its kind and a triumphal arch that is one of the Roman Empire's largest.

label: Salon-de-Provence
wikidata_description: commune and city in Bouches-du-Rhône, France

label: Toulon
scope_note: Seiged by Saracens in the 9th century; passed to French crown with Provence in 1481; taken by Charles V in 1524 and 1536; scene of Napoleonic victory over English, Spanish, and French royalists 1793; important naval station in World War I and World War II.
wikidata_description: capital city of Var department, Southern France

label: Bourg-Saint-Andéol
scope_note: Site of Mithraic center ca. 500 CE; monuments include a Romanesque church.

label: Gap
scope_note: Was an ancient center; was capital of medieval Gapençais; annexed by French crown in 1512; sacked by Huguenots in 1567 & 1577 during French Wars of Religion; noted for 17th-cen. cathedral & carved tomb by Jacob Richier (from 1613).

label: Mâcon
scope_note: A communications & railroad center; site of international wine fair; a wine trading center; industries include copper founding, printing & rope making; has remains of 12th-cen. cathedral; a Huguenot stronghold during 16th cen.

label: Tourcoing
scope_note: Located in N France on Belgian frontier, NE of Lille; one of chief textile centers of France; industries include soap works & sugar refineries; captured by Germans in World War I in 1914 & suffered great damage.

label: Bagneux
scope_note: Suburb located S of Paris; noted as site of battle during siege of Paris in October, 1870.

label: Fleury-sur-Orne
scope_note: Was a center of monastic reform during the Middle Ages.

label: Issy-les-Moulineaux
scope_note: A SW suburb of Paris; site where Bishop Jacques-Bénigne Bossuet & other churchmen gathered in attempt to settle doctrine of Quietism 1694-1695; modern industries include aeronautics, metallurgy, & production of chemicals & electrical equipment.

label: Sèvres
scope_note: SW residential suburb of Paris, on left bank of Seine; famous for the Manufacture Nationale de Sèvres, the porcelain factory established by Louis XV & Madame Pompadour in 1756; the Treaty of Sèvres, signed 10 Aug. 1920, abolished the Ottoman Empire.

label: Bich'vinta
scope_note: Sits on the location of what was once the ancient city of Pityus.

label: Gori
scope_note: Located on Kura river; was an ancient center; was fortress for Armenians in 12th century; was destroyed by Nadir Shah of Persia in 18th century; noted as birthplace of Joseph Stalin (1879-1953, dictator of the USSR.

label: Amfípolis
scope_note: Located at the mouth of the Struma river on Aegean Sea; founded by Athens as military garrison in 5th century.BCE. captured by Sparta during Peloponnesian Wars; captured by Philip II of Macedon, causing war with Athens; modern town covers ancient site.

label: Áthos
scope_note: Site is a mountain forming eastern end of the Acte peninsula; it has been occupied by Greek monastic communities of St. Basil since 9th century CE; noted as the "Holy Mountain" of the Greek church; declared itself a theocratic republic in 1927.

label: Dhéndra
scope_note: Inhabited until early Bronze Age; noted for a Bronze Age cemetery. Located outside modern village of the same name.

label: Aíyion
scope_note: Very ancient settlement; was described by Homer as part of domain of Agamemnon; one of 12 cities of Achaea in Classical times; declined in importance after Augustan period; modern city largely covers ancient remains.

label: Evritanía
scope_note: Note that this and other historical departments (prefectures) were abolished with the Kallikratis reform in 2010, although they have been largely replaced by comparable regional units.

label: Bodrum
scope_note: Located on Gökova Körfezi, opposite the Greek island of Kos; site of ancient city famed for the tomb of King Mausolus (351 BCE), one of the 7 wonders of the ancient world; modern town was developed by the Crusading Order of Hospitallers in 15th cen.

label: Kos
scope_note: Located on NE coast of island; was an important settlement in ancient times; badly damaged in earthquakes of146 and 554 CE.

label: Krannon
wikidata_description: town and polis in Ancient Greece

label: Lárisa
scope_note: An extremely old settlement; was chief city of ancient Thessaly; ruled by Aleudai family from 6th cen. BC; allied with Persia during Xerxes's invasion 5th cen. BC; capital of Thessalian League in Roman times; later held by Franks, Byzantines & Turks.

label: Míloi
scope_note: Was the most important early Helladic site in Greece; contains ruins of a sumptuous House of Tiles that was probably destroyed by invading early Greek tribes ca. 2200 BC; into the mound over this ruin were sunk Mycenaean grave shafts.

label: Lykosoura
scope_note: Ruined city located 7 km W of Megalopolis; Pausanias in 2nd cen. CE referred to sanctuary of very ancient Chthonic diety, Despoina; city walls date to 5th cen. BCE.

label: Mílos, Nísos
scope_note: Was a center of early civilization, due to strategic location between Crete and the mainland, as well as its deposits of obsidian.

label: Methone
scope_note: Methone was discovered by the Cassini spacecraft team in the summer of 2004. It has a diameter of only 3 km (2 miles) and is located between the orbits of moons Mimas and Enceladus. It may be the object spotted by NASA's Voyager spacecraft in 1981 and called at that time S/1981 S14.

label: Monemvasía
scope_note: Located on rocky promontory off the coast of Peloponnesus; was a refuge for Laconian Greeks; flourished as leading commercial port & fortress under Byzantine Empire; changed hands between Venice & Turks several times from 15th-19th cen.; noted for wine.

label: Neméa
scope_note: Located  at the head of the Nemea river, about 19 km N of Argos and 18 km from the Gulf of Corinth. Site of the Panhellenic Games and the Sanctuary of Nemean Zeus from the 4th century BCE.

label: Olynthos
scope_note: Located three km inland from bay of Terone, built atop two flat-topped hills; there was habitation in Late Neolithic period, but was deserted in Bronze Age; continuous habitation again occurred from around 1000 BCE; Iron Age settlement included Boiotians; population expanded after 432 BCE.

label: Orkhomenós
scope_note: Located next to the village of Skripou (now also called "Orchomenos") on Cephisus river, at the foot of a rocky ridge known in antiquity as Akontion. Inhabited from the Neolithic through the Hellenistic periods. Formerly lay on the shore of Lake Kopais. First recorded in Homer's Iliad. Home to the Minyae; later was subject of Thebes, but sided with Sparta in 379 BCE; was destroyed and rebuilt several times in Antiquity. Here Heinrich Schliemann found articles of a pottery type that he called "Minyan ware."

label: Orkhomenós
scope_note: Located next to the village of Skripou (now also called "Orchomenos") on Cephisus river, at the foot of a rocky ridge known in antiquity as Akontion. Inhabited from the Neolithic through the Hellenistic periods. Formerly lay on the shore of Lake Kopais. First recorded in Homer's Iliad. Home to the Minyae; later was subject of Thebes, but sided with Sparta in 379 BCE; was destroyed and rebuilt several times in Antiquity. Here Heinrich Schliemann found articles of a pottery type that he called "Minyan ware."

label: Patmos
scope_note: Located on southern end of the island.

label: Porta Panagia
