label: Psykhro Cave
scope_note: Ancient Minoan sacred cave. Possibly is Diktaean cave of legend, where (in Hymn of the Kouretes) Zeus was born in order to hide him from his father Kronos, who had been warned that one of his own children would dethrone him; site of remains from shrines from the Middle Minoan to Archaic Greek times.

label: Rhamnous
scope_note: Was the most distant of Athenian demes (communes), overlooking a strait separating the mainland from Euboia; due to this strategic location, became a fortified garrison town for Athens in 5th cen. BCE; flourished in Hellenistic period.

label: Salamís
scope_note: Located in the Saronic Gulf; noted as site of naval battle with Persians in 480 BC, & later was haven for Athenian refugees; a Greek naval base is now located on the island.

label: Thívai
scope_note: At one time the "seven-gated city of Thebes" was the seat of one of the oldest and greatest powers of Greece. Only a few ruins of the city remain today on the Cadmea, the acropolis of ancient Thebes. It was named for Cadmus, the mythical founder of the city. Thebes was the main city of ancient Boeotia, and is identified with many legends, including stories of Dirce, Epigonus, Oedipus and the Sphinx. It entered a power struggle with Athens in the 6th cen. BCE. It was destroyed by Alexander the Great.

label: Trípolis
scope_note: Town was founded by Turks, & flourished as seat of Turkish pashas of Morea (Peloponneus) from 14th cen.; in Greek war of independence, it was captured by Greeks, then burned by Ottomans in 1828.

label: Adlestrop
scope_note: Humphrey Repton designed the gardens at Adlestrop Park (ca. 1750).

label: Avening
scope_note: Stone Age long barrows are here.

label: Bakewell
scope_note: Central town of the Peak District, where the famous Bakewell tart originated; Roman and Saxon well sites here; Chatsworth and Haddon Hall are nearby.

label: Barrow-in-Furness
scope_note: Located on Furness peninsula; founded on iron and steel industry and planned in the mid-19th century by locomotive engineer, James Ramsden; first British Polaris submarine was built here in 1964; industries include paper, engineering, chemicals, and offshore gas.

label: Beechwood Park
wikidata_description: sports venue in City of Edinburgh, Scotland, UK

label: Belvedere House
wikidata_description: house in Perth and Kinross, Scotland, UK

label: Berkeley
scope_note: Where Double Gloucester cheese is made; Edward II was murdered in the 11th-cen. castle; birthplace of Edward Jenner (1749-1823), who discovered vaccination.

label: Berkhamsted
scope_note: Market town; ruins of the 11th-cen. castle where Edgar Atheling submitted to William I are here; the High Street is on the line of the Roman Akeman Street.

label: Blaise Castle
wikidata_description: 1766 folly near Henbury in Bristol, England

label: Blenheim Palace
scope_note: Royal manor built by Sir John Vanbrugh in 1704 for Duke of Marlborough, to honor his victory over French & Bavarians; built in heavy, ornate English Baroque style; includes a man-made lake by Capability Brown, a deer park & private chapel.

label: Bournemouth
scope_note: Popular resort since ca. 1810, when town grew around residence of Dorset squire, Lewis Tregonwell; expanded with railways 1870; called "Sandbourne" in Thomas Hardy's novel Tess of the D'Urbervilles; includes large residential areas & some light industry.

label: Bowood
wikidata_description: former civil parish, now in Calne Without, Wiltshire, England

label: Bradford
scope_note: Near Cookbury.

label: Brighton
scope_note: Located on English Channel; first mentioned in Domesday Book of 1086; was important seaside resort by 18th cen.; King George IV restored town in Regency style. noted for John Nash's Indian-style Brighton Pavillion (1817); became a city with Hove in 2000.
wikidata_description: city of Brighton & Hove, in East Sussex, England

label: Brighton
scope_note: Located on English Channel; first mentioned in Domesday Book of 1086; was important seaside resort by 18th cen.; King George IV restored town in Regency style. noted for John Nash's Indian-style Brighton Pavillion (1817); became a city with Hove in 2000.
wikidata_description: city of Brighton & Hove, in East Sussex, England

label: Bristol
scope_note: Located on River Avon; was a wool center in the 12th century; John and Sebastian Cabot sailed from here to New World 1497; center for sugar, tobacco, cotton and slave trade 17th-18th centuries; railway and dock expanded during Industrial Revolution; heavily bombed in World War II.
wikidata_description: city in South West England, United Kingdom

label: Burton Agnes
scope_note: The Old Hall here was built ca. 1170-75 by Robert de Stuteville and features a vaulted undercroft with piers and carved water-leaf capitals. The 17th-cen. Hall, built ca. 1601-10, features bow windows. Nearby is the site of a Romano-British settlement.

label: Bury Saint Edmunds
scope_note: Town grew around 7th-cen. monastery, built by Sigebert, King of East Angles; noted for 10th-cen. shrine of St. Edmund & ruins of 11th-cen. Benedictine abbey, where barons drew up basis for Magna Carta in in 1214; site of Town Hall (1780) by Robert Adam.

label: Canterbury
scope_note: Country's principal religious center, immortalized in Chaucer's Canterbury Tales; badly damaged by Danes in 1011 and bombed during World War II; Protestants executed here under Mary I in the 1550s; weaving center in the 17th century; site of ruins of Roman walls and theater; cathedral begun in 1070; city has Norman walls also.

label: Capesthorne Hall
scope_note: Rebuilt by Blore in 1820; chapel of 1772 is earliest work of John Wood the Elder; contains collection of paintings by Marieschi and Joli and Attic pottery.

label: Carlisle
scope_note: Important military post during Roman times; destroyed by Norse invaders ca. 875 and restored by English King William II the Rufus in 1092; ceded to Scots 1136-1157 and during the English Civil War (1642-1645); became major textile and railway center after the 1830s.

label: Cartmel
scope_note: There is a beautiful priory church here founded in 1188; also a 14th-century gatehouse; historically located in Lancashire.

label: Chichester
scope_note: Located on coastal plain of English Channel; retains plan of original Roman town; was important wool center during Middle Ages; noted for 11th- and 17th-century cathedral, Early English style Bishop's Palace and octagonal Market Cross (1501).

label: Corfe Castle
scope_note: Ruins here of a castle originally built by William I on a fortified Saxon site; Cromwell's Roundheads blew up the castle in 1646.

label: Coventry
scope_note: Town grew around Benedictine priory founded 1043 by Leofric, Earl of Mercia; site of legendary ride of Lady Godiva in the 11th century; center of many textile factories by the 18th century; destroyed by air attack in World War II; today industries include car and tool factories.

label: Coventry
scope_note: Town grew around Benedictine priory founded 1043 by Leofric, Earl of Mercia; site of legendary ride of Lady Godiva in the 11th century; center of many textile factories by the 18th century; destroyed by air attack in World War II; today industries include car and tool factories.

label: Derby
scope_note: Founded near Roman site of Derventio; one of Five Boroughs under the Danes in the 9th century; porcelain making began 1750 and given royal stamp 1773; also important for textiles; birthplace of painter Joseph Wright (1734-1797) and philosopher William Spencer (1820-1893).
wikidata_description: city in Derbyshire, in the East Midlands region of England

label: Derbyshire
scope_note: Consists of bleak moorlands in the north and lowlands of River Trent in the south; occupied since prehistoric times; formed part of kingdom of Mercia in 7th century; area remained pastoral until mining began in 18th century; important for textiles in 18th and 19th centuries.

label: Dorchester
scope_note: Located on River Frome; once the Roman town of 'Durnovaria;' nearby remains include Roman ampitheater at Mambury Rings and prehistoric fort at Maiden Castle; site of Franciscan priory founded in 1331; was a cloth center in the 16th century; famous citizens include Thomas Hardy and the poet William Barnes; Judge Jeffreys held his Bloddy Assize here after Monmouth's Rebellion.

label: East Meon
scope_note: 14th-cen. Court House is here.

label: Eastry
scope_note: Eastry Court is said to stand on the site of an ancient royal hall.

label: Englefield
scope_note: King Aethelwulf was victorious over the Danes here prior to King Aethelred's victory at the Battle of Ashdown in 870.

label: Greenwich
scope_note: Thames-side London borough; developed by the Stuart kings; the royal palace was the birthplace of Henry VIII, Queen Mary and Elizabeth I; historically located in the county of Kent.
wikidata_description: royal borough in the London Region in England

label: Guildford
scope_note: Located on the River Wey, Guildford was first mentioned as a borough in 1131. Its economy is based on railways, engineering, plastics, and pharmaceuticals. Guildford is noted for the 16th-century Royal King Edward VI Grammar School and the Women's Royal Army Corp museum.

label: Halesowen
scope_note: Located on River Stour, 8 miles SW of Birmingham; economy based on iron, electronic equipment & brick making.

label: Hampshire
scope_note: Part of Anglo-Saxon kingdom of Wessex in the 4th century; includes small Bronze Age farms, Iron Age hill forts, and Roman roads; county first mentioned in Anglo-Saxon Chronicle of 755; remained in episcopal see of Winchester 676-1927; besieged by Danes in the 9th and 11th centuries.

label: Harewood
scope_note: There are ruins of a 12th-century castle here. Also Harewood House, a magnificent 18th-century home with grounds by Capability Brown.

label: Hereford
scope_note: Roman and Saxon settlement; served as a fortress on Welsh border in the 7th century; was feudal holding 1086-1189, until sold to citizens by Richard I; wool trade important until the 16th century; 11th-century cathedral exemplifies styles from Norman to Perpendicular.

label: Highnam
scope_note: A Cromwellian manor house is here.

label: Ince Blundell
scope_note: There is an 18th-cen. hall here whose artworks include ancient Roman sculpture.

label: Inveraray Castle
wikidata_description: country house near Inveraray in the county of Argyll, in western Scotland

label: Kent
scope_note: Comprises chalk cliffs, grasslands and woodlands; inhabited since prehistoric times; settled by Romans ca. 43; invaded by Jutes and Saxons in the 5th century; in Middle Ages, pilgrims came to Canterbury and Rochester cathedrals; famous for its fruits and vegetables.
wikidata_description: ceremonial county of England, United Kingdom

label: Kilpeck
scope_note: Norman church (1135) here with Saxon remains & red sandstone carvings; also a ruined castle that once belonged to William FitzNorman.

label: Lancashire
scope_note: Consists of level plateaus, moorlands and river valleys; occupied in prehistoric and Roman times; suffered from Black Plague, War of Roses, and Scottish Border Wars; was large textile center from the late 18th century, but recent decline precipitated emigration.
wikidata_description: ceremonial county in North-West England, United Kingdom

label: Ledbury
scope_note: Main fruit market in Herefordshire; huge minster church here rivals the cathedral of Hereford; where William Langland conceived of 'Piers Plowman.'

label: Lincoln
scope_note: Important Roman town on line of Fosse Way and Ermine Sreet; Roman remains include stone gates, fountains, and baths; there is also a large 12th-century cathedral; castle built by William I; site of rebellion during reign of Henry VIII; industry began in the 18th century; birthplace of tanks during World War I.

label: Macclesfield
scope_note: Located on River Bollin 17 miles south of Manchester; 13th-century St. Michael's church sit at top of 108 steep steps; economy based on silk, cork, shoe, and electrical appliance manufacturing.

label: Melbourne
scope_note: Was a large royal manor in the Middle Ages. Norman church of St. Michael-with-St.-Mary (ca. before 1152) was the Bishop of Carlisle's: it has an imposing nave with dog-toothed arches; Melbourne Hall's gardens were laid out ca. 1700 for Thomas Coke by London and Wise in the style of André le Nôtre, gardener to Louis XIV; only a chunk of wall remains of the 14th-century castle.

label: Perth
scope_note: Located on River Tay; made a royal burgh by David I in 1210; held by English 1335-1339; James I of Scotland was assassinated here in 1437; scene of Gowrie Conspiracy to kidnap James I of England in 1600; manufacturing center for twine, whisky & glass.

label: Pitsligo
wikidata_description: Scottish parish in Aberdeenshire, Scotland, UK

label: Plymouth
scope_note: Lies between rivers Plym and Tamar; was point of departure for ships attacking Spanish Armada in 1588 and for the 16th century. Pilgrims setting sail for America; was Parliamentary stronghold during English Civil War; was heavily bombed during early phases of WW II.

label: Retford
scope_note: Market town including East and West Retford, divided by the River Idle. Name refers to the clay red-tinged water of the river here. The area was first settled on the West side of the river, but the eastern bank became the larger prominent settlement and claims the name today. First chartered in 1246 when Henry III granted the right for a fair; right for a Saturday market was granted by Edward I in 1275.

label: Romsey
scope_note: Was site of abbey constructed in 10th-12th cen.; also noted for King John's Hunting Box, a 13th-cen. house; a 12th-cen. church is here.

label: Romsey
scope_note: Was site of abbey constructed in 10th-12th cen.; also noted for King John's Hunting Box, a 13th-cen. house; a 12th-cen. church is here.

label: Sherborne
scope_note: 1000-year-old town, dominated by Sherborne Abbey.

label: Somerset
scope_note: Consists of a low-lying basin, bounded on the northeast by Mendip Hills and on the west by Quantock Hills; occupied by prehistoric peoples; Romans mined lead in area; formed part of Kingdom of Wessex in 7th century; distinctive "Zummerzetaheer" dialect is spoken in some areas.

label: Southampton
scope_note: Located near head of Southampton Water; site of Roman & early Anglo-Saxon settlements; developed as important port after 11th-cen. Norman Conquest; embarkation point of Richard I during Crusades & Pilgrims leaving for America; bombed during WW II.
wikidata_description: city and major port in Hampshire, South-East England, United Kingdom

label: Speen
scope_note: Adjoining Newbury; Speen House is here.

label: Stourbridge
scope_note: Located on River Stour 11 miles W of Birmingham; site of trade fairs ca. 1500; connected with water transport system during Industrial Revolution; produces glass & tools.

label: Stourbridge
scope_note: Located on River Stour 11 miles W of Birmingham; site of trade fairs ca. 1500; connected with water transport system during Industrial Revolution; produces glass & tools.

label: Stratford-upon-Avon
scope_note: Located on the River Avon; famous as birthplace of William Shakespeare; sights & events related to the playwright include Royal Shakespeare Theatre (1932), library & art gallery, birthday festivals & plays; site of 16th-cen. cottage of Anne Hathaway.

label: Tarporley
scope_note: Oldest hunting club in England is here.

label: Tissington
scope_note: Considered one of the Peak District's prettiest villages; famous well-dressing festival is held here.

label: Upton House
wikidata_description: Grade II listed building in Carmarthenshire. Situated opposite junction with Victoria Crescent.

label: Wantage
scope_note: A tiny Norman church is here; King Alfred was born here in 849.

label: Wantage
scope_note: A tiny Norman church is here; King Alfred was born here in 849.

label: Warwick
scope_note: Located on River Avon; famous for Warwick Castle, built in 14th cen. on site of 10th-cen. fortress; although ancient, much of town's character is derived from rebuilding after 1694 fire; supports some light industry.

label: Warwickshire
scope_note: County in central England, in the Midlands; drained by River Avon and headwaters of River Cherwell; comprises coal measures, woodlands, and meadows; evidence of prehistoric and Roman occupation; Roman road, Watling Street still forms part of county border; mostly agricultural, especially dairying and fruit-growing; county lost its more industrial northwestern area, including Birmingham, Coventry, and Solihull, to the West Midlands under local government reorganization in 1974.

label: Wilton House
wikidata_description: Grade II listed building in Pembrokeshire. On NE side of street some 50m S of its junction with High Street.

label: Wiltshire
scope_note: County in southern England; watershed area separating basins of Bristol Channel, English Channel and River Thames; chalk uplands populated in prehistoric times and contains many stone monuments and burial mounds, including Neolithic Stonehenge and Avebury; primarily an agricultural area; administrative center is Trowbridge; Swindon became an independent unitary authority in 1997.
wikidata_description: unitary authority (doesn't include Swindon) in Wiltshire, South West England, United Kingdom

label: Wimborne Minster
scope_note: Market town; Ethelred, king of the West Saxons and brother of Alfred the Great, is said to be buried here.

label: Winchester
scope_note: Ruled by many Saxon and Danish kings from the 7th to the 11th century; William the Conqueror, crowned here 1066, made city joint capital with London; cloth trade center 7th-12th centuries; burned during reign of King Stephen (1135-1154); famous for its 11th-/14th-century cathedral.

label: Worcester
scope_note: Located on the east bank of River Severn; modern town grew around 11th- and14th-century Norman castle; was textile center in Middle Ages; site of Battle of Worcester of 1651 that ended the English Civl War; has been famous for fine porcelain since the 18th century.

label: Wotton-under-Edge
scope_note: Important wool town in the 17th-19th centuries; Isaac Pitman developed his shorthand system here.

label: Yattendon
scope_note: Village that was once a market town; Bronze Age implements ('The Yattendon Hoard') were discovered here.

label: York
scope_note: Originally a settlement of Celtic Brigantes. Occupied by the Romans in 71 CE; it was the Romans' northern military headquarters and later capital of the province of Britannia Inferior. Emperor Severus died here in 211; Constantine proclaimed emperor by his troops in 306. York was the center of the Norse kingdom in the 10th century. In the Middle Ages it was a wool production and adminstrative center. Site of 12th-century York Minster church, as well as the ruins of medieval St. Mary's Abbey.
wikidata_description: city in North Yorkshire, England, United Kingdom

label: Mumbai
scope_note: Under Hindu rule until 1348, then taken by Muslims; ceded to Portugal by Sultan of Gujarat 1534; ceded to Great Britain in marriage agreement between Charles II and the Portuguese Infanta Catherine; center for British East India Company from 1685 to 1708. Under British imperial rule, the city was known as Bombay. It was renamed to Mumbai in 1995.

label: Jakarta
scope_note: Situated within Jawa Barat province; borders Teluk Jakarta to the north. Considered a national capital district, with the status of a first level subdivision.
wikidata_description: capital and largest city of Indonesia

label: Sebatu
wikidata_description: village in Gianyar Regency, Bali, Indonesia

label: Tell Abu Shahrein
scope_note: Ancient Sumerian city; the earliest known settlement in southern  Mesopotamia; inhabited from 5000 BCE to 600 BCE; one of most important urban centers of southern Babylonia; dedicated to the water god Ea.

label: Calah
scope_note: Founded in the 13th century BCE by Shalmaneser I; declined in the 7th century BCE since Sargonids used Nineveh as their residence; sacked 614 BCE. Ancient Assyrian city was called Kalhu, called by Arabic name, Nimrud.

label: Sippar
scope_note: Was one of chief cities of Sumer, then located on E bank of Euphrates river; was a capital of Sargon of Akkad from ca. 2637 BCE; was religious center for worship of Shamash through 7th cen. BCE; often sacked; taken by Cyrus the Great of Persia in 539 BCE.

label: Tel Aviv-Yafo
scope_note: Modern city founded in 1909 by Jews from Yafo; population expanded in 1920s & after World War II; capital of Israel 1948-Dec.1949; in 1950 Tel Aviv & Yafo merged to form the largest city in Israel & the country's cultural, commercial & financial center.

label: Caulonia
scope_note: Founded by Achaean colonists in the 8th-7th centuries BCE; an ancient city of Magna Graecia on the shore of the Ionian Sea.  After the destruction of the city by Rome in 200 BCE, the inhabitants moved inland to found Stilida, modern Stilo. Formerly believed to be on the site of Castelvetere (now also called Caulonia).

label: Mugello
scope_note: Area north of Florence, between the Apennine ridge & the Arno Valley.

label: Sicilia
scope_note: The region comprises the large island of the same name and several nearby smaller islands. Sicily became a major center of revolutionary movements in the 19th century: as a result of Giuseppe Garibaldi's revolt, it was liberated from the Bourbons in 1860 and in the following year it was incorporated into the united kingdom of Italy. Sicily gained regional autonomy in 1947.

label: Avezzano
scope_note: Located in the Fucino basin on land that was reclaimed in mid-19th cen.; was destroyed by earthquake in 1915, but rebuilt; was heavily damaged in WW II.

label: Corfinio
scope_note: Modern day town that is adjacent to the ancient ruins of the city of Corfinium.

label: Lanciano
scope_note: Was important Roman town; was important medieval center; was famous until 17th cen. for fairs that attracted merchants from Italy, France & the Balkans.

label: Pescara
scope_note: Located on Adriatic Sea at mouth of Pescara river; was established by Romans; was nearly destroyed in Germanic invasions; again flourished in Middle Ages; has often been scene of fighting by rival powers; was heavily damaged in WW II.

label: Pisticci
scope_note: Center was established in ancient times; was important center of the Normans; was held by various families in Middle Ages.

label: Policoro

label: Caulonia
scope_note: The town probably dates to Late Antiquity, when the settlement was known as Castrum Vetus. The name of Castelvetere was changed in 1862 because the citizens believed their town was the site of ancient city Caulonia. It has since been proven that ancient Caulonia was to be found 16 km away, near modern Monasterace.

label: Locri
scope_note: Near the ancient center of Locri. After 1850 Gerace Marina developed along the coast  forming a new center. In 1934 it changed its name in Locri.

label: Papasídero
scope_note: Noted for medieval castle & archaeological site of nearby cave of Romito.

label: Taverna
scope_note: Name derives from Latin Taberna, with reference to its function as a rest stop along Via Romana, which ascended from the coast to Sila.

label: Corfinium
scope_note: Ancient town of Samnium; capital of the short-lived republic of Italia, founded in 1st century BCE; taken by Julius Caesar 49 BCE; was important center on crossroads of Via Valeria & Via Claudia Nova; modern town grew up to north of ancient site.

label: Brescello
scope_note: Town on Po River, 11 miles NE of Parma; the Roman emperor Otho committed suicide here in 69 CE.

label: Marzabotto
scope_note: Town and commune. Was site of large massacre of civilians during WW II. Noted for a nearby site that is among the most thoroughly excavated and studied Etruscan cities.

label: Fondi
scope_note: Located on Appian Way near the Lago di Fondi; settlements here date to 1000 BCE; was a Volsci town; had limited Roman citizenship by 338 BCE; was papal property from 5th cen. BCE; sacked by Lombards in 592 CE & Saracens in 846 & 1534; held successively by several families in Middle Ages.

label: Latina
scope_note: Was first center established in newly reclaimed Pontine Marshes in 1932; industries include a beet-sugar refinery, vegetable cannery & glass factory; nuclear power plant is nearby.

label: Roma
scope_note: City positioned on 7 hills over the swampy Tiber river area; one of the oldest continuously occupied sites in Europe. Archaeological evidence attests to human occupation of the area from ca. 14,000 years ago, but the dense layer of later debris obscures Palaeolithic and Neolithic sites. Was an Etruscan city by 8th cen. BCE, their kings expelled and republic established by 500 BCE; soon ruled vast area and was center of Empire from 31 BCE; declined when capital moved to Constantinople in 330 CE; revived under popes.

scope_note: Located on Esino river; colonized by Romans; destroyed by Goths and Lombards; given to Church by Frankish king Pepin III in 756; supported Holy Roman emperors until Battle of Benevento (1266), when it passed to papacy; noted as birthplace of Frederick II.

label: Macerata
scope_note: Located on hill between Chienti & Potenza rivers; ancient town was destroyed ca. 408 CE by Visigothic king Alaric; was a thriving commune in 12th cen.; went to Papal States ca. 1445. Located near the site of ancient Ricina.

label: Senigallia
scope_note: Located on Adriatic Sea at mouth of Misa river; founded by Senonian Gauls 6th cen. BC; was noted Roman colony; part of Byzantine exarchate of Ravenna; destroyed 1264, rebuilt by S Malatesta in 1450; went to Della Rovere family, then to Papal States 1631.

label: Campobasso
scope_note: Modern town is located on a fertile plain, outside the walls of the medieval town; is noted for medieval castle & other architecture; was important as site where British & US forces joined during the Volturno campaign in WW II.

label: Alba
scope_note: Parts of the fortified gate, remains of a few buildings, and mosaics from the original Roman city remain.

label: Casale Monferrato
scope_note: Located on an upper course of the Po river in Monferrato hills. The Ligurian name of the Po river was "Bodincus," thus the ancient name of the town, "Bodincomagus." The site was settled in ancient times; the modern town was founded in the 8th century; it was ruled by the marquisate of Monferrato in the 10th century; it went to the Gonzaga family in 1536; it was disputed between France and Spain, then went to Savoy in 1707.

label: Domodossola
scope_note: Located at foot of Simplon Pass; site of countship under bishop of Novara established by Charlemagne; seized by Swiss in 1416; plundered by Upper Valais in 1487 during religious wars; went to Austria in 1714 & to Savoy in 1735; returned to Italy in 1815.

label: Ivrea
scope_note: Located on the Dora Baltea river; Romans seized town from Salassi to attain valuable gold mines here; was seat of a Lombard duchy during early Middle Ages; center of the March of Ivrea from 889; passed to Monferrato in 1266 & to House of Savoy in 1313.

label: Oria
scope_note: One of the most important Messapic cities according to Herodotos; besieged & taken by Hannibal; conquered by Goths, Byzantines, Lombards (569 CE), & by Ludovico II (867); noted for burial chambers & Greek ceramic ware.

label: Taranto
scope_note: A Greek colonial city founded in 706 BCE. Comprises old city on island and newer section on mainland. In the 8th century BCE, Greek settlers from Sparta and Laconia conquered the Messapian village of Taras on the Taras river and founded a new Taras on the peninsula (cut in 1480 by a canal) between the Mare Piccolo and the Mare Grande. Taras soon became one of the leading cities of Magna Graecia (Greek colonies in southern Italy), and its inhabitants founded several other coastal cities; fell to Romans 272 BCE; ruled by Goths, Lombards & Arabs 6th-10th cen.; part of Kingdom of Naples 16th-17th cen.; site of many Greek tombs & ruins.

label: Alghero
scope_note: Founded by Doria family of Genoa in 12th cen.; became a Catalan colony under Peter IV of Aragon in 1354; was residence of Emperor Charles V from 1541; noted as the only town in Italy where the Catalan language is still spoken; has Aragonese architecture.

label: Iglesias
scope_note: Located in center of district; famous for zinc & lead mines since 13th cen.; also noted for Franciscan architecture characteristic of Sardegna.

label: Adrano

label: Adrano

label: Centuripe
scope_note: Town of east-central Sicily, Italy, located on a ridge between the Simeto and Dittaino rivers, northwest of Catania. The ancient Centuripae was said to be a city of the Siculi (an ancient Sicilian tribe), according to the Greek historian Thucydides. It allied itself with Athens against Syracuse, and remained largely independent of Syracuse; it was taken by Rome in the First Punic War. The city apparently suffered in the Roman war against Sextus Pompeius, son of Pompey the Great, and did not regain its prosperity. Partly destroyed by Frederick II in 1233 (after which most of the inhabitants moved to Augusta), the city's ruin was completed by Charles of Anjou. It was later rebuilt by Francesco Moncada, count of Adrano.

label: Mozia
scope_note: Mozia was an ancient Punic city on the small island of San Pantaleo (also historically called Mozia) off the west coast of Sicily, north of Marsala; settled by Phoenicians from Syria during the 8th century BCE; an important commercial center until it was destroyed by Dionysius the Elder in 397 BCE.

label: Split
scope_note: Located on a peninsula on the Adriatic Sea; there is a deep, sheltered harbor on the south side.  The city was damaged by the Avars in 615. It was a port of medieval Dalmatia. It later became an important Byzantine city (from 812); also later held by Venice, Austria, and France. In 1918 it became part of Yugoslavia and in 1992 of independent Croatia. Controlled by Axis troops during WW II, most of port area was destroyed by Nazis. Best known for the ruins of the Palace of Diocletian (295-305 CE); collectively with the historic royal residences, fortifications, and churches in the city, the palace was designated a UNESCO World Heritage site in 1979.

label: 's-Gravenhage
scope_note: Originally located in woodland called Haghe ("hedge"), town grew around residence of counts of Holland. At the turn of the 19th century, it became an important conference center and headquarters for many institutions, most notably the International Court of Justice of the United Nations.

label: Jaca
scope_note: Jaca was one of the pilgrimage sites on route to the Cathedral of Santiago de Compostela, home of the shrine dedicated to Saint James, the patron saint of Spain. The symbol of Saint James, the scalloped shell, became the primary symbol representing pilgrims. Various pilgrimage routes in the autonomous communities of Aragon, Navarre, and León correspond to old Roman roads built in the northern portion of the Iberian Peninsula. Jaca during the 11th century consisted of two parts, the Burgos of San Nicolás and the Burgos Nuevo. Burgos Nuevo encouraged French people to become settlers. Historic sites in Jaca include the Cathedral of San Pedro, the Church of Santiago and Santo Domingo, the Church of San Gines, the Sarchophagus of Donä Sancha, and the Inn of the Church of the Holy Spirit.

Mérida's economy is based on agricultural trade and tourism.

label: Pamplona
scope_note: Pamplona was one of the pilgrimage sites on route to the Cathedral of Santiago de Compostela, home of the shrine dedicated to Saint James, the patron saint of Spain. The symbol of Saint James, the scalloped shell, became the primary symbol representing pilgrims. Various pilgrimage routes in the autonomous communities of Aragon, Navarre, and León correspond to old Roman roads built in the northern portion of the Iberian Peninsula.  It became the strongest fortified town of northern Spain after Philip II of Spain constructed the citadel of 1571. Pamplona is famous for the running of the bulls in the city streets during the Fiesta de San Fermín. Pamplona is located in an irrigated region that produces cereal and manufactures chemicals, liquor, and paper. Historic sites in Pamplona include the Catheral of Santa María, the Church of San Cernín, the parish Church of San Nicolás, and Hospital of San Miguel.

label: Ponferrada
scope_note: Ponferrada is one of the pilgrimage sites on route to the Cathedral of Santiago de Compostela, home of the shrine dedicated to Saint James, the patron saint of Spain. The symbol of Saint James, the scalloped shell, became the normal badge representing pilgrims. Various pilgrimage routes in the autonomous communities of Aragon, Navarre, and Castilla y León correspond to old Roman roads built in the northern portion of the Iberian Peninsula. Historically called San Pedro, Ponferrada received its current name from a bridge constructed in 1082 over the Sil River. The name Ponferrada first appeared in 1124. The Virgin de la Encina was said to have appeared at Ponferrada in 1200. The Church of San Pedro and Hospital of San Lázaro are located in Ponferrada.

Valtice's most notable buildings are the old monastery and alms-house of the monks Hospitallers, and the large Gothic Revival castle, famed for its wine cellars. label: Plzeň
scope_note: The city of Plzeň is situated in fertile Plzeň basin in Západočeský region, of which it is the capital city, in the Czech Republic. It lies along the old trade route between Prague and Bavaria, and its existence was first recorded in the 10th century. It. was chartered in 1292 and fortified by King Wenceslaus II in 1295. It served as a stronghold for the Roman Catholic Church during 1the 5th-century Hussite Wars. Though heavily damaged in World War II, it still retains many historic structures, including its medieval town square with St. Bartholomew's Church, the Franciscan Church of the Virgin Mary, and its Renaissance town hall and burger houses. The modern city is known for the long-operating Škoda Steel Works, in production since the late 19th century, producing heavy machinery, aircraft, locomotives, and cars. In addition, the city has been known for its Pilsner beer since medieval times. Its 2003 estimated population was 164,900.

label: Samarqand
scope_note: City located in east-central Uzbekistan, Samarkand dates from the 4th century BCE, when it was known as Maracanda. The city was captured by Alexander the Great in 329 BCE and was subsequently ruled by the Turks (6th century CE), the Arabs (8th century), the Samanids, and later was destroyed by Genghis Khan in 1220. By 1365, Samarkand had become part of the Timur empire, and was a flourishing city in the region. In 1500, the city was conquered by the Uzbeks, becoming part of the khanate of Bukhara. Samarkand had declined by the 17th century, becoming virtually uninhabited from ca. 1720-ca. 1780. Once the Russians had conquered the region, the city began to recover. Present-day Samarkand consists of an old city (containing many examples of 14th-20th century Central Asian architecture), and a 19th century section built by the Russians. In ancient times, the city had been on the Silk Road from India and China, and today its economy is largely agriculture-based.

label: Tashkent
scope_note: The largest city in Central Asia, Tashkent is located in the Chirchiq River valley close to the border of Kazakhstan. It dates from around the 2nd-1st centuries BCE, and has been known as Tashkent (stone village) since the 11th century CE. Because of its location along a strategic caravan route, the Arabs first conquered Tashkent in the 8th century, and later the Mongols conquered in the 13th. After Timurnid and Shaybanid rule, the city was annexed to the khanate of Kokand. By 1865, when the Russians captured the city, the population was 70,000. The Russians established the protectorate of Turkistan, and make Tashkent the capital in 1867. Turkistan was divided in 1924, and Tashkent became the capital of the new region in 1930. The city's main industry is cotton production, and it contains many institutions of higher education. Although several structures from the 15th and 16th centuries still survive, earthquake damage has caused much of the city to be rebuilt.

label: Asyūţ
scope_note: Largest settlement of Upper Egypt; was an ancient center for worship of jackal-headed god Wepwawet; was commercial center at terminus of ancient caravan routes crossing east and west deserts; was early Coptic Christian center; thrived as medieval Islamic center.

label: Hawara
scope_note: Located southeast of Birkat Qārūn (lake); site of a pyramid probably built by Amenemhet III of 12th dynasty; also site of ruins of a huge labyrinth, which was a funerary temple.

label: Al Uqşur
scope_note: With the village of Karnak, Luxor is on the site of ancient Thebes (capital of the New Kingdom). It is noted for having ruins of many temples and burial grounds. When Thebes declined, Luxor remained the more heavily populated part of the ancient city and grew into a modern market town.

label: Memphis
scope_note: The ruins of the capital of Menes, and for most rulers of Old and Middle Kingdoms until the 18th dynasty; it was superseded by Heracleopolis and later by Thebes; declined after Alexander's conquest. Site of ruins of the Great Temple of Ptah, a large necropolis and royal palaces. Adjacent to the modern city of Mīt Ruhaynah.

label: Būr Saʻīd
scope_note: Named after Khedive Muḥammad Sa'īd; world's largest coal-bunkering station, catering to Suez Canal traffic in 19th century; damaged in attacks by British and French 1956; restored after 1975; produces textiles, glass, china, watches and cosmetics.

label: Al Fayyūm
scope_note: Was an ancient center; noted for ruins dating to 12th dynasty (1991-1786 BC), & Greek & Coptic papyrus; today is center for cotton ginning & tanning.

label: Miṣr
scope_note: Area of modern Egypt comprises the core of the ancient kingdom of Egypt; area was home to Neolithic cultures by 6000 BCE; Thinite dynasty united Upper and Lower Egypt ca. 3100 BCE; important Hellenistic center; part of Roman Empire until Arab conquest in 640, then Mameluk and Ottoman; official language is Arabic, though English and French are also widely spoken.

label: Jirjā
scope_note: Located on Nile river; developed around Mara Girgis Coptic Monastery (dedicated to St. George), from which the town derived its name; also is site of Roman Catholic monastery said to be the oldest in Egypt. Possibly the site of the lost settlement of Thinis.

label: Nubia
scope_note: Area in northeastern Africa, extending from the Nile River valley in Egypt eastward to the Red Sea, and southward to Khartoum, Sudan. Nubia was subordinate to Egypt from the 20th to the 8th centuries  BCE. The Nubian kingdom of Kush dominated the area from the 8th-7th centuries BCE, then it ruled by Assyria, Ethiopia and Nobatae tribes. Much of the area was flooded with construction of Aswan High Dam in the 1960s.
